value.Name: 3V
value.Description:
3V is a student organization based upon music education and cultural appreciation. Our mission is to unify students through our shared passion for music and art, building a centralized culture that fosters creativity and music education.

3V provides a platform for student artists & creatives who desire a career in the music industry. This platform utilizes education, events, documentation, & a creative community to provide students with the tools & network that they need to succeed in the industry. Ultimately, 3V encourages our members to perfect their craft & shift the culture at UIUC. 

Vessels | We are encouraging students to embrace their creativity & allow your passion for art to become not just a hobby, but a part of your career & daily life. As a result, we are providing a platform for artists to develop their art and their brand to bridge them with opportunities in the industry.

Visions | By challenging ourselves to develop our creativity, we are creating a new vision that can help us further develop as a community, pushing one another to succeed with an understanding of what to know and how to succeed in our passions.

Vibes | Let's create a vibe that transcends negativity. 3V meetings are a space for good energy to thrive from music and art.
value.Summary: 3V is a student organization based upon music education and cultural appreciation. Our mission is to unify students through our shared passion for music and art, building a centralized culture that fosters creativity and music education.

value.Name: 8 to CREATE
value.Description:
8 to CREATE is an art event in which 8 artists have 8 hours to create 8 works of art.

The event is open to the public to observe, engage, and participate in the creative process. All artwork is temporary; no artwork is sold.  

The primary goal of 8 to CREATE is to provide an opportunity for students to gain professional art and design experience and to engage in the Champaign-Urbana community. 

Students are involved in all aspects of planning the event in order to gain practical experience. Members contribute their creative skills into real-life applications as well as learn from each other. Members also have the opportunity to network with professionals and organizations in the Champaign-Urbana community.

8 to CREATE has two secondary goals:

1) to make the typically private process of creating artwork accessible and open to the public for observation, engagement, and participation

and

2) to break down institutional and social hierarchies by bringing together a mix of artists from a variety of experiences and affiliations in one creative space.
value.Summary: 8 to CREATE is a group of art-minded students who organize public art events in which 8 artists have 8 hours to create 8 large-scale drawings. Students gain practical experience in all aspects of planning art shows.

value.Name: Acacia Fraternity
value.Description:
Acacia Fraternity was founded in 1904 at the University of Michigan in Ann Arbor. Acacia's founders established the fraternity on a unique basis.  Members were to be motivated by a desire for high scholarship and of such character that the fraternity would be free of the social vices and unbecoming activities that for years had been a blot on the fraternity life.

The Illinois (Heth) chapter of Acacia was the 8th chapter in the country, founded in 1906. We are currently the largest chapter in the nation.
value.Summary: Heth chapter of Acacia Fraternity, an international social fraternity with 33 chapters in the U.S. and Canada. Mission is Human Service.

value.Name: Academic Buzzer Team: A Quiz Bowl Organization
value.Description:
We’re the Academic Buzzer Team at the University of Illinois. We participate in tournaments of quizbowl, a competition between two teams in which players answer academic questions in categories such as the fine arts, history, literature, science, and social science.

“Regular” questions are called tossups, and they are written with many clues, with harder clues preceding easier clues in what is called pyramidal structure. This way, players with deeper knowledge of a subject can give correct answers earlier, rewarding extensive knowledge. A team that answers a tossup correctly is given a bonus, a set of (usually) three related questions that only the controlling team may answer.

If this sounds interesting to you, join us at one of our practices, Mondays and Thursdays from 5:30 to 8:00 PM in room 156 of the English Building, or feel free to send us an email.
value.Summary: We're the Academic Buzzer Team at the University of Illinois. We participate in tournaments of quizbowl, a competition between two teams in which players answer academic questions in categories such as the fine arts, history, literature, science,

value.Name: ACES without Borders
value.Description: ACES without Borders is a registered student organization affiliated with College of ACES Office of Education Abroad. The purpose of the organization is to introduce incoming College of ACES exchange students to life in America and at Illinois. ACES without Borders is run by students who have previously studied abroad through College of ACES programs, or plan to study abroad in the future. Members serve as ambassadors for the exchange students prior to their arrival as well as once they arrive on campus. They also organize cultural and social events throughout the semester to ensure that the exchange students get the most out of their study abroad experience while at Illinois. The executive board manages a Facebook page that serves as a tool for opening the lines of communication among all students in the group. Students have the additional opportunity to become involved within the International Association of students in Agricultural and related Sciences World Organization (IAAS). IAAS is one of the leading agricultural student associations that collaborates over with over 40 countries to facilitate the exchange of knowledge, information, and ideas among students, and to improve the mutual understanding between countries and cultures through seminars, working camps, international meetings, exchange weeks, an international exchange program, small-scale development projects, etc.

Our mission is to increase undergraduate business students' understanding of the connection between environmental issues and their business area of interest. This connecti...on is formed through our conferences, workshops, speakers, mentors, and curriculum development.

Our vision is to empower undergraduate business students to make business decision that will positively impact the environment. We want future global business leaders to be quipped with a sound knowledge and commitment to environmentalism and stewardship.

ActGreen is the catalyst in educating and empowering the future leaders of global business on the importance of environmentalism, sustainability, energy efficiency, and stewardship.

value.Name: Active Minds
value.Description:
About Active Minds

Our school’s chapter is part of a national organization called Active Minds, Inc. that has hundreds of chapters on campuses across the United States and Canada. We are changing the conversation about mental health on college campuses to create more open environments for students to seek help when they need it. We are here as students to educate our peers about mental health and mental health disorders to fight the stigma associated with this issue.

Our campus will be happier and healthier when we have an open dialogue around issues of mental health, so please join us in making that happen! Anyone can get involved with our chapter – you do not have to be a psychology major or have a mental health disorder to join this cause.

For more information, please contact us or visit the links below.

value.Name: Alpha Chi Sigma
value.Description:
Alpha Chi Sigma is a unique professional and social fraternity for men and women in the chemical sciences.

The three objects of Alpha Chi Sigma
1. To bind its members with a tie of true and lasting friendship.
2. To strive for the advancement of chemistry, both as a science and as a profession.
3. To aid its members by every honorable means in the attainment of their ambitions as chemists throughout their mortal lives.

What We Do
Professional
Being a unique professional fraternity with close ties to the school of chemical sciences, we are able to host many professional activities. Some of these include:

  • Hosting the annual Krug Lecture
  • Arranging faculty chats and luncheons
  • Teaching boy-scouts Chemistry to attain their Chemistry Merit Badge
  • Performing chemistry demo shows for local youth

Social
In addition to the many professional events, members share the benefit of attending the many social events. Past events have included:

  • Intramural Sports
  • Semi-formal
  • Barn-Dances
  • Chapter Dinners


Why should I join?
There is no other fraternity quite like Alpha Chi Sigma. Ask any one of our active members and they will probably say that joining AXE was one of the best decisions they’ve made in university. Many people join for the benefit their resume receives from our many professional events that we hold, while others do it for the social interaction with collegues in their field of study. The fraternal bonds that you make by joining are sure to last a lifetime.

Our History
The Zeta Chapter of Alpha Chi Sigma is located at the University of Illinois, Urbana-Champaign. We were founded on May 27, 1908, and have initiated more than 2750 men and women. Our educational backgrounds are primarily rooted in the chemical sciences, but we are also open to other majors.
value.Summary: Alpha Chi Sigma is a unique professional and social fraternity for men and women in the chemical sciences.

value.Name: Alpha Iota Omicron
value.Description: Alpha Iota Omicron (AIO) is a fraternity dedicated to providing males the means for success in a changing global society. Established on October 16, 1998, at the University of Michigan, AIO was the vision of a group of eighteen motivated young men who came together to begin brainstorming the foundation and ideals of a South Asian interest fraternity. This resulted in the development of the four fundamental principles of AIO: Brotherhood, Networking, Promoting South Asian Culture, and Community Service. Since its founding in 1998, Alpha Iota Omicron Fraternity has grown to become a National fraternity with chapters across the Midwest, and is the first South Asian interest Fraternity in the Midwest.

value.Name: Alpha Pi Sigma Sorority Inc. - Xi Chapter
value.Description:
Alpha Pi Sigma Sorority, Inc. was founded on March 10, 1990 at San Diego State University.
Latina women from a variety of backgrounds came together to form an organization that would unite and support women on each campus. The women of Alpha Pi Sigma pride ourselves in holding their education in highest regard.
We believe that campus involvement, academics, leadership, and community service are methods to achieve success at the University level. Other objectives of the Sorority include promoting members academically, personally, and professionally.
Although Alpha Pi Sigma identifies itself as a Latina based sorority, it does not discriminate against any ethnic group.
We believe in having diversity among our sisters or different ideas and viewpoints which is the key on becoming better women and building a stronger bond together. We welcome all women that are interested in the Alpha Pi Sigma experience.
A central tenet of Alpha Pi Sigma is promoting unity amongst women interested in the Latino culture.
value.Summary: In addition to its purpose of helping the Latino community, Alpha Pi Sigma works continuously with other organizations to improve the educational and community value, through its members academically, personally and professionally.

value.Name: Alpha Psi Lambda
value.Description:
Established in 1985 at Ohio State University, Alpha Psi Lambda is the Nation's Largest and Oldest Co-Ed Latino Fraternity. In May of 1988, Alpha Psi Lambda at Beta Chapter became Illinois' first Greek Letter Organization with a Latino Focus. The 8 purposes of Alpha Psi Lambda are:

  1. To serve the university campus and community.
  2. To bring forth on a scholastic level, Latinos and others at the university on the basis of friendship.
  3. To provide a supplementary educational, social, and cultural experience for the mutual cultivation of its members.
  4. To advocate for the needs and concerns of the Latino students.
  5. To promote a basis for the diversity of the Latino cultures.
  6. To enhance the educational experience through social and cultural activities, and to assist in the development of members' leadership abilities.
  7. To promote inter-Fraternity relations.
  8. To foster positive relations between the Greek system, University/College administration, and the outside community.
value.Summary: Established in 1985 at Ohio State University, Alpha Psi Lambda is the Nation's First and Largest Co-Ed Latino Fraternity. In May of 1988, Alpha Psi Lambda at Beta Chapter became Illinois' first Greek Letter Organization with a Latino Focus.

value.Name: Alternative Seasonal Breaks
value.Description:
Alternative Seasonal Breaks (ASB) is a student-run, non-profit service organization at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign (UIUC).  Despite the organization’s name, ASB sends U of I students on nationwide service trips four times throughout the year. Annually, ASB sends about 30 trips consisting of 14 students per trip. During their fall, winter, spring, and summer breaks, ASB participants travel across the country to learn about and actively combat social justice and environmental issues.

Since the inception of UIUC’s ASB chapter in 1989, thousands of University of Illinois students have positively impacted communities in the nation. Trips concern issues such as homelessness and poverty, childhood illiteracy, healthcare, environment, and many more. 

ASB’s mission is to educate students about social, political, and environmental issues through direct service, group reflections, student leadership, diversity, and engagement beyond the local community.
value.Summary: ASB sends students on volunteer road trips across the country during UIUC Winter and Spring breaks. We are 100% student-run and offer leadership positions. We've got a trip for everyone: animals, environment, education, immigration reform, and more!

value.Name: Altgeld Ringers
value.Description:
Background

For the past 70 years, chimesmasters and students have been voluntarily providing music to the campus. Chimesmasters are typically community members who are experienced musicians. Students are, well, students. They come from many different backgrounds.

In the past, students first become involved by simply by visiting the chimes tower, expressing interest in playing before practicing, and then performing. Most of them, from the day they first start to perform, continue to perform until the day they graduate. While this casual membership has yielded us some pretty great chimesplayers, it doesn’t help promote the what we do to the majority of campus who don't know about it.

Mission

This RSO, which is the first formal record of chimesplayers, is meant to help us inform the public of what we do and give people the opportunity to join us. The exact schedule for performances will be determined when we have a better idea of how many people are interested.

How to Join

If you would like to stay up to date with our special events, such as "jukebox" days and holiday concerts, send an email to altgeldringers@gmail.com stating that you want to receive periodic messages about these events.

 

At this time time, due to the closure of the tower for repair and maintanence, we are not recruiting new chimesplayers. If you are interested in becoming a chimesplayer once the tower reopens, send us an email at altgeldringers@gmail.com that briefly explains your interest in the tower and whether you have experience in playing music. Please note that you need to know or be willing to learn how to read music on a staff to be a chimesplayer.
value.Summary: We are students, faculty, and staff who are dedicated to performing music and hosting tours at the Altgeld Chimes Tower. Our songs reflect both university tradition and diversity. We welcome the campus community to join us in performance and events!

value.Name: American Advertising Federation at the University of Illinois
value.Description:
The American Advertising Federation at the University of Illinois is the nation’s premier student advertising club. Students in AAF Illinois are a part of a national professional organization headquartered in Washington D.C. Boasting itself as “The Unifying Voice for Advertising,” the American Advertising Federation is the glue that binds advertisers, agencies, media companies, local clubs and student groups across the nation. AAF provides students with remarkable opportunities to connect with professionals in the industry.

AAF Illinois is the largest of the 226 student chapters of the American Advertising Federation. Our students gain valuable experience through professional development activities, industry presentations, networking events, award programs, social events, philanthropic causes, and career conferences. We participate annually in the National Student Advertising Competition (NSAC) where students create and pitch a new campaign to a real client.

Most importantly, AAF is an organization that connects students with similar interests. We’re the type of people that like tossing ideas back and forth. Advertising is a collaborative business, and no matter what your interest or specialty, other AAF students will complement and contribute to your development. AAF Illinois provides an unmatched opportunity to immerse yourself in the advertising and communications industry.
value.Summary: A nationally accredited organization for students interested in the fields of advertising, marketing, public relations and communications.

value.Description: The American Association of Zoo Veterinarians, Illinois Student Chapter (AKA "The Non-Traditional Species Club") aims to provide veterinary students with additional educational opportunities and experience in the veterinary care of zoo and exotic animals. The executive board is made up of five branches: AAZV (American Association of Zoo Veterinarians), AAV (Association of Avian Veterinarians), ARAV (Association of Reptile and Amphibian Veterinarians), AEMV (Association of Exotic Mammal Veterinarians), and Aquatics (IAAAM- International Association of Aquatic Animal Medicine). The executive board plans events that cover a variety of topics involving exotic mammals, aquatics, avian species, reptiles, and zoo animals.

Outreach

value.ShortName: AFS, U of I Student Subunit
value.Description:
The mission of AFS, UIUC subunit is "to improve the conservation and sustainability of fishery resources and aquatic ecosystems by advancing fisheries and aquatic science and promoting the development of fisheries professionals.

       AFS is an organization open to undergraduate, graduate, and doctoral students, as well as faculty and professionals alike who share an interest or seek to gain experience in fisheries or aquatic sciences. The objectives of the UIUC student sub chapter are: 1) to seek and assemble those interested in fisheries science, conservation, and activities; 2) provide field experience to those seeking a profession in the field or those who enjoy being on the water; 3) educate and provide connections to professionals through monthly meetings featuring guest speakers; 4) aid our community by providing a childrens fishing clinic and other philanthropic events.  

 

Contact: Jared Wilson at jcwilso3@illinois.edu with any questions or to be added to the AFS listserv.

value.Name: American Medical Women's Association at UIUC
value.Description: The American Medical Women’s Association is a national organization open to any woman interested in or part of the medical field. The members of the AMWA national branch at UIUC are required to become members of the national organization. This membership provides numerous benefits, including but not limited to physician mentorship opportunities and discounts on Kaplan test preparation. American Medical Women's Association is comprised of physicians, residents, medical students, undergraduate students, and health care professionals.  AMWA is the only multispecialty organization dedicated to advancing women in medicine and improving women's health. The American Medical Women's Association empowers women to lead in improving health for all within a model that reflects the unique perspective of women. It functions at the local, national, and international level to advance women in medicine and improve women's health.  They achieve this by providing and developing leadership, advocacy, education, expertise, mentoring, and strategic alliances. The AMWA chapter at UIUC aspires to promote advancement in the medical field for women, help them find opportunities (volunteer, research, etc.), educate other women regarding the scope of the medical field, and prepare them for admission into graduate school (medical school, physician assistant school, dental school, etc.).
value.Summary: The American Medical Women’s Association is a national organization open to women interested in/part of the medical field. The goal of this organization is to promote advancement and provide preparation resources for women pursuing healthcare careers.

value.Description: The UIUC Student Chapter of ANS aims to provide to students interested in nuclear topics opportunities to further themselves professionally through the international ANS network of scientists, engineers, and other nuclear specialists. To further expand our members’ familiarity with the nuclear field, it is important to us that we regularly provide them with opportunities to tour power plants, national labs, and any nuclear-related facilities that are able to provide to interesting and educational real-life experiences.
value.Summary: The UIUC Student Chapter of ANS aims to provide to students interested in nuclear topics opportunities to further themselves professionally through the ANS network, and for them to become and act as educated advocates for the nuclear field to the public.

value.Name: American Red Cross Club at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign
value.Description:
The American Red Cross Club @ UIUC (ARCCUIUC) is governed under the 7 Fundamental Principles of the American Red Cross and addresses 4 of the 5 Areas of Service of the American Red Cross.

If you are interested in joining the American Red Cross club, If you have any additional questions or would like to join our mailing list please contact us at arccuiuc@gmail.com 

 

The 7 Principles:

  1. Humanity
  2. Impartiality
  3. Neutrality
  4. Independence
  5. Voluntary Service
  6. Unity
  7. Universality

The ARCCUIUC 4 Areas of Service:

  1. Service to the Armed Forces
  2. Blood Services
  3. Preparedness, Health & Service
  4. Disaster Response

Members have access to free CPR classes, volunteer opportunites, and leadership opportunities!
value.Summary: The Red Cross club works closely with the American Red Cross Heartland chapter and other community service organizations to advertise and manage regular blood drives, fund raise for Red Cross aid efforts, and assist in local service work however possible

value.Description:
The goal of the American Sign Language and Deaf Culture Club is to promote awareness and exposition of the language and culture of Deaf Americans to the University of Illinois community. American Sign Language is a non-Indo-European language that uses a visual and expressive mode of communication instead of spoken word. Organizational members will have the opportunity to learn basic communicative skills in sign language and will be encourage to continue their involvement in the Deaf community and fluency in American Sign Language. Lastly, students will have the opportunity to partake in outreach and engagement with the University of Illinois and Champaign-Urbana community.

For Fall 2017, our meetings are every other Monday at 7pm in Lincoln Hall 1066 beginning 9/18

value.Name: Analytics in Business
value.Description:
Goal:

1) Learn latest analytics software, best practices and technologies to collaboratively build your skill-set

2) Participate in talks, guest lectures, workshops, networking events and company visits

3) Get access to recruiters and opportunities

Prerequisites: None Concentration: Operations, Finance, Technology, Marketing, HR, Strategy and others Background: Analytics is the science of identifying meaningful patterns and trends in past data. It is a combination of statistics, computer programming and mathematics to collect, prepare, analyze and report data. Historically, analytics tools required advanced skills and knowledge in statistics and mathematics. However, upon the advent of information technology, these complex set of rules can be integrated into a programming language to automatically run regressions to analyze data. Big Data and Hadoop are a couple of the major technologies used to load, store and analyze unstructured data by establishing meaningful correlations between parameters.
value.Summary: The Analytics in Business Club is focused in equipping business students with the knowledge, skills and exposure to Analytics. We are also focused in utilizing the resources currently available  in the University to maximize our learning.

value.Name: Anthropology Club/Lambda Alpha
value.Description:
As of March 2013, the newly established Mu of Illinois chapter of Lambda Alpha National Collegiate Anthropology Honors Society has 38 official members. Upon launching our new chapter, it was agreed by students and faculty that a unification between the pre-existing Anthropology Club and the new Lambda Alpha chapter would be in the best interest of students and would allow for a closer community of anthropology students to grow.

It is the mission of the UIUC Anthropology Club/Lambda Alpha to create a community in which anthropology students can come together in order to share their passion for anthropos (“humanity” in Greek!) through linguistic, sociocultural, biological, and archaeological influences.  We promise to offer students social activities through the Anthropology Club as well as academic opportunities through Lambda Alpha National Collegiate Anthropology Honors Society in order to aid students through their growth and development as anthropologists.
value.Summary: We are a group of fun, friendly, dedicated students who love Anthropology!  We offer academic guidance and opportunities, form professional networks and organize social events to enrich the experience of students interested in Anthropology.

value.Summary: Our goal for the 2017-2018 year is to build lasting relationships among officers, members, and alumni throughout their college career and beyond by providing an open environment for personal growth and discover the meaning of the Asian American identity.

value.Name: Asian American Law Students Association
value.Description: To promote the professional goals of law students and to provide social, personal, and cultural support for its members and to promote Asian culture and career opportunities.
value.Summary: To promote the professional goals of law students and to provide social, personal, and cultural support for its members and to promote Asian culture and career opportunities.

value.Name: Asian American Student Housing Organization
value.Description:
The Asian American Student Housing Organization (AASHO) is a central housing organization that is affiliated with University Housing. It strives to promote the exploration of Asian culture, and to strengthen the Asian and Asian American community, particularly within the residence halls.

AASHO strives to provide and foster both an educational and social environment for students, in order to make an impact in the Asian American community as well as the Housing community. There are a variety of social, cultural, and leadership development events held throughout the year, which are open to everyone. Some events we have hosted include a Mid-Autumn Festival celebration, Asian House of Pancakes (AHOP), Lunar New Year celebration, resume critique workshops, DIY magnet events, and more. One of our greatest achievements was starting the specialty restaurant, Taste of Asia, to the Illinois Street Residence Hall (ISR) on Wednesdays.
value.Summary: We strive to promote the exploration of Asian culture, and to strengthen the Asian and Asian American community, particularly within the residence halls.

value.Name: Asian Illini Sports Organization
value.Summary: AISO is a sports and recreation organization intended to bring the Asian community at UIUC together.

value.Name: Asian Leaders and Professionals in Healthcare Alliance
value.Summary: Empowering Asian Americans to fight against discrimination, prejudice, and stereotypes,  while developing professionalism and leadership qualities in order to foster camaraderie within and outside the Asian healthcare professional

value.Name: Association for Computing Machinery
value.Description: To form a scientific and educational organization dedicated to advancing the arts, sciences, and applications of information technology.
value.Summary: To form a scientific and educational organization dedicated to advancing the arts, sciences, and applications of information technology.

value.Name: Association for Information Systems
value.Description:
The Association for Information Systems (AIS) is an international professional organization serving as the premier global organization for academics specializing in Information Systems.  Its mission is to progress knowledge in the use of IT to improve organizational performance and individual quality of work life.

AIS Illinois has 58 general members and seven Executive Board members this semester.  We are open to students of any major, though the majority of our members hail from the College of Business.  Majors represented include Information Systems/Information Technology, Supply Chain Management, Business Process Management, Marketing, Finance, Accounting, Economics, Statistics, and many more.
value.Summary: AIS is the premier organization focusing on IS/IT. Its goal is to provide members with technology skills, corporate & alumni networking opportunities, and professional development to set them apart in interviews and prepare for a successful career.

value.Name: Association for the Professional Development of Community-oriented Students
value.Description: The Association for the Professional Development of Community Students (APDoCS) seeks to promote and advance the professional development and advancement of students with interests in community research and action. This organization emphasizes a multileveled approach to contemporary social problems with an orientation toward issues of diversity and representation.
value.Summary: The Association for the Professional Development of Community Students (APDoCS) seeks to promote and advance the professional development and advancement of students with interests in community research and action. This organization emphasizes a

value.Name: Association for Women in Mathematics at UIUC
value.Description: Association for Women in Mathematics encourages women and girls to pursue and have active careers in the mathematical sciences. We promote equal opportunity and equal treatment regardless of the background, age, and gender. We provide horizontal fellowship (friendship among peers) and vertical fellowship (friendship and support across faculty, graduate students, and undergraduate students). All men and women are equally invited to join and participate in all of our events.
value.Summary: Association for Women in Mathematics encourages women and girls to pursue and have active careers in the mathematical sciences. We promote equal opportunity and equal treatment regardless of the background, age, and gender.

value.Name: Association of Data Science and Analytics
value.Description: ADSA is focused on creating a community where people interested in data science, data analytics, and big data can come together and learn about the field from each other and from corporations, professors, and industry/subject matter experts. We also want to help lower the barrier of entry to this extremely challenging field by providing easy to access resources and education. The university has a huge big data initiative but no student group to head it. This is the fastest growing CS field and we can provide the value of data science, data analytics, and big data to not only the CS/ECE dept, but also to the rest of campus.
value.Summary: The Association of Data Science and Analytics focuses on bringing the value of data science and analytics to UIUC. We aim to provide resources, education, and opportunities in these fields to lower the barrier of entry to those interested.

value.Name: Association of Food Technologists
value.Description:
Association of Food Technologists is an organization made to help food science students in all aspects of their college career. Our club objectives are:

To foster a close relationship among the Department of Food Science and Human Nutrition students and faculty at the Univerisity of Illinois Urbana-Champaign. 

To present leadership opportunities to Food Science and Human Nutrition students.

To make a connection between Food Science and Human Nutrition students and the food industry through guest speakers, company tours and internship opportunities.

We hold monthly meetings the first Tuesday of every month located in the Bevier Commons. Each meeting features a guest speaker or an activity.
value.Summary: Association of Food Technologists is an organization made to help food science students in all aspects of their college career.  We strive to connect students with faculty, leadership opportunities, and industry contacts.

value.Name: Association of Minorities in Political Science
value.Description: The Association of Minorities in Political Science at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign aims to provide students with professional development, mentoring, and leadership training in order to address issues of under representation within the field of political science and in government. We seek to build our country’s future leaders by promoting public service, and empowering students to pursue careers that will allow them to make the most of their education in political science, and give back to their communities.
value.Summary: Through public service, networking events and cultural recognition we hope to create a community in which those who are under represented can thrive and become the future leaders in the field of political science and government.

value.Name: Assyrian Student Association at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign
value.Description:
ASA is a chapter of the Assyrian Student Association of Chicago (ASAC) and we believe we are the generation of change. ASA-UIUC is a student organization that aims to promote the advancement of the Assyrian heritage. We also aim to promote the improvement of Assyrian-American students through higher education, appreciation for Assyrian culture, unity and support for the Assyrian community and to raise awareness of human rights issues. We believe we must positively impact our community by uniting to work towards one common goal; to preserve our heritage, culture, language, and traditions. We seek to accomplish these goals by basing our organization into 4 groups; education, culture, social, and humanitarian.

The Education committee will provide necessary tools and resources to help Assyrian students pursue and succeed in their academic careers while educating our generation on Assyrian heritage.

The Humanitarian committee will give back to the Assyrian community by providing aid, resources, and a helping hand for Assyrian immigrants.

The Culture committee will educate, promote and preserve the Assyrian heritage-focusing on the traditions, the history of the culture, the language, the food and dance.

The Social committee will hold formal and informal social gatherings to build friendships and networks within the Assyrian community locally and worldwide. 

All in all, we hope to provide Assyrian-American students at the UIUC an organization filled with opportunities to advance their educational experiences as well as an opportunity to play a crucial role in the preservation of the Assyrian heritage.
value.Summary: We are a student organization aiming to preserve and advance the Assyrian culture. Our mission is to promote the advancement of Assyrian-American youth and to unify and provide support for Assyrian-American students on campus.

value.Name: Astronomical Society at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign
value.Description:
UIAS is centered around a love of the sky we see and the universe of which we are a part. We are an organization of University students and employees who want to get the most out of the wonders of astronomy.

At meetings we'll often have a speaker - a club member might talk about astronomical imaging or telescope making, or a faculty astronomer might tell us about their current research. Sometimes we'll hold meetings under the stars and learn the constellations. Or we'll plan special events, such as observing at our dark site, camping at Walnut Point State Park, visiting Parkland College's Staerkel Planetarium, or even taking a trip to Adler Planetarium in Chicago or Yerkes Observatory in Wisconsin.

As a member, you can be trained on using the Observatory, then borrow keys from the department and use it overnight.

The club also has several Dobsonian telescopes with 8" to 12" apertures. We use them on campus and at our dark site.

Membership dues are $10 per year.
value.Summary: To interest and educate students, faculty, staff, and the community about the wonders of astronomy.

value.Name: Atius-Sachem Leadership Honorary
value.Description: Atius and Sachem are leadership honor societies comprised of highly motivated individuals dedicated to the development of our campus leadership.  Our strength is generated from our commitment of excellence to our university, our community, and each other.  Atius-Sachem serves as a campus model of excellence in our approach, our product, and our results.  We seek to foster personal growth, scholarship, and philanthropy in each other and our commitments, including the Illibuck Pass and annual Mom's Day Sing.
value.Summary: Atius and Sachem are leadership honor societies comprised of highly motivated individuals dedicated to the development of our campus leadership. Our strength is generated from our commitment of excellence to our university, our community, and each other.

value.Name: Attitutors
value.Summary: We are tutors with a welcoming attitude for international students with academic and college-life concerns. Our mission is to match students in need of tutoring help with experienced peers who speak their native language.

value.Name: Autism Speaks
value.Summary: At Autism Speaks, we are enhancing lives today and accelerating a spectrum of solutions tomorrow. We are dedicated to promoting solutions for the needs of individuals with Autism and their families. We do this through advocacy and support.

value.Name: Auto Club
value.Description: We will organize some picnics and meetings during every semester. All members in this organization will learn the basic information and knowledges of their cars.
value.Summary: Auto Club provides communication platform for all students who want to talk about their cars problems. They will learn huge information from the communication and make more friends.

value.Name: Automata Robotics
value.Description:
Our vision: to create a strong community of student leaders in robotics.

Our mission: to educate students about modern robotics research, mechanical design, computer aided design (CAD), 3D-printing, assembly, electronic components, coding, and testing as well as foster skills in entrepreneurship and effective communication. We will compete in the Cozad Competition and EOH.
value.Summary: We build robots inspired by cutting-edge research with an emphasis on entrepreneurship and competition.

value.Name: Automated Trading Systems Club
value.Summary: We are a group of students working to create an automated trading system by using knowledge in stock ratios and trends as well as computer science algorithms to track the ebb and flows of the market and predict future stock values.

value.Name: Aviation at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign
value.Summary: We are a group of aviation enthusiasts of all levels (student pilot to professional pilot) interested in creating a community for ourselves and reaching out to promote aviation to those who are interested or those who never thought they could fly.

value.Name: Avicenna Community Health Center-Student Initiative
value.Description:
Avicenna Community Health Center is a medical clinic in Champaign, IL that aims  to assist the medical needs of Urbana-Champaign community, particularly those who are uninsured and under-insured. Inspired by this mission and the desire to embody the spirit of community activism in Islam, Avicenna Community Health Center aims to be just that, a health center for the community. We aim to provide healthcare to those in our community who do not have access to it. Our three main objectives are:

  • To provide healthcare for the uninsured and underinsured
  • To engage in preventive healthcare through community health screenings
  • To promote health awareness through education and information dissemination

 

In order to fulfill these goals, Avicenna needs the help of the community at large by connecting with students and by providing volunteering opportunities and other ways of getting involved.
value.Summary: Avicenna Community Health Center is a free clinic in Champaign, IL that provides primary care to people without insurance. ACHC-SI supports the clinic and connects the students of UIUC to the clinic.

value.Name: AVS Illinois Student Chapter
value.Description: For those interested in materials science, surface science, materials processing, electronic materials, and vacuum science.
value.Summary: For those interested in materials science, surface science, materials processing, electronic materials, and vacuum science.

value.Name: Axiom
value.Description:
Axiom is a Christian ministry on campus that seeks to meet the needs of our campus, and provide a place for students to learn, serve, develop relationships, and build leadership skills, all while deepening their love for, and faith in, Jesus Christ.

An axiom is an accepted, established, and self-evident truth. Thus, we stand for, and are striving to be a representative of, the only real Truth: Jesus Christ.

Our large group is Sunday nights at 7PM at Axiom House on the corner of Lincoln and Oregon - all are welcome!

And they devoted themselves to the apostles' teaching and fellowship, to the breaking of bread and the prayers. And awe came upon every soul... Acts 2:42-43
value.Summary: Axiom is a Christian ministry on campus that seeks to meet needs and provide a place for students to learn, serve, develop relationships, and build leadership skills, all while deepening their love for, and faith in, Jesus Christ.

value.Name: Badminton For Fun
value.Description: Our purpose is to welcome all students, staff and faculty that share a passion for badminton and a simple desire to have fun. No tryout necessary, beginners are welcome. Check us out and meet new people while sharpening some mad badminton skills!
value.Summary: Our purpose is to welcome all students, staff and faculty that share a passion for badminton and a simple desire to have fun. No tryout necessary, beginners are welcome. Check us out and meet new people while sharpening some mad badminton skills!

value.Name: Ballet Folklorico Mitotiani
value.Description: Ballet Folklorico Mitotiani is an organization focusing on the cultural aspect of Mexico. Ballet Folklorico has been a long tradition of dancing depending on the different regions of Mexico. The dances include colorful dresses that stem mainly from Jalisco, Nuevo León, Veracruz, Michoacán, Nayarit, Guerrero, Yucatán, San Luis Potosi, and Puebla. Each region developing a different, yet similar style of dancing. For these dances to be heard, heels for women and boots for men have nails on the tip and the heel. This requires a vast range of dancing techniques that we are prepared to show you. Although these physical logistics are important to know, Ballet Folklorico is a cultural enhancement to this campus, bringing lively color to many events that promote Latinx culture. Our mission is to increase a deeper understanding and connection to Latinx culture on campus and demonstrate the broad variety of regions that Mexico has to offer.
value.Summary: Ballet Folklorico is a cultural enhancement to this campus, bringing lively color to many events that promote Latinx culture. Our mission is to increase a deeper understanding and connection to Latinx culture on campus.

value.Name: Bangladeshi Students Association
value.Description: To promote Bangladeshi culture, traditions, and heritage to UIUC people as well as to the International community.
value.Summary: To promote Bangladeshi culture, traditions, and heritage to UIUC people as well as to the International community.

value.Name: Bankruptcy Law Society
value.Summary: An organization dedicated to the study of the Bankruptcy Code and its interrelation with businesses and individuals.

value.Name: Baptist Campus Ministries
value.Description: The BCM is a student group aimed to provide fellowship and service opportunities for Christians on campus.  We coordinate with the University Baptist Church to connect undergrads, grads, and professionals through Bible study, worship, and service.
value.Summary: The BCM is a student group aimed to provide fellowship and service opportunities for Christians on campus.  We coordinate with the University Baptist Church to connect undergrads, grads, and professionals through Bible study, worship, and service.

value.Name: Barkada
value.Description: In Tagalog, Barkada means "close knit group of friends."
value.Summary: To foster relationships and promote the learning of Filipino culture through cultural dancing.

value.Name: Be The Match on Campus
value.Description: Be the Match on Campus (BTMOC) is a Registered Student Organization at the University of Illinois. Our mission is to spread awareness regarding issues of bone marrow transplant and supporting the Be The Match registry through recruiting more willing donors and also fundraising to offset the costs to add those donors to the registry. Every year, thousands of people of all ages are diagnosed with blood cancers like leukemia or lymphoma, sickle cell anemia or other life-threatening diseases. Many of them will die unless they get a bone marrow or cord blood transplant from a matching donor. You could be the donor they are waiting for. BTMOC plans on hosting educational events to the U of I campus and throughout Champaign-Urbana to educate potential donors what a marrow donation entails and why more registry members are needed. Through events like these, we hope to recruit new, dedicated registry members and give patients hope for A Better ToMarrow.
value.Summary: You have the power to cure blood cancer. It’s in your DNA. Ask Be the Match on Campus on how to get started at the University of Illinois campus or go to www.bethematch.org to learn more!

value.Name: Beekeeping Club at UIUC
value.Summary: The Beekeeping Club is a new RSO that is working to keep bees at the Sustainable Student Farm. Join us at our meetings to talk about bee conservation, eat honey foods, and have fun. Even if you aren't into beekeeping we will have an activity for you!

value.Name: Bellydance UIUC
value.Description: Bellydance of all kinds! If you want to learn or practice with us or even perform, join us!
value.Summary: We are an organization to bring people together in order to teach and practice bellydancing in a relaxed, friendly atmosphere. We welcome dancers of all levels and backgrounds and enjoy sharing our knowledge of different types of bellydance.

value.Name: Bengali Students Association (UIUC)
value.Summary: Abol Tabol is a Bengali cultural organization at University of Illinois, Urbana-Champaign, which invites all students, scholars and faculty of the university in celebrating the bengali culture through food, adda and cultural events

value.Name: Beta Alpha Psi
value.Description:
Beta Alpha Psi is an honorary organization for Financial Information students and professionals. The primary objective of Beta Alpha Psi is to encourage and give recognition to scholastic and professional excellence in the business information fields. This includes promoting the study and practice of accounting, finance and information systems; providing opportunities for self-development, service and association among members and practicing professionals, and encouraging a sense of ethical, social, and public responsibility. 

We provide networking opportunities with the Big 4 and mid-sized accounting firms, investment banks, consulting companies and many other industry companies. With our internal development team, we provide one-on-one mentorship throughout the semester as well as develop close relationships through our Family system.
value.Summary: Beta Alpha Psi is a business honors society for Financial Information students and professionals. Our primary objective is to encourage and give recognition to scholastic and professional excellence in the areas of Accountancy, Finance and ISIT.

value.Name: Beta Psi Omega
value.Description:
Beta Psi Omega aims to provide a supportive brotherhood for students pursuing the biological sciences to further the advancement of biology as a science and profession. We are committed to serving the needs of students and thereby the community. Beta Psi Omega is aimed to connect passionate students with opportunities, insights, and guidance to success. We were founded on Five Pillars of Excellence: Intellect, Service, Unity, Diversity, and Proactivity.

Our members have the benefit of having access to class resources, organic chemistry tutoring, exposure to labs on campus, professional development workshops, volunteer experiences, and an exceptional support system. We welcome all majors to get involved (biology, kinesiology, public health, psychology, pre-health, etc.) as the skill one will gain are transferable to any field.
value.Summary: Beta Psi Omega is a co-ed professional fraternity that aims to provide a supportive brotherhood for students pursuing the biological sciences to further the advancement of biology as a science and profession.

value.Name: Beta Sigma Psi
value.Description: Beta Sigma Psi is the national Lutheran fraternity, whose purpose is to provide an environment in which the Christian college man can grow spiritually, scholastically, and socially.
value.Summary: Beta Sigma Psi is the national Lutheran fraternity, whose purpose is to provide an environment in which the Christian college man can grow spiritually, scholastically, and socially.

value.Name: Beta Theta Pi Fraternity
value.Description: Beta Theta Pi was founded at Miami University in 1839, and it has existed at the University of Illinois as the Sigma Rho chapter since 1902. Beta has had a rich history of promoting the academic endeavors, leadership skills, and social interactions of over 200,000 alums. Beta has been recognized for its Men of Principle Initiative, which produced Beta’s award-winning leadership development programs, Men of Principle Scholarship, and fostered a renewed connection with the Fraternity’s founding principles. Beta boasts numerous famous alumni, including Wal-Mart founder Sam Walton, Nike co-founder Bill Bowerman, and NCAA’s most decorated coach John Wooden. The Illinois chapter also boasts entrepreneur Shahid Khan as one of its proud alumni.
value.Summary: Our mission is to develop men of principle for a principled life.

value.Name: Bhakti Yoga Club
value.Description: Through regular meetings, invited speakers, discussions, and cultural presentations on Bhakti Yoga we wish to provide an open, soothing, and enriching environment to escape from the stress and anxiety of today's world. Rooted in Vedic teachings, BYC's activities revolve around looking at the world from a different perspective, thus helping youth become effective managers of their own lives and powerful leaders in society. We model our events in a way that they are both reposeful and enriching for participants.
value.Summary: Bhakti Yoga Club aims to create a culture of holistic well-being, cultivating progressive habits, expanding our knowledge base, and deepening our relationships with each other. Our events include discussions, cultural presentations & talks by guests.

value.Name: Big Brother Big Sister at UIUC
value.Description: The Big Brothers Big Sister's mission is to help children reach their potential through professionally supported, one-to-one mentoring relationships.
value.Summary: The Big Brothers Big Sister/s mission is to help children reach their potential through professionally supported, one-to-one mentoring relationships.

value.Name: Biomedical Engineering Society
value.Description: As the full service professional society for Biomedical Engineering and Bioengineering, our goal is “to promote the increase of biomedical engineering knowledge and its utilization.” Student memberships in BMES have many opportunities to learn about engineering and to meet fellow students with similar interests, including presentations on current information in research topics, academic programs, and career options; bioengineering projects for Engineering Open House; and numerous volunteer/outreach opportunities as well as social events.
value.Summary: To promote the increase of biomedical engineering knowledge and its utilization.

value.Name: Bioscience Journal Club
value.Description: Bioscience Journal Club is an open, welcoming place for undergraduate students to review scientific research papers. Members will collaboratively interpret papers from a variety of biological fields while practicing presentation, reasoning, and critical thinking skills. The club hopes to bring together academically driven students interested in staying up to date on new technologies and discoveries. Members will have the opportunity to choose the club's topics and papers.
value.Summary: A place for undergraduate students to rationally and logically discuss current biological research.

value.Name: Black Chorus at the University of Illinois
value.ShortName: Black Chorus at the University of Illinois
value.Description: To promote the awareness and appreciation of african-american culture through musical and artistic performance, including the genres of spirituals, anthems, rhythm and blues, as well as comtemporary and traditional gospel.
value.Summary: To promote the awareness and appreciation of African-American culture through musical and artistic performance, including the genres of spirituals, anthems, rhythm and blues, as well as contemporary and traditional gospel.

value.Name: Black Congratulatory Committee
value.Description: Plan and organize the Black Congratulatory Ceremony as well as any and all related events.
value.Summary: Plan and organize the Black Congratulatory Ceremony as well as any and all related events.

value.Name: Black Entrepreneurs & Technology
value.Description: Black Entrepreneurs & Technology (BET) is a black student organization created to promote entrepreneurship and the use of technology within the Black community here at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign. Our vision is to provide a safe space for students to share ideas, thoughts, and suggestions about possible companies, products, apps, services, and ventures. Even those who don't have an idea but would like to work in a team are welcomed. We will have weekly meetings and scheduled programs throughout each semester providing essential tools to entrepreneurship such as articulating ideas, beginning a startup, marketing skills, getting funding, project proposals, Intellectual Property (IP), and company sustainability. We plan to invite guest speakers who have had stories of both failures and successes, as well as various speakers to elaborate about specific departments in the entrepreneurial world. As our organization grows, we plan to take trips to entrepreneurship forums, workshops, startups, and a trip to Research Park.  Hopefully our members that do experience success will return to speak about it or even donate to the organization. This organization is a place where individuals can express themselves free of judgement and criticism. We maintain a positive, nondiscriminatory environment where students can learn how to turn an idea into a venture, while simultaneously networking with other students from various backgrounds and disciplines. Within this organization is where students will learn the importance of individuality, while also placing an emphasis on cooperation.
value.Summary: The purpose of Black Entrepreneurs & Technology is to systematically promote entrepreneurship and self-driven initiatives and provide adequate resources for team projects, while enhancing multicultural student's ability to present valuable ideas.

value.Name: Black Graduate Student Association
value.Description: The Black Graduate Student Association will serve as a home base to unify all Black graduate students at UIUC. Our uniqueness as a distinguished body of people allows us to come together for personal development, academic support, and social networking. We are a people of unprecedented perseverance, and will remain committed to ensuring Black graduate students at UIUC maintain a high matriculation rate.
value.Summary: The mission of the Black Graduate Student Association (BGSA) is to facilitate black graduate student matriculation. In this effort, BGSA acts a bridge connecting students with on-campus resources and with the black intellectual community at large.

value.Name: Black Greek Council
value.Description: To connect Black Greek Lettered Organizations on campus.
value.Summary: To connect Black Greek Lettered Organizations on campus.

value.Name: Black Law Students Association
value.Description: BLSA is a multicultural organization that provides resources to law students that enhance academic performance and leverage career planning and networking.  Our organization also provides programming on legal issues which impact our society.  The programming BLSA offers is very diverse.  For example, this year we will offer workshops led by COL deans on how to write effective outlines for your classes and how to write an exam.  We will also a host professional panel where we reenact scenes from a the Darren Wilson grand jury proceeding using actual transcripts for dialogue.  We then have a panel of professional speakers consisting of a judge, a states attorney, a federal defense attorney and a police officer to lead our discussion on the legal and social ramifications of this grand jury verdict.  BLSA also does volunteer work in the local community, conducts voter registration drives during election cycles, and throws an annual banquet in downtown Chicago for BLSA members and College of Law alumni.  We are a high energy organization dedicated to providing resources and perspectives that our student body, alumni and friends find insightful, meaningful and enjoyable.
value.Summary: BLSA is a multicultural organization that provides resources to law students that enhance academic performance and leverage career and networking opportunities. We also provide programming on legal issues which impact meaningfully on our society.

value.Name: Blueberry Champaign: the Campus Podcast
value.Summary: Our organization stands to provide social impact on campus students by producing short films and videos that relate to college students' daily lives!

value.Name: BOLD - Women in Innovation and Entrepreneurship
value.Description: BOLD is a student organization at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign that aims to empower women in innovation and entrepreneurship by building a vibrant community that is inclusive of all students. At its core, BOLD focuses on providing students with the resources they need for personal and professional development. Moreover, BOLD advocates for diverse representation in entrepreneurship and serves as a forum for showcasing the talents of the next generation of innovators, makers, and entrepreneurs.
value.Summary: BOLD is a student organization at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign that aims to empower women in innovation and entrepreneurship by building a vibrant community that is inclusive of all students.

value.Name: Bollywood Dhamaka
value.Summary: Bollywood Dhamaka is an Indian Dance Organization . India is a country with extremely diverse dance styles- Classical, Mujra, Tapori, just to name a few.. Bollywood Dhamaka aims to highlight and spread awareness of these dance styles at UIUC,

value.Name: Bradley Johnson Fan Club
value.Description: The Bradley Johnson Fan Club will serve as the premier organization on campus for people to find friends through mutual interests, namely Brad Johnson. We openly invite new members to come in and experience the shared camaraderie we all feel when speaking of Brad Johnson. He has touched all of our lives in many different ways, and we hope to use this RSO as a platform to thank him, as well as spread his positive message of humor and kindness. His celebrity status and platform have inspired us all to lead better lives.
value.Summary: BJFC is dedicated to promoting positivity through the recognition of all the amazing things done by Bradley Johnson.

value.Name: Brands Give Back
value.Description: Known for our annual Sustainable Fashion Show, Brands Give Back will be entering its second year on campus! Join us for monthly general meetings and fundraisers where we support MADE-BY, our non-profit cause that sheds light on social and environmental issues that can be contributed to using/wearing/making sustainable clothing.
value.Summary: BGB promotes sustainable fashion from an environmental and humanitarian perspective in order to preserve our planet in present-day and for the future.

value.Name: Brave New Midnight
value.Description:
Vampire the Requiem is a game of Gothic Horror with a theatrical approach. Create a character and explore the Vampiric night, becoming anything from the exalted antihero to the despicable monster in a game of undeath and politics. Interact with fellow players as their characters, each with a story and goals all their own. Journey to a darker Champaign-Urbana where stories of gritty mystery and personal horror abound. Intrigued? Come check us out for a night! We meet every second and fourth Friday of the month on the second floor of Gregory Hall.

In honor of the beginning of the Fall semester, we will have game on September, 2nd and every Friday in September except the 22nd to bring in the new year!
value.Summary: Live-Action RolePlaying (LARP) group based on White Wolf’s Vampire the Requiem

value.Name: Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu Club at UIUC
value.Description:
We practice 3x per week at the ARC Combat Room.

Join our Facebook group for more info: https://www.facebook.com/groups/100718087238691/
value.Summary: A club for people of all skill levels interested in practicing and learning brazilian jiu-jitsu.

value.Name: BridgeIllinois
value.Summary: BridgeUSA (the national affiliate of bridgeIllinois), stands to provide an open forum for political discourse and a good spirited debate, ultimately bringing together the left, right, independents, etc.

value.Name: Bridges International
value.Description:
The purpose of Bridges International is to encourage friendships amongst International and American students through: conversation partners, social events, Bible studies, and cultural events.

 

In other words, Bridges International is here to:

Serve International students

Be a Social resource to International students

Be a Spiritual resource to International students
value.Summary: The purpose of Bridges International is to encourage friendships for International and American students through conversation partners, social and cultural events, and Bible studies.

value.Name: Bridges to Prosperity - University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign Chapter
value.Summary: The UIUC Bridges to Prosperity (UIUC B2P) is a student-run chapter under the international, non-profit organization, Bridges to Prosperity. We engage students in the design and construction of footbridges for rural communities in developing countries.

value.Name: buildOn Community Team
value.Description: buildOn's focus is to fundraise and allow college students to travel, and help build a school in one of the seven developing countries that the organization is tied to. -Encouraging teamwork amongst peers

value.Name: Business in Environmental Responsibility
value.Description:
Create. Educate. Research. Volunteer. 

 

Business in Environmental Responsibility (BER) student organization in the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign is an organization welcoming students from all majors. Our organization focused on business, environment and sustainability. We aim to create a more sustainable environment for business, to raise more awareness in business responsibilities for future leaders, and to contribute more efforts considering sustainability for both the University and community. We focus on providing students with four main programs: Education, Volunteering, Research and Social. 

Our research projects focus on environment issues, and resources allocation in our University. We provide students with different types of educational programs including peers to peers education, conferences, lecturers speaking, and Facts on the Quad.

Our volunteering programs including volunteer for the Each Years' BP Case Competition. Serve in the Champaign-Urbana community where we students can help, connect and contribute to the local community considering topics related to environment and resources.

We gather information, conduct research on selected topics,  analyze each topic with business perspectives, and provide our recommendations for them each semester.
value.Summary: BER focuses on business, environment and sustainability. We aim to create a more sustainable environment for business, to raise more awareness in business responsibilities for future leaders, and to contribute more efforts considering sustainability.

value.Name: Business International Exchange Network
value.Description:
BIEN (Business International Exchange Network) is a registered student organization affiliated with College of Business International Programs. The purpose of the organization is to introduce incoming College of Business exchange students to life in America and at UIUC. BIEN is run by students who have previously studied abroad through College of Business programs, or plan to study abroad in the future. Members serve as ambassadors for the exchange students prior to their arrival as well as once they arrive on campus. They also organize cultural and social events throughout the semester to ensure that the exchange students get the most out of their study abroad experience while at UIUC.


Partner Universities:

--Bocconi University (Milan, Italy)
--Cass Business School (London, United Kingdom)
--ESADE (Barcelona, Spain)
--ESCP Europe (Paris, France)
--FREIE (Berlin, Germany)
--Hong Kong University of Science and Technology (Hong Kong)
--Insper (Sao Paulo, Brazil)
--Korea University Business School (Seoul, Korea)
--Manchester Business School (Manchester, United Kingdom)
--Nanyang Technical University (Singapore)
--Norwegian School of Management (Oslo, Norway)
--RSM Erasmus University (Rotterdam, The Netherlands)
--Vienna University of Economics & Business (Vienna, Austria)
--Universitat Duisburg (Duisburg, Germany)
--University of Melbourne (Melbourne, Australia)
--University of New South Wales (Sydney, Australia)
value.Summary: BIEN (Business International Exchange Network) is a registered student organization affiliated with College of Business International Programs. The purpose of the organization is to introduce College of Business exchange students to American campus life.

value.Name: Card Connoisseurs
value.Description:
Card Connoisseurs is focused on learning and playing card games together, mainly poker (specifically No Limit Texas Hold'em) and contract bridge. Members can learn and teach everything from basic rules to advanced strategy. Above all, this club aims to provide a comfortable and fun environment for playing with friends.

Note that all poker play is for practice only (no entry fees and no prizes). This club does not condone gambling.

Meeting times and locations will be communicated through the club Facebook page.

The board consists of six positions:

President
Coordinates the other board members and organizes board meetings. Ensures that the other board members can perform their duties. Maintains the smooth running of the club.

Treasurer
Manages and accounts for any funds or payments related to the club, such as application fees.

Secretary
Schedules general meetings and reserves appropriate locations. Fills out and submits any forms or paperwork for the club.

Vice President (Communications Director)
Manages the club Facebook page. Communicates general meeting times and locations through the Facebook page. Manages the club email address and sends emails as necessary. Takes any relevant feedback from members and informs the board.

Vice President (Event Director)
Comes up with ideas for events. Manages events as they happen.

Vice President (Education Director)
Assists beginners with learning the rules of card games. Answers questions about rules and strategy.

Any major decision regarding the club must be made with a majority vote of the board, with the president having veto power.
value.Summary: A club focused on learning and playing card games together, mainly poker (specifically No Limit Texas Hold'em) and contract bridge.

value.Name: Central Illinois Tang Soo Do
value.Description:
Visit our webpage at: http://www.citangsoo.com.

A traditional and practical martial art that has been refined over 2,000 years, Tang Soo Do emphasizes self-defense, physical fitness, and personal growth.  

Tang Soo Do practitioners learn to apply a wide range of techniques (including upper and lower body striking, joint locks, and throws) in order to defend themsleves and others against a wide range of attacks (including strikes, grabs, weapons, and multiple opponents).

Central Illinois Tang Soo Do is a member of the World Tang Soo Do Association (WTSDA), an organization with more than 100,000 members in 36 countries.  We are one of over 20 studios within WTSDA Region 5, which includes Illinois, Indiana, Michigan, and Wisconsin.

Head instructor Herschel Pangborn has over fifteen years of martial arts practice and has been teaching students across all ages and experience levels for more than five years.  He is a third-degree black belt, internationally certified instructor, and certified tournament corner judge with the WTSDA.  Herschel is also a PhD student in the Department of Mechanical Science and Engineering.
value.Summary: A traditional and practical martial art that has been refined over 2000 years, Tang Soo Do emphasizes self-defense, physical fitness, and personal growth.

Each of us come from a unique set of dance experiences which we as a team hope to share with one another and to others. As dancers, performing is just something we do, but our aim here is for growth. We hope to challenge each other as dancers and to help one another improve. This group is a means of expression for us all; a place to be able to experiment with your creative movement and feed off of others.

Members of this group have had considerable success reaching competitive levels, and placing very well.

value.Name: Champaign-Urbana Business and Engineering Consulting
value.Description:
Champaign-Urbana Business and Engineering Consulting (CUBE) is a non-profit consulting organization with a talented group of students who work together on meaningful projects for local businesses. We are guided by the following values: 

Impact
Our members come from a variety of academic and professional backgrounds, but we are unified in our desire to combine our diverse skill sets in order to provide the most holistic insights for our clients and impact our local community. 

Leadership 
From day one, our members are given opportunities for professional development and leadership. These real world experiences help prepare our members to be leaders in any field. 

Growth
Our community is smaller, which allows us a unique opportunity to closely support each other to work towards achieving our goals.

Diversity
Our membership consists of students at the top of their class across a variety of majors and fields. We specialize specifically in Engineering, Business, and Design. This range allows us to deliver closely-customized technical and multi-faceted solutions to our clients, as well as offers students an exposure to a wide-range of skills and the opportunity to be a leader in their own area of expertise.
value.Summary: CUBE Consulting uses engineering expertise to provide business solutions through the creation of tangible products. Services are provided to small businesses, start-up companies, and research organizations within Champaign-Urbana and beyond.

value.Name: China Studies Forum
value.Description: The China Studies Forum aims to provide an interactive platform for interested students to deliberate and debate about China-related contemporary issues. The rise of China is a unique phenomenon in the 21st century. Its ascendancy not only represents a reshuffle of the existing geopolitical world order, but also appears to be an attractive research and study area. Yet a sense of secrecy and incomprehension still prevails when college students are trying to interpret China-related news and issues, and the UIUC is still lacking a place for student China watchers to exchange thoughts with each other. This forum dedicates to make up this void by holding weekly roundtable discussions. For one thing, the diversity of UIUC is a resource too invaluable to be wasted. For a forum committed to facilitate students’ understanding of an alien civilization, a diverse composition of participants is an innate requirement. This forum will carry out multilingual publicity, hoping to generate a multilateral interpretation into discussions. The membership includes two layers. Core members are responsible for the daily operation of the Forum and discussion topic preparation whereas discussion members are only expected to engage into weekly discussions. Every week, the Forum will select a relevant topic for discussion based on weekly hot news and it will then pick out one researcher from core members with some expertise in this area to undertake academic studies in this area. No later than two days before the announced discussion date, this researcher is required to send two or three analysis or features and several questions to all members to introduce the general background, different schools of thought, and interpretation of the issue. The discussion will take place at night on a selected day of the week and that researcher is to lead the 1.5 hours discussion. The whole discussion process includes a brief review of the articles being sent and in-depth discussion of the questions raised by the researcher.
value.Summary: The China Studies Forum endeavors to become a podium where students from different national and disciplinary background can learn and exchange views on China-related issues.

value.Name: Chinese Business Students & Alumni Association
value.Description:
Chinese Business Student & Alumni Association is a start-up association. We connect Chinese students and alumni to get valuable information for students no matter whether they would like to go back to China or find a job in the US.

Our resources come from career services at Business School and School of Labor and Employment Relations and also alumni network to make the education of Chinese Master Students in U of I more valuable to their career.

In order to maximize the efficiency of our platform, CBSAA would like to invite every proactive Chinese graduate student in business-related program to join us. We expect our partners to collect and share resources and job-hunting information from different programs, alumni, professors/staffs, visiting scholars/short-term training professionals, etc.

Our forms of activities include:
 Career fair information sharing: companies, jobs, networks and skills
 Networking events in major cities
 Storybooks of successful alumni
 Alumni panel, conference call, webinar, etc.

For detailed information about our events, please visit our official website uiuccbsaa.com.
value.Summary: CBSAA is an association which focuses on providing better career opportunities to Chinese students with business related major at University of Illinois.

value.Name: Chinese Career Board

We also hold events that trains some of the most important skills in job searching, so students, after graduating, can be better prepared for their future, no matter where they choose to work.

To get access to more career opportunities, networking opportunities and our skill-developing workshops, please subscribe our WeChat(Chinese-only) platform: UIUC_CCB. For your convenience, the barcode is in Gallery

Anyone who is interested in helping other students or develop your own skills is welcome to join us. We accept applications all year round. To apply, please email: yhuang92@illinois.edu with your resume. We are a group of fun and energetic people who want to have more fun with YOU!
