value.Name: Chinese Engineering Student Association
value.Description:
Organization description

Chinese Engineering Student Association is committed to provide high-quality services and resources to help Chinese Engineering students on campus to achieve their academic and career goals.

As the largest minority group on the UIUC campus today, one third of the over 5000 Chinese international students population attend to the College of Engineering. Thus, we see the necessity to establish an association that strives to help them achieve excellence and success in both academic and professional fields. Specifically, CESA aims to perform the functions as described below.

First of all, CESA will build a platform for Chinese engineering students to share their study experiences and resources by collecting resources from students who are taking or have taken different engineering courses in their curriculum. All membership of CESA can use these resources and have responsibility to share their own resources. Nonetheless, we object to pure duplication of homework and projects while encouraging original work and ideas.

Also, through general meetings, activities and workshops, CESA offers members the opportunity to socialize with peer students, build study groups, and share research and job opportunities. In order to make this function more efficient, we will appoint an undergraduate student advisor for each department .

In addition, each semester, we will invite professors from the Engineering Department and representatives from corporations in the field to give speeches. Through the speeches, our members will not only learn the current trends in the Engineering field, but also build network with prospective employers. Moreover, these speeches can be opportunities of researches and internship as well as answers to questions about future study and career for students.

At the same time, we will hold some indoor and outdoor activities to enrich engineering students’ life, such as sports tournaments, weight training groups, paintball, BBQ parties, etc. During these activities, we will also corporate with other student organizations on campus, which will help our CESA members to get involved in American campus life. We do believe that physical fitness is as important as academic ability even for engineering students.
value.Summary: The CESA dedicated to help Chinese engineering students develop and  achieve their academic and career goals. We provide opportunities and organize activities for student to realize their potential and further impact society.

value.Name: Club Football
value.Description:
The University of Illinois Football Club provides the opportunity for students to play full contact and organized football under NCAA regulations through the National Club Football Association (NCFA).

Many students who previously played football in high school miss the intensity and competitiveness of it, and this club presents another outlet for students to get involved.

Football demands a level of teamwork like no other. Unlike other sports, all eleven players on the field must do their jobs in order to be successful. When players realize the advantage of cooperating in a single effort and learn the dynamics of working together with people aiming for the same goal, they can utilize these skills in their academic and professional life.

Similar to other sports, leadership is the key to any successful team. Players constantly face challenges and adversity in the sport of football. Situations like these open opportunities for students to step up and become leaders.
value.Summary: The University of Illinois Football Club provides the opportunity for students to play full contact and organized football under NCAA regulations through the National Club Football Association (NCFA).

College years are a stressful time and adding diabetes on top of it can make for a difficult transition and we want to make an environment where everyone understands what we are going through.

value.Name: College Republicans at UIUC
value.Description:
College Republicans at UIUC seeks to defend and uphold the constitutional government of the United States, whose founding ideals include limited government, personal freedom, free market entrepreneurship, and self-responsible individuals. Through active participation at the local, state, and national levels of politics and government, as well as social interaction with individuals on campus, members of CRs have the opportunity to impact current events and topics in an effective and positive manner, while obtaining valuable professional skills.

Now more than ever, when our personal freedoms, way of living, and opportunities are daily threatened, it is up to OUR generation to take our country back. Join us!
value.Summary: College Republicans at UIUC seeks to grow and foster the Republican ideals of limited government, personal freedom, free-market entrepreneurship and self-responsibility on campus.

value.Name: College Service Project
value.Description:
Appalachia Service Project was started almost 50 years ago when a United Methodist minister wanted to connect the energy of youth with the needs of the poor in central Appalachia. Today, over 16,000 volunteers travel every summer down to Appalachia to provide critical repairs to over 500 families. ASP construction is much more than painting rooms and cosmetic work. ASP volunteers rebuild foundations, replace roofs, construct room additions, construct entirely new homes, and do a variety of other construction intensive projects all while placing an emphasis on creating lasting relationships with homeowners and the community. ASP’s goal is to eradicate substandard housing in central Appalachia by making homes warmer, safer, and drier.

 In its more recent years, ASP has started a college program to focus on repairs and other needs of ASP outside of the summer. Currently, 11 chapters of CSP work to spread awareness of poverty in central Appalachia on campus, raise money for ASP, and make trips to Appalachia during winter, fall, and spring breaks to conduct work and construction for ASP.
value.Summary: College Service Project is a student-led, campus based organization focused on raising awareness of poverty in central Appalachia and organizing trips to Appalachia to provide home repair for families in need.

value.Name: Colleges Against Cancer
value.Description:
Colleges Against Cancer is a nationwide collaboration of students, faculty and staff dedicated to eliminating cancer as a major health threat by working with the American Cancer Society to help people stay well, get well, find cures and fight back. An organization that started right here at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign back in 2001 has since grown into a movement that encompasses nearly 400 college campuses across the country. 

Colleges Against Cancer focuses on four strategic directions including Cancer Education, Advocacy, Survivor and Caregiver Engagement, and Relay For Life. We work year round to help bring the mission of the American Cancer Society to all demographics on our campus. Our organization also works to grow the grassroots base of American Cancer Society volunteers right here at Illinois.
value.Summary: Colleges Against Cancer is a nationwide collaboration of students, faculty and staff dedicated to eliminating cancer as a major health threat by working with the American Cancer Society to help people stay well, get well, find cures and fight back.

value.Name: Collegiate Farm Bureau
value.Description:
Grain invaluable leadership and communication skills. Take up a leadership position in our organization. Learn how to converse with consumers that have differing viewpoints. Participate in Collegiate Discussion Meet to solve real-world problems in agriculture with your peers.

Make invaluable, personal contacts with industry professionals. CFB goes beyond speakers and presenters. Be matched with your very own mentor that will be there throughout your college career to answer your questions and help foster your career. You'll also meet some of the most influential people in our industry.

Get outside Chambana, the county and the state with CFB. Attend the Collegiate Discussion Meet in Kansas City, MO. Check out the Illinois Farm Bureau's annual meetings in Chicago and St. Louis. Go to the Young Leaders Conference in Peoria, Ill. Learn about agriculture on farm tours of wineries, dairies, alpaca farms and more!

Receive a multitude of scholarships and discounts. CFB has dedicated scholarships available for its members. Collegiate Discussion Meet participants may receive $250 and up to $2,500. Each CFB member receives local and state discounts such as a free drink with entre at Za's and 20% off Choice and Wyndham hotels.

value.Name: Colombian Student Association at the University of Illinois
value.Description:
Our Mission

To offer an extended network for all Colombian students, as well as other Colombians in the Champaign-Urbana community to ensure their academic and personal success.
 

Our Vision

We expect to be more than just a "student group." We would like to be a group that provides support to any Colombian on campus. That includes UIUC faculty, visiting scholars, and their families,  Colombian students at Parkland College, as well as Colombian families in Champaign-Urbana and nearby areas.
 
For us, being Colombian is about having a link to our culture and traditions. There are students born from Colombian parents whose participation we would like to encourage. We hope they also feel that this is THEIR Association also.
 

Our Purposes

The Colombian Students Association, as a Registered Student Organization (RSO) at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, has two main purposes:
  1. To provide Colombian students and community members within Champaign-Urbana with a social support network that can make their experience at UIUC a very successful one. 
  2. To seek and provide opportunities to share information and experiences about Colombia to other campus and community organizations.
value.Summary: The Colombian Student Association is the main social network for Colombians in the University of Illinois. Our mission is to offer an extended network for all Colombian students, as well as other Colombians in the Champaign-Urbana community.

Mentors (upper-class students) assist Mentees (first year students) become acquainted with the University and its resources. In many cases, Mentors and Mentees establish friendships that stretch beyond the CORE program and continue for the duration of their college careers. The CORE Mentor Program sponsors events and activities throughout the year, which address the needs of the students.

We meet once every week on Wednesdays 6:30-7:45 PM in the English Building, providing students with a non-demanding outlet to write, share, and connect with their peers. Students from all different majors are welcome to join.
value.Summary: Our club encourages creativity through fun writing activities and peer-to-peer collaboration. CWC is an engaging community where students of various backgrounds can connect with fellow writers and share their work in an informal and open atmosphere

Where cafe and extra credits cannot be donated, food can. We are encouraging students to utilize whatever credits are left over from each week that will be lost and donate packaged food from any of the several 'A La Carte' dining locations. This food will then be donated to the Eastern Illinois Foodbank.
value.Summary: We seek to get the most out of the University Meal Plan in using extra meal plan credits to contribute donations to local food banks.

It was one of the first organized Cricket Clubs founded in this region at the time. Over the last two decades CCI has had a very diverse group of members coming from different countries and cultures.

The club has played in several regional cricket tournaments and has successfully hosted the Illini Cricket Cup for four consecutive years. CCI has participates in major tournaments like Midwest Cricket Conference (Chicago) and Midwest Cricket League (Ohio).

This holistic club gives members a glance at all facets of  the world of cryptocurrency, from production, investment, and price analysis. New trends and advances in technology will be discussed at bi-weekly meetings. All students are encouraged to join and experience the ever-changing world of modern money.

value.Name: Cryptocurrency Trading Club
value.Description:
The Crypto Trading Club (CTC) @ UIUC has been established with these goals:

1- Education

Even though cryptocurrencies have been around for almost a decade, many including students lack knowledge on this topic. Our main goal is to educate whoever wants to be involved in cryptocurrencies whether it is because they are interested in Financial Technology (FinTech) or want to learn some basics in trading before risking much.

2- Succeeding Together

Many are interested in this area because they are intrigued by the idea of anonymity and decentralization of banks. However, many also want to be involved because of the media and how it promotes cryptocurrencies as an investment tool for both the long and the short term. We will be providing insight on how to trade these currencies as well as sharing market analyses every week, hopefully leading our members to succeed together.

3- Preparing for the Future

No matter the major, many are interested in cryptocurrencies. Some see it as a short term investment tool however some may want to be involved with cryptocurrencies for the long term. We aim to prepare students by giving insight on the logistics and mechanics of cryptocurrencies.
value.Summary: Organization for students who are involved in cryptocurrencies and the blockchain technology.

value.Name: CSL Student Conference
value.Description: The CSL Student Conference is  an annual student-led, multidisciplinary conference held at the Coordinated Science Laboratory (CSL) at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign (UIUC). The main goal of the conference is to enable students to present their work and interact with faculty, invited speakers, industry representatives, and invited students from other top schools.  The conference engages students and faculty from various departments at the University of Illinois working on various topics in computing, communications, signal processing,electronics, decision and control. The organizing committee is completely comprised of graduate students from various backgrounds. The conference is typically held in February each year.
value.Summary: The CSL Student Conference is an annual student-led, multidisciplinary conference held at the Coordinated Science Laboratory (CSL), that enables students to present their work and interact with faculty, invited speakers, and industry representatives.

value.Name: CURE International at UIUC
value.Description: CURE International is a non-profit organization that operates charitable hospitals and programs in 29 countries worldwide where patients experience the life-changing message of God’s love for them, receiving surgical treatment regardless of gender, religion, or ethnicity. CURE UIUC strives to raise awareness about disabilities in the developing world while providing support for these children through our own communities here at University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign. By hosting fundraisers, we will raise money to sponsor surgical procedures, while also empowering the students and residents of University of Illinois to realize that together we can make a difference.  cureuiuc.weebly.com
value.Summary: CURE International UIUC is a group dedicated to raising money for children's surgical procedures, and reaching out to UIUC community in order to provide awareness of disabilities in the developing world, CURE International, and the children they support

value.Name: Cure it Foundation
value.Description:
The Cure It Foundation is a nonprofit organization fighting to cure pediatric cancer while providing personalized support for the children diagnosed with this terrible illness and their families. Founded in 2011, The Cure It Foundation is a grassroots organization built upon the compassion, hard work and dedication of patients, survivors, parents, physicians, nurses and community members. While encouraging advances have been made in the treatment of pediatric cancer, The Cure It Foundation will continue to fight until the day when all children diagnosed with cancer can be cured.

It is the dual mission of The Cure It Foundation to fund national pediatric cancer research and to lessen the impact of the illness by providing support and care for children in our communities. A portion of all funds raised goes directly to pediatric cancer research, helping those actively researching and implementing trials that will lead to curing this life-threatening illness. Locally, The Cure It Foundation supports the communities that sustain the mission by directly giving back to fighters and survivors of childhood cancer through its various programs.

The struggles faced by children diagnosed with cancer are unimaginable. No child deserves this fate, which is why The Cure It Foundation is committed to ensuring that all of our kids can continue to play, thrive and live their lives to the fullest. Join us, and together we can… we will… CURE IT
value.Summary: The Cure It Foundation is a nonprofit organization fighting to cure pediatric cancer while providing personalized support for the children diagnosed with this terrible illness and their families.

value.Name: Delta Kappa Delta Sorority, Inc.
value.Description: Delta Kappa Delta Sorority, Inc. is the first and only South-Asian interest, service sorority in the nation. The University of Illinois at Urbana Champaign is home to Epsilon Chapter, which was founded on September 30, 2006.  After 10 years on campus, we have strived to promote Delta Kappa Delta’s principles of sisterhood, service, culture, and indomitable spirit, as well as our motto – Sisterhood built through Service. We are incredibly proud of our work to further our philanthropy, child abuse awareness and prevention. We do service on campus with organizations like Crisis Nursery, The Center for Women in Transition, and Asha for Education, as well as at events like Read Across America and Relay for Life. In addition, we enjoy a strong social life through monthly sisterhood socials and mixers with other campus organizations.
value.Summary: Multicultural service sorority dedicated to the prevention and awareness of child abuse, as well as the education of children.

value.Name: Delta Kappa Epsilon: Delta Pi
value.Description: It is the mission of Delta Kappa Epsilon at the University of Illinois to promote the Objects and Principles of DKE and the Qualities of the Gentleman, Scholar, and Jolly Good-Fellow. It is our intent to foster brotherhood in accordance with the traditions and proud history of Delta Kappa Epsilon. Among our chief goals is the desire to be active members of the Greek and local communities, contributing to them through our acts of service, philanthropy, and leadership. We further commit ourselves to the development of each member in the areas ranging from, but not limited to, academic and intellectual excellence, honorable friendship, community involvement, a spirit of tolerance and understanding, high moral character, self-respect, and an appreciation and understanding of social culture and general literature.
value.Summary: Five U.S. Presidents, a President of Cuba, astronauts, Medal of Honor recipients, trailblazers, CEOs, scientists, professors, famed musicians, hall of fame athletes, Nobel Prize winners, and more. One thing is for sure: in DKE we build a house of fame.

value.Name: Delta Phi Delta Dance Fraternity, Inc. ( Co-Ed )
value.Description: To cultivate a sense of unity amongst the dance community in the Champaign-Urbana area through the hosting of competitions, community service, and performances without restitution.
value.Summary: Delta Phi Delta Dance Fraternity, Inc. has strived to be a national non-profit educational organization dedicated to the preservation, study, teaching, enjoyment and continuing evolution of all dance styles.

value.Name: Delta Phi Omega Sorority, Inc.
value.Description:
Delta Phi Omega Sorority, Inc. was established on December 6, 1998 at the University of Houston by sixteen South Asian women who recognized the need for an organization to promote the advancement of South Asian women. Sixteen women from various backgrounds came together with the common goal of uniting women among the South Asian community. The Founders created the backbone of this sorority on the basis of the five pillars of Sisterhood, Respect, Loyalty, Honesty, and Friendship. They envisioned an organization that would highlight the diverse Indian culture through participation in community and social service projects

Through determination and perseverance, this vision evolved into a reality and as a result has become the most sought after sorority for not only South Asian women, but woman of all backgrounds, across theUnited States. With each passing year, Delta Phi Omega continues to grow and make its presence known not only within their respective universities but also within the community. It is proud to be known as the nationa's largest, strongest, and fastest growing South Asian interest sorority.
value.Summary: Delta Phi Omega was founded on December 6, 1998. The Sorority is based on five pillars including Sisterhood, Friendship, Loyalty, Respect, and Honesty. Furthermore, the Sorority aspires to instill leadership traits as well as build community awareness.

value.Name: Delta Sigma Omicron (Disability Service Organization)
value.Description:
Delta Sigma Omicron (DSO) is a rehabilitation service fraternity whose members originally were students with disabilities on the University of Illinois campus. Membership is now open to all persons enrolled in the University of Illinois, Alumni and field members with an interest in ensuring that qualified individuals with disabilities are afforded an equal opportunity to participate in, and benefit from, the curricular, co-curricular and vocational opportunities available at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign.

Delta Sigma Omicron has a long, proud, and distinguished history. It was founded in 1948 and incorporated in 1949 in Illinois, long before individuals with disabilities received any public or media attention and long before there were any meaningful State or Federal laws. Delta Sigma Omicron, through its programs and membership, played many significant roles in bringing about some of the legislation and benefits that now exist.

It was the first Fraternity dedicated to education, research, and service in rehabilitation, made up entirely of achieving individuals with disabilities. It pioneered in many areas of concern such as education, employment, accessibility, transportation, sports and recreation on behalf of those with disabilities.

Since its founding, Delta Sigma Omicron has contributed significant funding to charities aiding persons with disabilities. Finally, its members have conducted, participated in and have been subjects for research furthering rehabilitation.
value.Summary: Delta Sigma Omicron (DSO) is a rehabilitation service fraternity whose members originally were students with disabilities on the University of Illinois campus. Membership is now open to all persons enrolled in the University of Illinois, Alumni

value.Name: Delta Sigma Pi Business Fraternity
value.Description: Delta Sigma Pi is a professional fraternity organized to foster the study of business in universities; to encourage scholarship, social activity and the association of students for their mutual advancement by research and practice; to promote closer affiliation between the commercial world and students of commerce, and to further a higher standard of commercial ethics and culture and the civic and commercial welfare of the community.
value.Summary: Delta Sigma Pi is America's foremost professional fraternity for men and women pursuing careers in business. Delta Sigma Pi advances its members professionally, academically, socially, and philanthropically.

value.Name: Delta Sigma Theta Sorority, Inc Alpha Nu Chapter
value.Description: Delta Sigma Theta Sorority, Incorporated. is a private, not-for-profit organization whose purpose is to provide assistance and support through established programs in local communities throughout the world. Since its founding more than 200,000 women have joined the organization. The organization is a sisterhood of predominantly Black, college educated women. The sorority currently has 1,000 collegiate and alumnae chapters located in the United States, England, Japan (Tokyo and Okinawa), Germany, the Virgin Islands, Bermuda, the Bahamas, Jamaica and the Republic of Korea. The organization prides itself on the current bienium theme: Uncompromising Commitment to Communities: Service, Leadership, Empowerment. - Dr. Paulette C Walker (National President)

value.Name: Design For America at UIUC
value.Description: Design For America brings together students from all majors and backgrounds to create products and solutions that solve real world problems with a focus on the community. Our mission is to provide all University of Illinois students interested in making a difference with the opportunity to develop themselves professionally, achieve personal growth, and foster relationships with a diverse group of people while completing hands-on projects. Projects are DFA's main focus, but there are also workshops, social events, and networking events with companies.  We believe that people from different majors each bring their own perspective and skills, and that is what makes for a well-rounded team. DFA gives students the opportunity to learn the human centered design process with a purpose and have the opportunity to create real, lasting impact.
value.Summary: Design For America is a unique organization where all backgrounds and majors come together to create products and solutions to solve real world problems. Design For America allows students to engage in hands-on projects that create real, lasting impact.

The organization will serve as a mentoring resource to undergraduate students within the School of Art + Design. This organization also serves as a point of contact for Art + Design faculty and administration with the industrial and graphic design graduate students.

value.Name: Downstate Legal Association
value.Description: The Downstate Legal Association will actively work to improve the career prospects of law students wishing to practice law in downstate Illinois. This goal will be accomplished in part by hosting social events where members of the DLA can network amongst each other. The DLA will also try to establish connections between its members and downstate alumni and employers. The DLA will also invite guest speakers who can speak on relevant topics. Any law student is welcome to join.
value.Summary: The Downstate Legal Association will actively work to improve the career prospects of law students wishing to practice law in downstate Illinois.

value.Name: Dr. Interns UIUC
value.Description:
Dr. Interns (formally known as Global Aid L.L.C.) is a 501(c)3 non-profit organization for medical and healthcare internships abroad. Our organization is dedicated to providing not only a career enhancing experience, but also a life changing one. Interns work side-by-side with doctors in developing countries to save lives and improve healthcare conditions. Dr. Interns seeks to educate future medical leaders on the preventable disparities that cripple many under-served regions of the world today. 

 

Our long term-goal includes building mobile medical clinics that provide self-sustaining basic health care for those who normally would go without. We credit our interns and donors for their desire to make an everlasting impact in the communities they help serve. For more information on the mobile clinics, please continue the tour below. 

 

At Dr. Interns, we take a simple approach to a complex problem. By being dedicated, upfront and passionate about what we do, our organization is able to work with a variety of students, companies, and doctors who share the same vision. We encourage everyone who is interested in our program to apply, because one person leads to others making the same difference.

 

-The Dr. Interns Team
**taken from the orignal site: http://www.drinterns.org
value.Summary: Dr. Interns provides medical and health care internships abroad. Dedicated to bringing life changing experiences and assistance everywhere.

value.Name: Earthquake Engineering Research Institute
value.Description: Student Chapter of the EERI at the University of Illinois
value.Summary:
We are the student chapter of the EERI at the University of Illinois. 
Our activities include the Undergraduate Seismic Design Competition, seminars and webinars from accomplished guest speakers,and more!  Anyone is welcome to join.

value.Name: ECE Pulse
value.Description: The Pulse conference is an annual technical conference hosted by the students of the ECE Department. This conference is held in the Spring semester and consists of workshops, technical competitions, tech talks, networking events and a keynote speech. Students attending the conference learn about the latest innovations from the most innovative companies and have the opportunity to speak directly with company representatives to explore the opportunities available during or after finishing their undergraduate or graduate studies.
value.Summary: The ECE Pulse organization consists of students of the ECE Department who are interested in organizing the tech conference, ECE Pulse. The organization consists of a Director and other subdirectors who help organize different aspects of the conference.

value.Description: This organization challenges students' engineering and analytical skills and raises awareness for our world's energy and environmental needs. Students from all majors are encouraged to join, especially those in design, marketing, engineering and business. For more information visit https://ecoillini.wordpress.com/ and https://www.facebook.com/ecoillini/.
value.Summary: The purpose of this organization is to design and fabricate a highly fuel efficient car to compete annually in the Shell Eco-Marathon Americas and SAE Supermilage Competitions.

Welcome to the Econ Club!

The UIUC Economics Club is a combination of an Academic Club, Professional Club, and a Social Club.  The purpose is to bring people together that are interested in Economics, no matter what your major, to create and develop a strong network.

value.Name: Education And Training For Health
value.Description:
With chronic lifestyle related disorders such as obesity, high blood pressure, and diabetes on the rise, it is important to teach children proper nutrition and give them the resources to live a healthy life. We visit elementary schools delivering 1 hour long lesson plans for 8-weeks, personalized for each grade level. Each lesson introduces a nutrition concept, has a hands on activity, and ends with a healthy snack making portion. The intent is to provide children with the knowledge and skill set to lead a happy and healthy life.

 

Meet our Sponsors:

 

 

Studypool is an online marketplace that connects students with questions with tutors who can answer them. Using Studypool gives you access to thousands of verified tutors to help you with any question at any time.

 

 

The Most Booked Restaurant In The U.S. 5 Years Running: Founding Farmers

 

We are sponsored by owlmetrics.
value.Summary: We visit elementary schools each week introducing a new nutrition concept followed by a hands on activity and ending with a healthy snack making portion. The intent is to provide children with the knowledge and skill set to lead a happy and healthy life.

value.Name: Education Law and Policy Society
value.Description: The mission of the Education Law and Policy Society is to build University of Illinois students’ awareness and commitment to the legal and policy issues affecting education through: (1) forums encouraging dialogue about educational issues between leaders in the field including attorneys, professors, educators, legislators, and policy experts, (2) opportunities to learn the process of creating and influencing state and federal educational law and policy, and (3) establishing long-term collaborative networks for career and education related goals.
value.Summary: The Education Law and Policy Society builds University of Illinois students' awareness and commitment to the legal and policy issues affecting education.

value.Name: Egyptian Student Association in North America
value.ShortName: Egyptian Student Association in North America
value.Description:
The Egyptian Student Association in North America (ESANA), is a registered non-profit organization, that aims at integrating the Egyptian student community in North America with the research and public community in North America, Egypt and worldwide. ESANA is the largest Egyptian student gathering outside Egypt, with a number of members exceeding 1800 and over 37 local chapters (units) throughout Canada and the US. To download ESANA Brochure, click here .

We are the student chapter of ESANA in UIUC.

ESANA has the following primary goals:

  1. A syndicated goal: to protect and care for the affairs of its members, to objectively analyze and struggle to solve their problems and to represent them in front of all official and non-official levels.
  2. A promotional goal: to expose the true civilized character of Egypt and to promote for the national efforts of Egypt for peace in front of the American, Canadian and International societies.
  3. A scientific goal: to follow-up on the scientific deficiencies in Egypt and try to provide solutions within the resources of ESANA.
value.Summary: The Egyptian Student Association in North America (ESANA), is a registered student organization, that aims at integrating the Egyptian student community in North America with the research and public community in North America, Egypt and worldwide.

value.Name: Electronic Music Club
value.Description:
The Electronic Music Club (EMC) is an organization dedicated to the appreciation, production, and exploration of all genres of electronic music. We are currently seeking to build the foundation for a strong and welcoming electronic music scene in Champaign-Urbana. Emphasis will be placed on social engagement as well as on opportunities for musical exploration and production.

Check us out on Facebook for active updates on the club! 

https://www.facebook.com/groups/679384435495847/

uiucemc.com

or search UIUC Electronic Music Club
value.Summary: The Electronic Music Club (EMC) is an organization dedicated to the appreciation, production, and exploration of all genres of electronic music. Emcee seeks to develop a friendly and accessible electronic music scene in Champaign-Urbana.

value.Name: Elysium on the Prairie
value.Description:
Vampire the Requiem is a game of Gothic Horror with a theatrical approach. Create a character and explore the Vampiric night, becoming anything from the exalted antihero to the despicable monster in a game of undeath and politics. Interact with fellow players as their characters, each with a story and goals all their own. Journey to a darker Champaign-Urbana where stories of gritty mystery and personal horror abound. Intrigued? Come check us out for a night! We meet every second and fourth Friday of the month on the second floor of Gregory Hall.

In honor of the beginning of the Fall semester, we will have game on August, 28th and every Friday in September to bring in the new year!
value.Summary: Live-Action RolePlaying (LARP) group based on White Wolf's Vampire the Requiem

value.Name: EmpowerME
value.Description: The purpose of EmpowerME is to inspire minorities, both in race and in gender, to channel their inner strengths and power in order to better themselves and their community. EmpowerME aims to aid individuals in overcoming everyday obstacles, so that they may achieve greatness and success. Formally known as Black Women Rock!, EmpowerME will still uphold BWR!'s values of channeling full potential within each of our members, for the purpose of inspiring others and bettering our community. Through uplifting workshops, award ceremonies for those who are not regularly appreciated or recognized, and other insipartional events, EmpowerME will bring an improved sense of inspiration to both campus and the community. Just as before, we will RECOGNIZE and INSPIRE, only this time EMPOWERing others along the way.
value.Summary: EmpowerME works to inspire minorities, both in race and in gender, to channel and nourish their inner strengths. Formally known as Black Women Rock!, EmpowerME brings an improved sense of inspiration to campus,  improving our community and its members.

value.Name: Enactus
value.Description:
Enactus is an international non-profit organization that brings together student, academic and business leaders who are committed to using the power of entrepreneurial action to improve the quality of life and standard of living for people in need.

Guided by academic advisors and business experts, the student leaders of Enactus create and implement community empowerment projects around the globe. The experience not only transforms lives, it helps students develop the kind of talent and perspective that are essential to leadership in an ever-more complicated and challenging world.
value.Summary: We are students dedicated to changing the world through entrepreneurial action. With a head for business and a heart for the world, our projects impact lives and create sustainable solutions fro today's most challenging problems.

value.Name: Energy and Environmental Law Society
value.Description: The Energy and Environmental Law Society is an organization at the College of Law. This organization hosts speaker events where we invite professors who are experts in the field and environmental lawyers to come talk about their careers and network.
value.Summary: The Energy and Environmental Law Society is an organization for law students interested in learning more about environmental law and/or want to foster connections in the field of environmental or energy law.

value.Name: Engineering Council
value.Description: Engineering Council (EC) is an engineering student council that aims to provide resources and support for engineering students and societies.
value.Summary: Engineering Council (EC) is an engineering student council that aims to provide resources and support for engineering students and societies.

value.Name: Engineering Employment EXPO
value.Description: The Engineering Employment EXPO at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign is one of the largest student-run engineering career fairs in the nation. Our mission is to connect students and employers through our career fairs in the fall and spring semesters. All of the proceeds from both events support student activities within the College of Engineering.
value.Summary: The Engineering Employment EXPO at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign is one of the largest student-run engineering career fairs in the nation.

value.Name: Engineering Open House
value.Description:
Engineering Open House is an annual student-led event featuring two days of exciting exhibits and captivating competitions that showcase the talent and ingenuity of engineering students. The exposition attracts thousands of visitors to the Illinois campus each year and stands as the largest event of its kind in the country. EOH brings together students, faculty, and corporate sponsors to feature cutting-edge innovation in the fields of science and technology.

Engineering Open House strives to create a more educated, science-oriented culture with the University of Illinois College of Engineering at the forefront of technological advancements. We aim to inspire the next generation of engineers and lay a foundation for engineering to become the key to solving future problems.
value.Summary: Engineering Open House is an annual student-led event featuring two days of exciting exhibits and captivating competitions that showcase the talent and ingenuity of engineering students at Illinois.

value.Name: Engineering Outreach Society
value.Description: The Engineering Outreach Society (EOS) is a student-run organization that welcomes UIUC students of all majors to visit Leal Elementary School and Dr. Williams Elementary School in order to perform hands-on, engineering-inspired experiments with elementary school students. In the past, EOS members have also participated in volunteer events with the Boy Scouts of America, the Society of Women Engineers, and the Illini Society of Fire Protection Engineers. We give you the flexibility to volunteer as much or as little as you would like, but most members typically dedicate one hour a week to EOS volunteering. This organization is perfect for those who are looking for a fun and relaxed way of getting involved in STEM outreach.
value.Summary: The Engineering Outreach Society works to provide an interactive learning environment for elementary school students through the use of hands-on science experiments!

value.Name: Engineering Student Alumni Ambassadors
value.Description:
ESAA strives to create an interactive student alumni community within the College of Engineering by coordinating innovative programs promoting pride, networking, and collaborative opportunities.

We hope to establish relationships among students and alumni that foster possibilities for continued growth and development of the College of Engineering.
value.Summary: ESAA strives to create an interactive community among everyone related to the College of Engineering by coordinating innovative programs promoting pride, networking, and collaborative opportunities.

value.Name: Engineers For a Sustainable World UIUC
value.Summary: The mission of Engineers for a Sustainable World is to forge innovative, lasting solutions to local and global sustainability challenges through implementation of student design projects and education efforts.

value.Name: Engineers Volunteering in STEM Education
value.Description:
The mission of ENVISION is to increase the opportunity of STEM outreach for engineering graduate students at the University of Illinois. The organization seeks to promote leadership, communication, and teaching skills. We strive to encourage personal connections amongst the students in the Graduate College of Engineering. Furthermore, we seek to partner with professors who are looking to expand their outreach. Recently, we have helped a few professors develop outreach activities to include in the "Broader Impact" section of NSF grants. We are always looking for new opportunities to volunteer, partner with other groups, and recruit new members. 

 

We started in January of 2016, and in the past year we have grown to an organization of about 40 graduate student members. Check out our webpage below to get an idea of all of the awesome events we have hosted at local K-12 schools! 

 

In summary, the overall goal of ENVISION is two fold: 1) positively impact attitudes towards STEM in K-12 populations, in particular those underrepresented in STEM (gender, ethnicity, socio-economic) and 2) build effective and enthusiastic communicators about the value of STEM in our graduate student members.
value.Summary: ENVISION is a STEM outreach organization for graduate students at the University of Illinois.

value.Name: Engineers Without Borders, UIUC Chapter
value.Description:
Our Vision A world in which the communities we serve have the capacity to sustainably meet their basic human needs, and where our members have enriched global perspectives through their interactions with EWB-USA initiatives

Our Mission Engineers Without Borders promotes community-driven engineering projects fostered by local partners for a sustainable global future. We foster leadership and personal growth within our student members through the transformative experiences embedded in our projects.

Engineers Without Borders is an international organization which strives to develop bottom-up sustainable growth at the community level in the developing world. With over 12,000 members, and 350 projects in 45 different countries, EWB has had a profound impact on the lives of millions of people around the world. EWB-USA UIUC is one of the largest Engineers Without Borders student chapters in the USA. Founded in 2004, the chapter has grown to include three international programs in Nigeria, Guatemala and Cameroon, and over 150 active members. Although the projects constitute the heart and soul of our EWB vision, our chapter looks forward to future growth in many diverse areas. These include the development of new curriculae focused on international development through the College of Engineering, and the creation of chapter-wide workshops and training seminars. The bottom line? You don’t need to be an engineer to make a significant difference in our chapter!

Website: http://www.ewb-usa-uiuc.org

Membership Sign-Up: http://www.ewb-usa-uiuc.org/donate
value.Summary: To help disadvantaged communities improve their quality of life through implementation of environmentally and economically sustainable engineering projects, while developing internationally responsible engineering students.

value.Description: Organize graduate students, liaison between faculty and students, host Insect Fear Film Festival, community/campus outreach, recreation
value.Summary: Organize graduate students, liaison between faculty and students, host Insect Fear Film Festival, community/campus outreach, recreation

value.Name: Entrepreneurs Without Borders
value.Summary: Entrepreneurs Without Borders (EWOB) at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign focuses on using entrepreneurship as a means to address problems in subsistence marketplaces as well as enabling entrepreneurship within these communities.

value.Name: Epsilon Delta Professional Teaching Organization
value.Description:
Welcome to Epsilon Delta Professional Teaching Organization, sponsored by the College of Education at the University of Illinois at Champaign-Urbana! 

Epsilon Delta is a professional education organization on the University of Illinois campus. In addition to giving recognition to and informing its members, the organization seeks to foster an exchange of experiences and ideas among those students of education active in its meetings and events.

Specifically,  Epsilon Delta can provide you with the opportunity to:
                      · Learn more about the issues surrounding the field of education.
                      · Meet and interact with others in your field of study.
                      · Volunteer in the community.
                      · Find out important job-seeking strategies for a future career in education.
                      · Gain invaluable experiences in education related areas.
                      · Build a resource base of driven professionals in education.
                      · Receive recognition for having an involvement and interest in education.

If you would like more information, please visit our website:

www.epsilondeltauiuc.weebly.com

 

Thanks!

Ana Vancea

President of Epsilon Delta
value.Summary: To inform and involve future teachers in the changing field of education.

value.Name: Equities Group
value.Summary:
We are a group of students passionate about investing. During our sessions we present our picks and learn more about investing.
We are mostly focusing on equities, but members are free to give a presentation or pick a play outside that scope.

value.Name: Eta Kappa Nu Electrical and Computer Engineering Society
value.Description:
Eta Kappa Nu, the Electrical and Computer Engineering honor society, is a community that promotes Leadership, Scholarship, and Character through service to the ECE Department, members, and students.

We offer tutoring, review sessions, power lunches with professors, and a variety of other student services. We also host many social events throughout the semester. All service and social events are open to anybody, and are not restricted to members of Eta Kappa Nu. We work closely with the student branch of IEEE to assist the ECE deparment and the ECE community.
value.Summary: Eta Kappa Nu, the Electrical and Computer Engineering honor society, is a community that promotes Leadership, Scholarship, and Character through service to the ECE Department, members, and students.

value.Name: Etc. Coffeehouse
value.Description: This organization works to promote the Etc. Coffeehouse - a volunteer-run, donation-based coffeehouse located on campus, offering fair-trade, organic coffees and teas, the proceeds of which go to support the Wesley Food Pantry and its efforts to fight hunger in our community. Group members oversee the logistics of running the coffeehouse, and plan programs and events meant to enrich campus life, including music/open mic nights, poetry slams, trivia/game nights, holiday theme parties, and opportunities for domestic and international students to make friends and to learn about one another’s cultures.
value.Summary: This organization works to promote the Etc. Coffeehouse - a volunteer-run, donation-based campus coffeehouse offering fair-trade, organic coffees and teas, the proceeds of which go to support the Wesley Food Pantry and its efforts to fight hunger.

value.Name: Eternity to Express
value.Description:
This RSO wants to use creative arts as a means of expression for the campus and community. We want to incorporate dance, video, drama and music and other arts to share about life and the world.

Our hope is to gather like-minded people who have a passion for creative arts in hopes to connect with college students and this community. Our bigger vision is to connect with other colleges and share this passion.
value.Summary: This RSO wants to use creative arts as a means of expression for the campus and community. We want to incorporate dance, video, drama and music and other arts to share about life and the world.

value.Summary: The University of Illinois Chapter of European Horizons, a student-run non-partisan think-tank based at Yale University.

value.Name: Evangelical Christian Union
value.Description: To promote unity among all organizations of similar interests at UIUC.
value.Summary: To promote unity among all organizations of similar interests at UIUC.

value.Name: Events@UI
value.Description: Events@UI Studio is a hybrid form of a social media channel, a communication consulting service and software development for Chinese population in C-U area. We manage a WeChat account (major Chinese social media) with 1,700 Champaign-Urbana Chinese users, providing information about events, culture and food, student course reviews and so forth. We also offer strategic insights, customizable content development for non-profit organizations and local businesses sponsors to better communicate with UIUC Chinese community. Furthermore, we are developing a software platform that helps student make informed choices academically and professionally.
value.Summary: Events@UI Studio is a hybrid form of a social media channel, a communication consulting service and software development for Chinese population in C-U area.

value.Name: FACES
value.Description:
About Us

FACES is the first RSO dedicated to international students who want to pursue a career in the consulting industry. We are open to international students from all majors and all nations. Our main goal is to provide members with professional transferable skills that are attractive to recruiters. We bring the finest and most creative minds of the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign to help our members reach their career goals.


We emphasize the development of critical thinking and problem solving skills through our consulting team, which has the potential to operate in various industries. Also, we are always excited to bring together all international students through our cultural events team to make the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign a home away from home.

Our Mission

Prepare members through practical applications to become exceptional job candidates with professional skills and critical thinking.

Objectives

  1. Guide members into developing job skills through practical applications.
  2. Create more opportunities for international students to learn about companies and network with employers
  3. Create a community that fosters professional and cultural growth
value.Summary: FACES is the first RSO dedicated to international students who want to pursue a career in the consulting industry. Our main goal is to provide members with professional transferable skills that are attractive to recruiters.

value.Name: Faithful Leaders Of Worship
value.Description:
Studies show that over 80% of college students leave the faith, or rebel against Christianity once on college campuses.  Faithful Leaders of Worship (or F.L.O.W.) are acting as the light on these college campuses in order to lead their peers back to God and out of the darkness.  This means that through all of the persecution or negative feedback that these students may endure for standing up for Christ, these leaders will continue to peacefully push forth the message of Jesus Christ in order to reach students on campus.

FAITHFUL LEADERS OF WORSHIP (aka F.L.O.W.) is a non-profit organization of leaders that help cultivate the walk in Christ through mental, emotional and spiritual development.  This will take effect through a series of fellowship events, bible studies, and community service lead by the organization.  F.L.O.W.’s target audience is currently (but not limited to) college students between the ages 18-22.  This organization was founded in September of 2014 by Rev. Willie G. Comer Jr. at Berean Covenant Church, located in Champaign, IL.
value.Summary: FAITHFUL LEADERS OF WORSHIP (aka F.L.O.W.) is a non-profit organization of leaders that helps cultivate the walk in Christ through mental, emotional and spiritual development.

value.Name: Falling Illini
value.Summary: Join for major discounts on all jumps!  Whether you are an experienced jumper, someone looking to cross skydiving off your bucket list, or anything in-between, the Falling Illini is for you!

value.Name: Falun Dafa at UIUC
value.Description: Bring the wonderfulness of Falun Dafa to students, faculty, and staff, and people in the community.
value.Summary: Bring the wonderfulness of Falun Dafa to students, faculty, and staff, and people in the community.

value.Name: Family Housing Council
value.Summary: The main purpose of Family Housing Council is to create more opportunities for all the residents living in Orchard Downs to meet and know, and help them to learn more about UIUC and live better.

value.Name: Family Support Services Outreach Council
value.Description: Family Support Services Outreach Council is for University of Illinois students to provide support for families by facilitating workshops associated with academic success for middle school and high school students while partnering with Family Support Services of CU. We will provide support through tutoring, mentoring and coaching. Our overall goal is to help students build academic and life skills essential to succeed.
value.Summary: Enthusiastic individuals with a passion for helping others. We collaborate to provide social and academic support for young students through tutoring, mentoring and coaching while encouraging each student to reach their potential.

value.Name: FarmHouse Fraternity
value.Description: Building the Whole Man...intectually, spritually, socially & morally, and physically.
value.Summary: Building the Whole Man...intectually, spritually, socially & morally, and physically.

value.Name: Federal Bureau of Investigation Springfield Citizens' Academy Alumni Association - Students' Academy
value.Description:
The Students' Academy is a certification program run by students at the University of Illinois and the Federal Bureau of Investigation in Springfield, IL for the purpose of spreading awareness of the FBI's mission, goals, history, and internal workings, and giving students the opportunity to ask questions and have discussions with the FBI firsthand. 

The Campus academy was created based on the FBI CREST program, standing for "Community Relations Executive Seminar Training". CREST serves as a means to exchange information between the FBI and the participating communities. Through this exchange, problems affecting communities will be identified and addressed and the community will learn about the work of the FBI. 

This program is a series of seminars focused towards a college student body on different topics of the FBI. Each seminar will be run by a special agent of associate director specializing and directly involved in that field.
value.Summary: FBI Springfield - C3ASA is a pre-professional program for the purpose of spreading awareness of the FBI's mission, goals, and internal workings as well as answering community concerns for the FBI. Membership requires attending 8-10 seminars.

value.Name: Federalist Society for Law & Public Policy Studies
value.ShortName: Federalist Society for Law & Public Policy Studies
value.Description: The Federalist Society for Law and Public Policy Studies is a group of conservatives and libertarians interested in the current state of the legal order.  It is founded on the principles that the state exists to preserve freedom, that the separation of governmental powers is central to our Constitution, and that it is emphatically the province and duty of the judiciary to say what the law is, not what it should be.  The Society seeks both to promote an awareness of these principles and to further their application through its activities.
value.Summary: A conservative and libertarian organization for students in the College of Law and the campus at large who are concerned about the current state of the legal order.

value.Name: Fellowship of Catholic University Students
value.Description: To teach and to live the message of Christ through small group Catholic Bible Studies, one-on-one Discipleship, and large group social events.
value.Summary: To teach and to live the message of Christ through small group Catholic Bible Studies, one-on-one Discipleship, and large group social events.

value.Name: Fellowship of Christian Athletes
value.Description: To present to coaches and athletes and all they influence the challenge and adventure of receiving Jesus Christ as savior and lord.
value.Summary: To present to coaches and athletes and all they influence the challenge and adventure of receiving Jesus Christ as savior and lord.

value.Name: Fencing Illini
value.Description: To provide a club resource where university students can both learn to fence and have access to a competitive conference with other collegiate teams and clubs, both in the Midwest and nationally.
value.Summary: To provide a club resource where university students can both learn the sport of fencing and have access to a competitive conference with other collegiate teams and clubs, both in the Midwest and nationally.

value.Name: Field and Furrow Agronomy Club
value.Description: The purpose of the Field and Furrow Club is to inform and expose its members to every aspect of agriculture, and supply them with the leadership skills needed to be a success. The club is not limited to any certain major, yet it strives and wants to gather and incorporate students of other majors to become a well rounded and diversified agricultural club. The club is open to any person of any major who would like to broaden or enhance their knowledge of agriculture. The club welcomes any interested students to come to a meeting anytime and see what the club is about.
value.Summary: The purpose of the Field and Furrow Club is to inform and expose its members to every aspect of agriculture, and supply them with the leadership skills needed to be a success. The club is not limited to any certain major.

value.Name: Finance Club
value.Description:
The Finance Club is the premier finance organization at the University of Illinois.  We’re a student-led club that focuses on providing our members opportunities for professional, service, and social development.  Our members are University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign students from all colleges and majors.

Our mission is to give University of Illinois students outstanding opportunities in all areas and realms of finance.  We do this by combining professional, academic, and extracurricular experiences to create well rounded members.
value.Summary: The Finance Club is the premier finance organization at the University of Illinois.  We’re a student-led club that focuses on providing our members opportunities for professional, service, and social development.

value.Name: Financial Engineering Club
value.Description: To promote the understanding of financial engineering and to explore the career opportunities available by inviting corporate speakers.
value.Summary: As part of the Financial Engineering Club (FEC) you will be exposed to methods, tools, and ideas behind derivatives. FEC will provide educational seminars as well as opportunities to meet professionals from the industry. All majors are welcome.

value.Name: Financial Planning Club
value.Description: The Financial Planning Club is designed to be a useful resource for all students of any major or concentration that are interested in learning about the career path of a financial planner. The course accomplishes this objective in a variety of ways while working in conjunction with the College of ACES consumer economics department to provide students the very best opportunities. Some of the ways the club accomplishes this initiative is through developmental course on a variety of topics ranging from building your brand to providing reading lists of pertinent industry literature, arranging internship and job opportunities and even mentoring and job shadowing. The end goal of the club is to make our members not only more knowledgeable on the many facets of becoming a financial advisor, but also to make them more competitive as a candidate once they enter the field.
value.Summary: An organization meant to provide students interested in the financial planning field the opportunity to meet with financial planning professionals, job shadowing opportunities, internship opportunities, and continuing education content.

value.Name: Fitness for the Ages
value.Description: Fitness for the Ages is a student organization at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign that promotes physical activity for individuals across all stages of life. To support our mission, we travel to local assisted living facilities, youth after-school programs, and preschools to lead them in various forms of exercise and teach them the importance of physical activity for their health because fitness never gets old!
value.Summary: Our mission is to provide the elderly and youth with physical fitness in order to promote their bone strength, reduce stress and help prevent the onset of disease. We will achieve this through regular sessions of activity because fitness never gets old!

value.Name: Fizaa
value.Description: We are focused on displaying Indian culture through various styles of dance. Fizaa's purpose is to maintain the Indian cultural traditions of dance, music, and drama as well as to create more cultural awareness for our fellow students and community. Our foremost efforts are directed towards performing at collegiate and inter-collegiate national dance competitions as well as at on-campus events.
value.Summary: Fizaa, a completely student-run, nonprofit organization, was founded in 2008 and is the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign's very own Bollywood Fusion Dance Team.

value.Name: Flashpoint Photography Club
value.Description: This is a student-run organization with the goal of bringing together creative people to collaborate and learn about photography. We welcome photographers and enthusiasts of all skill levels with or without a camera. We plan on talking about basic photography and editing principles as well as going out on group photo shoots.
value.Summary: A fun, inviting, collaborative group of aspiring photographers of all skill levels. Master new skills, improve your current abilities, and learn everything there is to know about photography!

value.Name: Flippin' Illini Gymnastics Club
value.Description: Flippin' Illini is a gymnastics club at the University of Illinois that gives peoples the opportunity to continue gymnastics in college or start learning for the first time. No experience is necessary.   Our main goal is to have fun with a sport we love and meet new people.
value.Summary: "For the Love of the Sport"

value.Description:
Floor Lovers Illinois (FLI) is dedicated to spreading the art/culture of Hip-Hop through one of its 4 elements-breaking aka breakdancing. We hold competitions every semester and have beginner workshops throughout the year.

 

Open to all ages and gender with a willingness to learn.

No experiences necessary.
value.Summary:
Floor Lovers Illinois (FLI) is dedicated to spreading the art/culture of Hip-Hop through one of its 4 elements-breaking aka breakdancing.
 
Open to all ages and gender with a willingness to learn.

value.Name: Flow Arts Club
value.Description: This is an opportunity for everyone at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign to learn and grow together by coming together and practicing flow arts. This includes hooping, gloving, poi, or any other flow toys! Even if you do not flow already and want to learn you are more than welcome to join! We will get together on a weekly basis and practice and build off of each other.
value.Summary: This is an opportunity for everyone at the university to learn and grow together by coming together and practicing flow arts. This includes hooping, gloving, poi, or any other flow toys! Even if you do not flow already and would like to learn you can!

value.Name: Folk and Roots Club
value.Description:
This club will provide a place for students, faculty, and staff to engage in the art of playing folk, bluegrass, blues, Americana, and roots music. We accept musicians of all skill levels (including first-time pickers) who are interested in joining. The Pickin' Illini's purpose is to take people back to where music started, where history came from, and to keep these genres alive by playing music and performing for the community.

We meet in the Union every Wednesday from 8 PM to 9:30 PM. Our room assignment is variable this year, so please get in touch via email or Facebook for more info. All instruments and skill levels are welcome to attend and jam with us.

We also host workshops for anyone at the University who would like to learn more about their instrument, and provide a place for people to get together and jam with others who share their passion for folk and roots styles. Overall this organization will be a fun way to perform, network, and develop as a singer or musician.
value.Summary: The goal of this club is to get students of the university to discover and get involved with folk and roots music by playing traditional instruments (guitar, banjo, resonator, ukulele, mandolin, bass etc.) and performing around campus and town.

value.Name: Food Preservation Club
value.Description: Founded by several driven food science students, the Food Preservation Club welcomes all students and faculties who are interested in the science and art of preserving foods -- from canning to fermentation, and everything in between. In club meetings, we share credible information about the tradition of different preserving methods, as well as the scientific reasons and necessary precautions when experimenting with foods; after the introduction, in small groups club members will make the products in a kitchen themselves.
value.Summary: The Food Preservation Club aims to bring the methods of food preservation to interested students and faculties with both practical and theoretical approach.

value.Name: Food Product Development Club
value.Description: Provide students pursuing food industry related study an opportunity to participate in food industry product development competitions.
value.Summary: Provide students pursuing food industry related study an opportunity to participate in food industry product development competitions.

Welcome New Graduate Students! – will be hosted by the networking committee. FSHN facility/ laboratory tour, student speed networking, and a welcome party to introduce faculty will be held for our new friends!

 

FSHN Pioneer Seminar Series – will be organized by the Vice President. Monthly seminar given by FSHN faculty members with free lunch in an informal environment inspires brilliant ideas with great collaborations!

 

FSHN Professional Development Series – will be hosted by the Professional Development Co-Chairs. Interact with industry professionals and learn their experiences through panel discussions and fun activities!

FSHNGSA is an association run by FSHN graduate students to increase the interaction among faculty and graduate students by providing social, academic, and career related events.

value.Name: Food Science and Human Nutrition Mentor Club
value.Description: The purpose of this club is to inform food science and human nutrition students about internships, research, careers, and opportunities related to their field. Furthermore, the club will offer students guidance about classes, resumes, and the James Scholar Program. This club is unique because it allows FSHN students from all different concentrations to come together and get the guidance and information they need in order to have a successful academic career at U of I.
