value.Name: For Art's Sake
value.Description:
For Art's Sake is an organization which serves lovers of art. Anyone interested in art history, art theory, film studies, architecture history, new media, criticism, etc. is welcome, regardless of major or background. We are happy to serve as educators for those new to art history and as a community for seasoned historians.

We will provide a space for intelligent, insightful conversation as well as activities to extend and practice your understanding of art. We plan to use ambitious fieldwork to discover new methods of expression.
value.Summary: Love the arts? Excited about art history and theory? For Art's Sake serves those interested in intelligent, insightful conversation on all forms of art, from film to architecture.

value.Name: Formosa Volleyball Enthusiasts
value.Description: FVE was started by Tawanese students, and later combined with Chinese students and other Asian students. We attend intramural volleyball tournaments in the forms of men, women, and co-ed teams. We also attend out-of-campus tournaments in St.Louis, Chicago, or Purdue University. By participating in these tournaments every year, we not only play more competitive volleyball games, but also establish networks through knowing more people. We have regular plays every week on Wednesday 9-11pm and Saturday 3pm-5pm. Any volleyball lovers are welcome to join our club.
value.Summary: We are a group of enthusiastic volleyball players from Taiwan, China, Hong Kong, Malaysia and Vietnam. We participate in tournaments in and out of campus and establish friendly games with clubs from other schools to promote interactions between schools

value.Name: Foundation for International Medical Relief of Children - UIUC Chapter
value.Description: A global non-profit organization dedicated to improving the lives of children worldwide, FIMRC provides medical support and health education for underprivileged and medically underserved children. FIMRC organizes international medical mission trips for UIUC students and also organizes weekly volunteering events in the Champaign-Urbana community to ensure both a global, and local focus to service.
value.Summary: FIMRC is a global non-profit organization dedicated to improving the lives of children worldwide. FIMRC accomplishes this goal by providing medical support and health education for underprivileged and medically underserved children around the world.

value.Name: Founders - Illinois Entrepreneurs
value.Description: Founders is a new unifying student entrepreneurship organization at Illinois. Our mission is to expose students to entrepreneurship and foster a growing Illinois entrepreneurial community. We hold events to help students get their own ideas going, find awesome jobs at incredible startups, and more!
value.Summary: Founders is a unifying student entrepreneurship organization at Illinois. Our mission is to expose students to entrepreneurship and foster a growing Illinois entrepreneurial community.

value.Name: Fragrance Experiment Club
value.Description:
The popularity of "layering" has increased significantly over the recent years. In modern society "layering" includes clothing, accesories and hairstyle. The concept of layering allows people to express multiple emotions through layers of clothing and accesories. Perfume is a new emerging field of interest as many find "perfume layering" a good method of self expression. 

The ultimate purpose of this organization is to explore, learn and develop different fragrances. The organization will serve as a bridge for people who are interested in this field to connect, allowing them to mature their understanding of fragrances.
value.Summary: The primary purpose of this organization is to teach and learn about different fragrances including perfume layering, perfume mixing and perfume making. We will also teach the science behind fragrances and how different scents are achieved.

value.Name: Friends of Student Union
value.Description:
The GEO works to find common ground among all graduate employees, regardless of race, gender, religion, disability, sexual orientation, citizenship status, department, job category, or membership in the union. Membership in the GEO is, and will remain, voluntary.


The GEO strives to be inclusive and open to all graduate employees, operate along democratic principles, act always in the best interests of graduate employees, and act responsibly toward the entire university community.


What We Work for as a Union
By bargaining with the university administration in good faith, toward mutually agreeable improvements to employment policies and benefits for graduate employees, we hope to achieve the following:

  • Grievance Procedure: GEO seeks a written and widely publicized procedure for resolution of employment problems. The procedure should be multi-step, protect employees from retaliation, give employees the option of union representation, and include the right to appeal to a neutral arbitrator to make binding decisions.
  • Workload: the GEO and the university administration should cooperate in addressing the problem of unreasonable workloads in certain departments and move toward greater consistency of workloads across departments. Unpaid job duties should be phased out. However, the union will not seek to limit the right of graduate employees to choose for themselves the time and manner of their work, only to rectify problems of overwork identified by graduate employees.
  • Health Care: The University should waive the student health insurance plan and McKinley fees for graduate employees. The GEO and the University should work together to improve health care so that it more closely serves the needs of the graduate employee population, and includes such things as a choice of plans and affordable plans for spouses, dependents and domestic partners.
  • International Employees: The GEO will work for policies that address the specific employment concerns of international graduate employees. The union and the university administration should work together to find creative responses to rules that limit international students to 50% appointments and therefore makes pay increases difficult or limit the types of appointments non-citizens can take.
  • Stipends: The University should continue improving the stipends of all graduate employees both by increasing the minimum stipend and providing regular cost of living raises. No employee or category of employees should receive a pay cut or freeze in order to fund pay increases for others. The union will not seek pay caps or limits on departments’ ability to offer higher salaries.
  • A Good Work Environment for All: Recognizing that a work environment free from hostility and discrimination is a necessary prerequisite for improving the quality of education and research at the UI, the GEO will work to strengthen and enforce university policies against discrimination and sexual harassment.
  • Tuition Waivers: The University should restore full tuition waivers for all graduate employees regardless of program status. Employees with less than 25% FTE appointments should receive partial waivers. Graduate hourly employees whose work exceeds 10 hours a week on average should receive a full waiver.
  • Paid Training: Graduate employees new to an assistantship should receive paid job training. If a graduate employee’s job description includes work in hazardous settings (which include, e.g., exposure to chemical, radiation, or biological hazards), the employee should be paid to attend formal safety training programs.
  • Family Issues: The GEO is committed to making affordable child care a goal of the University and supports University subsidized child care for all employees. The GEO and the University administration should work together to establish a feasible child care plan for graduate employees with children.
  • Workplace Safety: The University will observe all applicable laws and regulations regarding workplace safety. No employee should be forced to work under conditions that violate safety laws. GEO representatives should serve on all University and Departmental committees on workplace safety.
value.Summary: The FLU is the identical twin of GEO. GEO works to find common ground among all graduate employees, regardless of race, gender, religion, disability, sexual orientation, citizenship status, department, job category, or membership in the union

value.Name: Fulbright Student Association
value.Description:
The Fulbright Student Association promotes Academic excellence and development of leadership potential among its members. It seeks to foster international understanding in a framework of cultural and educational exchange.
 
The association also serves as a mutual support network among Fulbright Alumni and Faculty, and it aims to provide assistance and support in Urbana Champaign for visiting Fulbrghters.

The FSA engages current and former Fulbright exchange participants at UIUC in lifelong experiences that advance international understanding through dialogue, cultural exchange and professional and personal growth activities for its participants.
value.Summary: The FSA engages current and former Fulbright exchange participants at UIUC in lifelong experiences that advance international understanding through dialogue, cultural exchange and professional and personal growth activities for its participants.

value.Name: FUSE
value.Description: An organization focusing on Queer Students of Color and their experiences. A safe place to create community and learn from one another
value.Summary: Branching from the original group Infusions, Fuse, serves the purpose of creating a space for queer folks of color

value.Name: Fusion
value.Description: To help business students connect with the resources of alumni, faculty, and peers within the College of Business. Host mentorship programs where members get to learn how to improve their skills (ex: Communication, Soft skills, LinkedIn Profile). Network with companies to learn more about opportunities they have available. Connect with faculty to talk about their experience in school/work.
value.Summary: To connect business students to resources of alumni, faculty, and peers within the College of Business. Provide opportunities to students to pave their path to success.

value.Name: Future Health Care Executives
value.Description: To be the professional membership society for future health care executives; to meet its members' professional, educational, and leadership needs; to promote high ethical standards and conduct; and to advance health care leadership and management excellence.  FHCE aids members in furthering their knowledge and exposure to the health care field.  Through guest speakers , graduate school representation, and networking, we adequately prepare all members for a successful career in health care.
value.Summary: To be the professional membership society for future health care executives; to meet its members' professional, educational, and leadership needs; to promote high ethical standards and conduct; and to advance health care leadership and management

value.Name: Future Physicians of Applied Health Scienes
value.Description: Future Physicians of AHS, is a brand-new organization on campus that intends to unite bright minds alike, currently on the pre-medicine path in the college of Applied Health Sciences. FP-AHS’s development resulted from a communal feeling that those in AHS and on the pre-medicine path have never been recognized or given the same resources or support from professors and others around them. We encourage those majoring in Kinesiology, Community Health, Interdisciplinary Health Sciences, and highly encourage those who are not in AHS to come and explore our mind-set and approach to medicine.
value.Summary: The Future Physicians of Applied Health Sciences RSO intends to unite bright minds in the college of AHS to reach their path in creating a career in medicine

value.Name: Gah Rahk Mah Dahng
value.Description: GRMD(Gah Rahk Mah Dahng) is a performance group at UIUC for  the style of traditional Korean percussion called Samulnori. The goal of this group is to spread Korean culture through our percussion music.
value.Summary: GRMD(Gah Rahk Mah Dahng) is a performance group at UIUC for  the style of traditional Korean percussion called Samulnori. The goal of this group is to spread Korean culture through our percussion music.

value.Name: Galvanizing A New Generation
value.Description: Galvanizing A New Generation (G.A.N.G.) is an organization dedicated to Black and other minority students from various backgrounds with the aim of collaborating in efforts to bring awareness to issues that cater to our demographic, and serving the local communities in Champaign-Urbana through volunteer work and programs. We plan on addressing issues such as academic retention, lack of proper black/latinx advocacy in education systems, discrimination against minorities within society, addressing socioeconomic disparities, islamophobia and more. Members of G.A.N.G. will become engaged in serving the local communities by leading and participating in various community service efforts, such as volunteering at local food pantries, homeless shelters, and more. G.A.N.G.’s primary goals are (1) to unify black and brown students on the University of Illinois campus, (2) to promote awareness of critical matters that impact our communities, (3) to organize and develop real solutions to these issues, and (4) to make a positive impact on the local UIUC community, not just limited to students, through community service. The values of G.A.N.G. include (but are not limited to) activism, advocacy, expression, guidance, service, and inclusion. We emphasize the significance of the inclusion of all peoples of various identities and backgrounds. We also believe in the importance of social responsibility and our contribution to not only our communities, but the University of Illinois’ student community overall.
value.Summary: Galvanizing A New Generation (G.A.N.G.) is an org dedicated to minority students from various backgrounds with the aim of collaborating in efforts to bring awareness to issues that cater to our demographic and serving our local communities.

value.Name: Game Night
value.Description: Game Night gathers twice a month to unplug from electronics and play a variety of games.  Game Night gives everyone a chance to explore new and different games.  We unplug, hangout, and engage in various games and discuss the gameplay.  We play a large range of games from Capture the Flag to Uno and everything in between.  The games played during Game Night will adjust based on interest and weather (i.e. Playing Capture the Flag on ice is painful).
value.Summary: Unplug and meet other game lovers.  Cards, board games, mystery and adventure games, outdoor games, and more.  Bring your favorite and introduce it to everyone.

value.Name: Gamma Phi Beta Sorority
value.Description: We strive to foster a nurturing environment that provides women the opportunity to achieve their potential through life-long commitment to intellectual growth, individual worth and service to humanity.
value.Summary: We strive to foster a nurturing environment that provides women the opportunity to achieve their potential through life-long commitment to intellectual growth, individual worth and service to humanity.

value.Name: Gamma Phi Omega International Sorority, Inc.
value.Description:
Gamma Phi Omega International Sorority, Inc. unites women in the principles of achieving academic excellence, serving the communities in which we live and learn, preserving the sacred bond of sisterhood among women, and advancing a cultural awareness among Latinos and those in our global communities.

"We are gorgeous, as represented most importantly by our intellectual abilities. We are presitigous by achieving and transcending standards of excellence. And, we are original in our thinking."

 

Living by our four goals:

Academic Excellence

Maintain exemplary scholastic standards by motivating and stimulating  academic achievements. 

Community Service

Collaborate with surrounding communities to positively create awareness and sponsorship to local and global causes.

Cultural Awareness

Promote and display an understanding of international diversities and various lifestyles; especially within the Latino community. 

Sisterhood

Unite women through the loving spirit of friendship with a shared respect and support system.
value.Summary: Gamma Phi Omega International Sorority, Inc. is a Latina-oriented sorority founded in 1991. Our organization revolves around academic excellence, community service, cultural awareness and sisterhood. "Unity & Sisterhood, Now & Forever, One & Inseparable"

value.Name: Gender and Women's Studies Student Organization
value.Description:
The goal of the Gender and Women's Studies Student Organization is to create a network in which students from all disciplines can come together and discuss ideas, professional goals, and interests regarding gender, women and sexuality. This organization is open to undergraduate and graduate students interested in the interdisciplinary field of gender and women's studies. We aim to provide a supportive space in which individuals can discuss academic, professional, as well as social goals. We aim to create awareness of issues concerning gender and women's studies on our campus as well as in our community. This organization is open to all individuals regardless of race, religion, biological sex, gender identity, or sexuality.

 

Feel free to contact us for more information!
value.Summary: The goal of the Gender and Women's Studies Student Organization is to create a network in which students from all disciplines can come together and discuss ideas, professional goals, and interests regarding gender, women and sexuality.

Our mission is to develop the leadership potential, entrepreneurial spirit and professional abilities of young girls through building confidence, knowledge and creating opportunity. Through directed professional leadership training, we give young girls the foundation they need to bridge that gap and use their voice as an avenue to advocate. Facilitated by volunteer coaches, GGFI's curriculum is focused on self-confidence, empowerment, challenges women face, entrepreneurship, and career building.

value.Name: Global Business Brigades at the University of Illinois
value.Description: Global Business Brigades (GBB) is a University of Illinois RSO within the College of Business' Council of Presidents. GBB provides a unique combination of international philanthropic experiences, coupled with applicable financial advisory skills. Our members prepare for week-long trips to Honduras in January and Panama in March, to educate families and small businesses about financial literacy. This includes business topics such as credit, loans, cooperatives, personal financing, and basic accounting. The experience provides students with an opportunity to utilize the skills they have obtained from their business curriculum, making an impact on the lives of dozens of Honduran and Panamanian citizens.  The week spent in Honduras or Panama with GBB, further develops our member’s professional skill set and offers the opportunity to make a real and tangible difference in the global community.
value.Summary: Global Business Brigades (GBB) is a University of Illinois RSO within the College of Business. GBB provides a unique combination of international philanthropic experiences, coupled with applicable  financial advisory skills. Visit us at www.uiucgbb.com.

value.ShortName: Global Medical Brigades at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign
value.Description: Global Brigades is an international non-profit that uniquely implements a holistic model to enable the Empowered 100 model of the organization, which is striving to pull 100 communities out of poverty through sustainable intervention over the course of the next 5 years. Global Medical and Dental Brigades empowers its members through international travel to provide free primary health and dental care to underserved regions of rural Honduras, Nicaragua, Panama, and Ghana.
value.Summary: Global Medical Brigades is a secular, non-profit network of university clubs and volunteer organizations that travel to developing countries. We are a grass roots movement all over North America working in concert to provide medical relief and health.

value.Name: Global Medical Training
value.Description:
Global Medical Training (GMT) is an international, non-profit, and humanitarian organization that provides free medical, dental, and veterinary services in developing communities in parts of Central America and Mexico. Students are given the unique chance to directly participate in “hands-on” diagnoses and treatments under the supervision of medical professionals. This is the reason why our motto is “LEARN BY DOING.”

As a health-focused organization, our main purpose is to increase awareness of the lack of healthcare in third world countries by giving undergraduate students the chance to expand their understanding of life and medicine outside the United States. This is made possible by educating and exposing students to the prevalent global and medical issues that many underserved communities in developing countries face. Such issues include poverty, poor national health-care systems, and the various circumstances that contribute to and perpetuate a specific population’s situation.

GMT also understands there are major health issues that reside right in our own community. It is this very reason why we also offer our students the opportunity to volunteer in various community service events including free health fairs servicing the underprivileged in the Los Angeles and surrounding counties.

Altogether, GMT views student volunteers as a vital force for change.  After all, they may be the next generation of health-care providers. Therefore, their education, training, and exposure to such issues are an integral part of GMT’s mission for a sustainable future.
value.Summary: Global Medical Training is an International Humanitarian Organization that provides free medical and dental services to medically deprived communities in Central American countries.

value.Name: Graduate Women in the Society of Women Engineers
value.Description:
The mission of GradSWE is to promote diversity in graduate education in engineering and science to enable innovative and creative solutions to the future technical challenges of society.

Engineers and scientists contribute to the betterment of society by identifying and solving technical problems. The development and distribution of clean water, medical imaging, and the Internet are just a few highlights of engineering and scientific breakthroughs that have improved lives. With the advancement of technology, the future challenges facing society are becoming increasingly complex, and their solutions will require an innovative workforce that is diverse in its education, gender, culture, age, etc. For example, to accomplish the National Academy of Engineering’s Grand Challenge to engineer personalized medicine, people of many different backgrounds must work together to ensure no groups’ needs are overlooked. GradSWE advocates for women in graduate education so that they can confidently excel at the frontier of scientific advancement. A diverse and balanced workforce of individuals with M.S. and Ph.D. degrees is necessary to tackle society’s biggest challenges with innovation and creativity, and GradSWE strives to make this workforce a reality.

GradSWE is a support community and advocate for graduate women in engineering and for undergraduate women interested in pursing graduate studies in engineering. We encourage women to pursue graduate school, support them throughout their graduate education, and help prepare them for their future careers after they complete their degree. GradSWE provides events that cater to the needs of graduate students and undergraduate students interested in pursuing graduate school, some of which are listed below:

Graduate professional and academic development workshops

The backbone of GradSWE is to support the professional and academic development of graduate students at the University of Illinois. Our workshop topics address the issues facing graduate including:

 

  • Effective presentations and public speaking
  • Funding options for graduate education
  • Resume writing
  • Career paths for graduate degrees
  • Individualized career planning
  • Health and wellness

Graduate social events

All members of GradSWE know that networking and social interaction is an important and fun part of grad school! GradSWE members are encouraged to bring their friends and family to our social events, like weekend BBQs, potlucks and the Barn Dance with SWE!

Undergraduate academic development workshops

GradSWE stays connected to the undergraduate SWE section by organizing academic development events for undergraduate students. We encourage undergraduate women to consider graduate school through events like the Why Grad School Panel, Undergrad Decision Making Panel, and the Advanced Degrees Workshop.
value.Summary: GradSWE is a support community and advocate for graduate women in engineering and for undergraduate women interested in pursing graduate studies in engineering.

value.Name: Growth International Volunteer Excursions at UIUC
value.Description: GIVE at UIUC seeks members that are eager to work on and/or help support sustainable development projects that are designed to make a lasting difference through improving infrastructure, increasing educational opportunities, implementing fresh water systems and protecting endangered wildlife. These students ultimately embody the characteristics of GIVE's international volunteers, who partner closely with host communities in Central America, Africa, and Southeast Asia to drive these changes. GIVE at UIUC will carry out GIVE's mission locally through community service, fundraisers, and culturally immersive activities, encouraging our members to reflect on life in the developing world and their own lives. These activities will empower them to embark on GIVE excursions abroad where they are constantly immersed in meaningful projects, interactions with host communities and unforgettable adventures. This leads to the development of lifelong memories and friendships, both among volunteers and local community members. Past volunteers who have harnessed their engagement will have the opportunity inform students on how to become sustainable development leaders upon their return home.
value.Summary: GIVE at UIUC works to inspire growth, empower global citizens, and ignite sustainable change world wide & locally through community service, fundraisers, culturally immersive activities, and reflections on their lives & life in the developing world.

value.Name: Guidance for Physics Students
value.Description:
GPS is inspired by similar student-initiated physics education programs on other campuses, such as the Berkeley Compass Project (http://www.berkeleycompassproject.org/) and ASU Sundial Project (http://sundial.physics.asu.edu/).

----------------------

Why "GPS"?
More and more of us carry around in our pockets a tiny device that represents one of the most remarkable applications of physics and engineering to our daily lives. When needed, this device calls on a network of satellites which, because of their onboard atomic clocks that are accurate to about 1 second in every 2 million years, and because of our understanding of the effects of special and general relativity, are able to pinpoint our location to within a few meters from 20,000 km away. Our interactions with this technology are usually pretty quick and mundane, but without us really thinking about it, it quietly keeps us going where we'd like to go.
Sorry, we got distracted. The point is, "GPS" stands for "Guidance for Physics Students."
value.Summary: We are a group of graduate and undergraduate students within the UIUC physics department looking to improve our scientific community through grad-undergrad mentorship, social activities, and programs designed to make our department feel more connected.

value.Name: Habitat for Humanity Campus Chapter
value.Description:
OUR HISTORY

HOW DID HABITAT FOR HUMANITY START?

Habitat grew out of the dedication of two visionary men: the late Clarence Jordan, founder of Koinonia Farm, a cooperative community; and Millard Fuller, a young millionaire who decided to give away his fortune and spend his life in Christian service. Together they recognized the desperate need for decent housing among the poor of southwestern Georgia and envisioned the partnership that became Habitat for Humanity International. Since its founding in 1976, Habitat has grown rapidly and now includes more than 1400 U.S. affiliates in Habitat USA and over 100 projects in 30 other countries sponsored by Habitat International. Over 100,000 Habitat houses have been built. Among Habitat's many volunteers and supporters is former President Jimmy Carter. Local organizing efforts began with a few individuals in December 1990. In December 1991, Habitat for Humanity of Champaign and Piatt Counties (HHCPC) became an official affiliate of Habitat for Humanity International. Our UIUC Student Chapter began that Spring of 1992, and became an official chapter with Habitat for Humanity International in March of 1993.

WHAT DOES HABITAT FOR HUMANITY DO?

Habitat USA and Habitat International are ecumenical Christian housing ministries that seek to eliminate poverty housing and homelessness worldwide. Everywhere we work, Habitat builds new relationships and a sense of community as well as new housing. Habitat also improves the local community by putting property back on the tax rolls and by adding life to older neighborhoods Through volunteer labor, careful management, and donations of money and materials, Habitat builds and rehabilitates simple, decent homes so they are affordable for low-income families currently living in substandard housing. Houses are sold to these partner families at cost, through no-interest mortgages. Each family's house payments go into a revolving fund to help pay for the construction of other houses. Construction of Habitat homes is a cooperative effort between volunteers and the future home owners. This reduces the cost of the home, increases the pride of ownership, and fosters the development of positive relationships.

OUR GOALS

Our University's Chapter works with the Champaign County Chapter of Habitat to end poverty housing right here in Champaign. Since starting in 1992, the students have sponsored and helped complete 8 houses. When not working on a house, the students fundraise, plan events and volunteer projects to connect with local Habitat families, and raise awareness about poverty housing. During spring break we also send trips to different states to build with Habitat.
value.Summary:
Our mission is to end substandard housing in partnership with the campus, local, and global communities by advocating, educating, fundraising, and building.

VISIT US AT UIUCHABITAT.ORG

value.Name: Haiti Clean Stove Project
value.Description:
The Haiti Clean Stove Project at the University of Illinois in Urbana-Champaign aims to implement improved cook stoves to replace charcoal and open fire cooking in Haiti. We are partnered with researchers, designers, and experts in both TLUD stoves and biochar to assist us with technical aspects, as well as a community developer to help facilitate implementation.

Besides being a major driver of deforestation in Haiti, charcoal is expensive and its emissions are detrimental to health and the environment. Using improved cookstoves, Haitians can expect to consume up to 50% less fuel - a significant savings since charcoal accounts for 40% of many Haitian's incomes. These stoves dramatically reduce emissions of carbon monoxide and particulate matter as well. As an added benefit, many improved cookstoves produce biochar, which when added as a soil amendment can enhance crop yields and sequester carbon dioxide.
value.Summary: The Haiti Clean Stove Project at the University of Illinois in Urbana-Champaign aims to design and implement improved clean cookstoves to replace charcoal cooking in Haiti.

value.Name: Higher Education Student Association
value.Description: The Higher Education Students Association (HESA) at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign is an academic, professional, and social organization established to: 1) facilitate the academic progress of students enrolled in the University of Illinois Higher Education Program, 2) act as a forum for the discussion of issues, current events, and research related to Higher Education, 3) promote the professional development of its students, and 4) provide a focal point for social gatherings and events.
value.Summary: The Higher Education Students Association (HESA) at UIUC is an academic, professional, and social organization established to facilitate the academic progress of students enrolled in the Education, Policy and Organization Program.

value.Name: Hillel Student Board
value.Description: Hillel's mission is to enrich the lives of Jewish undergraduate and graduate students so that they may enrich the Jewish people and the world.  Hillel seeks to create a pluralistic, welcoming and inclusive environment for Jewish college students: an environment where students are encouraged to grow intellectually, spiritually and socially.  Hillel helps students find their own balance in being distinctively Jewish and universally human.  It does this by providing opportunities to pursue tzedek (social justice); helping students to engage with critical Jewish issues in the US, Israel and around the world through experiences in Israel, Eastern Europe and helping to "repair the world" (tikkun olam).  Hillel encourages Jewish learning and celebration and provides students with an opportunity to explore culture and the arts.  The Hillels of Illinois creates a variety of ways that students can advocate for and support Jews in Israel and around the world.  Hillel seeks to inspire every Jewish student to find their own approach to making an enduring commitment to Jewish life.
value.Summary: We envision a world where every student is inspired to make an enduring commitment to Jewish life, learning and Israel.

value.Name: Hindu Students Council
value.Description:
HSC is an international forum providing opportunities for college students and young professionals to learn about Hindu heritage through various activities, events and projects. Hindu Students Council was formed in 1990 by three college students who saw a need for Hindu representation on campuses. We want to open a chapter at UIUC to foster a more accurate representation of Hinduism, providing a reliable student network.

HSC’s vision is to inspire the development of an “integrated personality” based upon the spiritual and cultural treasures of Hindu heritage. An integrated Hindu personality is the amalgamation of the highest Hindu values and the best western cultural values, and enables the youth to be spiritual, ethical, caring and socially adept citizens.

Our HSC Mission is four-fold:
1. Provide opportunities to learn about Hindu heritage and culture
2. Provide and promote awareness of issues affecting Hindus
3. Provide SEVA (service) to the community
4. Provide social network for Hindus
value.Summary: Hindu Students Council's chapter at UIUC aims to bring awareness and understanding of hinduism to the general student body at UIUC.

value.Name: Hindu Yuva UIUC
value.Description:
One-sixth of humanity follows, in one or more ways, what is broadly termed the Hindu way of life (encompasses religion, culture and heritage). Hindu YUVA is about giving an experiential exposure of Hindu way of life to the campus community while having a lot of fun in a friendly and positive atmosphere. 
The objective of Hindu Yuva is to create opportunities for college communities, both students and faculty members, to understand and practice Hindu Dharma. The activity would include conducting regular programs with focus on all the aspects of personality development (physical, mental and spiritual). We aim to develop strong character and leadership skills in our members, emphasizing values such as self-discipline, self-confidence and a spirit of selfless service for the society. In addition doing service activities in and around campus to benefit the local community will also be focused.
value.Summary: Hindu YUVA aims at providing an exposure of the Hindu way of life to the campus community through activities which enhance individuals' physical, mental and spiritual aspects. We also focus on serving the local community through service activities.

value.Name: Hip-Notic Dance Team
value.Description: To provide an outlet for UIUC student performers to be versatile and diverse in dance.
value.Summary: To provide an outlet for UIUC student performers to be versatile and diverse in dance.

value.Name: Historical European Martial Arts Urbana/Champaign
value.Summary: A group dedicated to re-constructing historical European martial arts. We study primary documents for the martial systems they teach and re-construct the combat system they teach.

value.Name: History Student Graduate Association
value.Description: HGSA is formed to promote excellence in academic and professional areas and to further the interests of Graduate Students in History at the University of Illinois, Urbana-Champaign. All students pursuing a graduate degree under the direction of the Department of History, University of Illinois, Urbana, are members of HGSA.  No dues shall be assessed.
value.Summary: HGSA is formed to promote excellence in academic and professional areas and to further the interests of Graduate Students in History at the University of Illinois, Urbana-Champaign.

value.Name: Hong Kong Student Association
value.Description: Hong Kong Student Association (HKSA) is a registered social and cultural organization at University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign. Representing students from Hong Kong, HKSA strives to promote intercultural understanding and appreciation.
value.Summary: Representing students from Hong Kong, HKSA strives to promote intercultural understanding and appreciation.

value.Name: Honors Student Council
value.Description: Organize social, service, and academic opportunities for students in the Campus Honors Program.
value.Summary: Organize social, service, and academic opportunities for students in the Campus Honors Program.

value.Name: HonorSociety.org
value.Description:
HonorSociety.org is the preeminent organization dedicated to recognition of student success, and to empower students to achieve. Our community emphasizes leadership and is a platform to showcase your talents.

Our society's goal is to help you succeed, and to connect you with the people and opportunities to help you achieve your goals.
value.Summary: HonorSociety.org is the preeminent organization dedicated to recognition of student success, and to empower students to achieve. Our community emphasizes leadership and is a platform to showcase your talents.

value.Summary: To provide horticultural experiences and opportunities to members.

value.Name: Hospitality Management Association
value.Description: The Hospitality Management Association strives to provide students of any major the opportunity to learn more about the Hospitality Industry, make contacts within the industry, and provide opportunities to meet new people also interested in hospitality.
value.Summary: The Hospitality Management Association strives to provide students of any major the opportunity to learn more about the Hospitality Industry, make contacts within the industry, and provide opportunities to meet new people also interested in hospitality.

value.Name: Human Development and Family Studies Ambassadors
value.Description:
A group organized to improve undergraduate experience by engaging in departmental and

community service that supports leadership and professional development

of undergraduates, students’ abilities to market themselves as Human

Development and Family Studies majors, and mentor relationships among

current students, prospective undergraduate students, and faculty.
value.Summary: A student group at UIUC in the Department of Human Development and Family Studies. The group is committed to creating a welcoming environment and promote mentoring among peers. HDFS Ambassadors engage in a variety of departmental and community service.

value.Name: Human Development and Family Studies Graduate Student Organization
value.Description: i.    The HDFS-GSO is dedicated to establishing and maintaining effective channels of communication and cooperation between graduate students, faculty, the department, and the university.
value.Summary: i.    The HDFS-GSO is dedicated to establishing and maintaining effective channels of communication and cooperation between graduate students, faculty, the department, and the university.

value.Name: Human Nutrition Association.
value.Description: The Human Nutrition Association is a growing group of dedicated human nutrition and dietetic students that are interested in pursuing health-related careers. We accept anyone from any major as long as they're interested in healthcare. We offer a variety of resources and opportunities for any student that joins, such as facilitating discussions with healthcare professionals and professors, providing advice on courses and career paths, and providing health-related service opportunities in the community.
value.Summary: The Human Nutrition Association is dedicated to aiding students who are studying human nutrition and dietetics to understand and pursue careers in the healthcare field.

value.Name: Human Resource Development Student Association
value.Description:
Our goals are

  1. Strengthen personal contacts among students
  2. Promote teacher-student relationshi
  3. Initiate professional HR workshop/lecture/speech
value.Summary:
We aim to create an open learning environment to support students’ relationship and 
professional development.

value.Name: Humanitarian Association
value.Description: We are a student organization seeking to actively inform students about refugees displaced due to current conflicts and disastrous events around the world. In addition, we seek to partner with larger non-profit organizations to assist us in advocating for our cause and raising funds. Assistance may come in the form of monetary aid or humanitarian relief. The main purpose of this RSO is the improvement of refugee conditions and advocate for the betterment of displaced populations. Our organization is non-partisan and seeks to explore the humanitarian, rather than political aspects of conflicts affecting refugees.
value.Summary: To raise awareness of current global conflicts and disasters causing humanitarian challenges and partnering with non-profit organizations seeking to provide assistance.

value.Name: Humanity First at Illinois
value.Description: The primary purpose and intention of the Humanity First Student Organization (HFSO) at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign (UIUC) is to advocate for human life by means of undertaking disaster relief efforts, as well as human development projects for socially disadvantaged communities in collaboration with Humanity First USA (HF-USA). HF-USA can provide programs that University of Illinois members could potentially partake in -- such as Water for Life, Our Kids Our Future, and others-- However, there is no limit to the different types of projects, with the approval of HF-USA and the school, that we may engage in.
value.Summary: Humanity First is a humanitarian organization whose sole purpose is to serve those in need of help from   the people in our town all the way to people across the globe.

value.Name: Humans Vs Zombies
value.Description: Humans Vs Zombies is a modified game of tag lasting for a week. All players start out as Humans, except for a few original Zombies. The Zombie tries to tag Humans, converting them into Zombies. Humans can use the socks to stun zombies, so they can escape.
value.Summary: Humans Vs Zombies is a modified game of tag lasting for a week.  All players start out as Humans, except for one original Zombie.  The Zombie tries to tag Humans, converting them into Zombies.  Humans can use the socks to stun zombies, so they can escape

value.Name: I-CAUSE
value.Description: I-CAUSE is a service and advocacy organization that works in solidarity with the undocumented community, focusing primarily on equal secondary educational opportunities for all students, regardless of legal status. We work to educate the University of Illinois and the community about issues of DACA/undocumented students, educational access, and immigration. We collaborate with other social justice organizations for service projects, panels, fundraisers and more. We seek to be involved in our community and welcome all individuals into our organization.
value.Summary: I-CAUSE is a service and advocacy organization that works in solidarity with the undocumented community, focusing primarily on equal secondary educational opportunities for all students, regardless of legal status.

value.Name: IDentity Company of Irish Dance
value.Description: IDentity is a performance-based Irish dance group consisting of upper-level dancers who wish to put a modern spin on on a traditional form of dance.
value.Summary: IDentity is an RSO for experienced Irish Dancers that wish to continue performing.

value.Name: iENGAGE
value.Summary: Student leaders of iENGAGE, in partnership with OVP, ISSS and OIIR-IE, connect international and domestic students through community  service, leadership development and global competency programs.

value.Name: iHair
value.Summary: Our goal is to reach campus community with seminars and discussions that give support to hair care and beauty. With the rising movement of taking back your Natural hair, we would like to be a supportive guide and inspire your hair and beauty journey.

value.Name: IlliAAC Academic Advisors
value.Description: The purpose of IlliAAC is to promote and develop quality academic advising at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign. It is dedicated to supporting professional growth for academic advisors and advising. As the official voice for the academic advising community at the UIUC, it shall provide a forum for discussion, debate, and the exchange of ideas and information relevant to advising. In its efforts to enhance academic advising services on campus, IlliAAC advocates the highest level of professional ethics and standards.
value.Summary: IlliAAC's purpose is to promote and develop quality academic advising at Illinois. IlliAAC is dedicated to supporting professional growth for academic advisors and advising by providing a forum for discussion, debate, and the exchange of ideas.

value.Name: IlliDell of Alpha Gamma Sigma
value.Description: Professional Agricultural Fraternity
value.Summary: Professional Agricultural Fraternity

value.Name: Illini 4000
value.Description: The Illini 4000 is a non-profit organization dedicated to the fight against cancer, the support of those affected by cancer, and the documentation of how cancer impacts the lives of Americans. Through our annual cross-country bike ride, we reach out to new communities and new individuals each year spreading our message of hope and awareness. As long as cancer remains an issue of public health, as long as cancer affects daily life, and so long as cancer takes its toll, we shall continue our fight.
value.Summary: The Illini 4000 will send students on a summertime cross country, 4000 mile journey by bicycle to spread awareness and raise money for cancer support programs.

value.Name: Illini Aerospace Outreach
value.Description:
Illini Aerospace Outreach serves three primary functions:

1. By organizing outreach across the aerospace department, IAO makes outreach convenient and rewarding for members of the C-U community.
2. The increased volume of outreach provides an incentive for corporate sponsors looking to support STEM and grow their brand awareness.
3. Students volunteer in order to build business relations with important companies in the aerospace field.
value.Summary: IAO uses outreach opportunities created by the UIUC Aerospace Engineering department and corporate sponsors to teach students in the community about Aerospace Engineering

value.Name: Illini Algae Research Group
value.Description: Students can partner up with graduate students to help work on projects using algae and laboratory techniques to learn about and help advance research currently happening on the University of Illinois campus.  Furthermore, the club works as a whole entity to self educate students about the industry and current developments. Apart from the research projects in the ABE department, the club also organizes its members and sometimes in conjunction with other organizations to facilitate involvement in competitions begging for new projects on both a local and national scale.  Students are encouraged to join for the learning experience and the opportunity to gain laboratory experience working with relevant systems in algae and bioenergy sustainability.
value.Summary: Our organization brings together students of both undergraduate and graduate curriculums to facilitate the learning and understanding of research development and industry growth of algae and bioenergy systems.

value.Name: Illini Automotive Club
value.Description:
Anyone with interests and passion for cars are welcome.

  • Learn about cars and help with club projects
  • Do not have to own your car-- your passion about cars is what matters!
  • Bring in your own cars across different manufacturers to learn basic to advanced principles about your car: from oil changes to suspension engineering and engine computer mapping
  • Race together in intercollegiate and local autocross events, go-karts and track days
  • Frequent social gatherings at the club house!

 

**This Club was previously named UIUC Car Tuners. Club details have been renewed for 2011 Fall.


Activities





Photography Sessions



Autocross







2010 Winter Auto Challenge at Rantoul Airforce Base
value.Summary: The networking hub for automotive enthusiasts at U of I. Our members share interest in driving and working on cars. We are also dedicated to racing in legal forms of motorsports such as autocross, drag racing and track days. We welcome those without cars

value.Name: Illini Awaaz A Cappella
value.Description:
Illini Awaaz A Cappella is the premier co-ed South Asian A Cappella team at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign. We are a cooperative group of student musicians who bring together the stylings of contemporary English and Indian music to create a truly unique listening experience. 

For more information, contact illiniawaazuiuc@gmail.com
value.Summary: Illini Awaaz A Cappella is the premier co-ed south Asian A Cappella team on the University of Illinois campus.

value.Name: Illini Badminton Intercollegiate Sports Club
value.Description: A competitive and recreational badminton club that is available to U of I campus community. Tryouts are held during the year, at the beginning of each semester. Tryouts dates will be announced in our websites or you can simply visit us on Quad Day for the Fall tryout date. We seek to spark a friendly competition among our members so they can get better with the help of one another. Club members often join various competitions in the nation but mostly those in Midwest area. Once a year we may also participate in Intercollegiate tournament if it is possible.
value.Summary: An organization that provides competitive and recreational badminton play for U of I campus community.

value.Name: Illini Bags Club
value.Description:
As an organization we strive to encourage everyone to participate in playing bags. People will be able to learn to play and compete in bags at our meetings. We will also provide instructions and tips on what material is needed to create a bags set.

We will host a campus wide bags tournament. We also have plans to host miniature tailgate games and tournaments at fall football games. We will also work to organize a travel team for some off campus tournaments

Most of all we just want people to enjoy themselves playing the ridiculously simple and fun game of bean bags
value.Summary: As an organization we strive to encourage everyone to participate in playing bags. People will be able to learn to play and compete in bags at our meetings. We will provide a fun and competitive environment for people to enjoy the fun game of bean bags.

value.Name: Illini Ballista
value.Description: Illini Ballista is dedicated to bringing accuracy, precision, and power to the annual pumpkin chunking competition. Each year we plan on building something along the lines of a cannon, trebuchet, catapult, or anything capable of launching a pumpkin over a mile. This RSO not only is for real world applications, it's to help bring students together and teach them the values of team work.
value.Summary: We are an organization dedicated to helping students take what they're learning in their classes and applying it to real world problems by building a cannon, trebuchet, or catapult from scratch.

value.Name: Illini Barbers
value.Description: We want to provide interested people with the necessary resources to learn how to cut their own hair - a skill that can save time and money. We also hope that these people would want to learn to cut other people's hair, thus growing a network of local (i.e. students) and reliable haircutters. All the money raised through cutting other people's hair would go to charity.
value.Summary: Our purposes are to provide people with a greater sense of control of their hair by teaching them to cut it themselves and to promote the lifetime applicable skill of cutting other people's hair while raising money for charity in the process.

value.Name: Illini Bass Fishing Club
value.Description: To promote the sport of Collegiate Bass Fishing as well as promote conservation.
value.Summary: To promote the sport of Collegiate Bass Fishing as well as promote conservation.

value.Name: Illini Bhangra
value.Description: To promote Bhangra, a traditional Indian dance style native to the state of Punjab.
value.Summary: To promote Bhangra, a traditional Indian dance style native to the state of Punjab.

value.Name: Illini Billiards Club
value.Description: To promote activities related to billiards and to foster a community of pool players of all skill levels.
value.Summary: To promote activities related to billiards and to foster a community of pool players of all skill levels.

value.Name: Illini Bodybuilding Club
value.Description:
Mission Statement: The purpose of this club is to provide a place where members of the bodybuilding community can unite and share a vast amount of information pertaining to the sport or other related activities. This includes but is not limited to training, proper nutrition, and supplementation. The club also aims to provide members with a chance to network socially and find others who share similar passions and can discuss common interests.

Executive Board

President - William Velez

Treasurer - Yasser Arrocha

Vice President - Jonathan Igartua
value.Summary: The purpose of this organization is to promote lifting, proper nutrition, and supplementation. Please contact the President in order to join the private group discussion page on Facebook to become a part of the club.

value.Name: Illini Bowling Club
value.Description: To generate interest in bowling and win the Intercollegiate Bowling Championship.
value.Summary: To generate interest in bowling and win the Intercollegiate Bowling Championship.

value.Name: Illini Chess Club
value.Description:
The Illini Chess Club meets weekly every Sunday from 6-8 PM in the Illini Union. Players of all skill levels are encouraged to come and partake in the numerous events that will be held throughout the year.

 

In the coming months, we will have lectures, free play, simuls, blitz tournaments, and much more! If you are someone interested in learning more about chess, you've come to the right place.
value.Summary: The Illini Chess Club is dedicated to promoting chess throughout UIUC and Champaign-Urbana community. We strive to create an engaging environment where everyone from beginners to seasoned experts alike can learn to be a better chess player.

value.Name: Illini Chinese Christian Fellowship
value.Description:
ICCF is 40+ years old and exists to be a Christ-centered, Bible-based family where Chinese Christians can find fellowship, study God's Word, and be equipped to expand God's kingdom in Champaign-Urbana and throughout the world.

 

Our members are primarily students at the University of Illinois; the fellowship is subdivided according to language, which are English, Cantonese, and Mandarin. Typcially our primary events are Bible study, worships, sharing refreshements, games, and fellowship. In addition, we also have prayer meetings. We welcome both Christians and non-Christians to come and know more about Christ.

 

We usually meet at Twin City Bible Church on Fridays at 7pm during the semester. Please don't hesitate to contact listed contacts of this fellowship if you are interested in coming.

value.Summary:
ICCF is 40+ years old and exists to be a Christ-centered, Bible-based family where Chinese Christians can find fellowship, study God's Word, and be equipped to expand God's kingdom in Champaign-Urbana and throughout the world.

value.Name: Illini Collegians for Life
value.Description:
Mission Statement:

Illini Collegians for Life (ICFL) is a human rights group open to all faiths and beliefs that respects the dignity of every human life from conception until natural death. We are for women and children, and are dedicated to promoting a culture of life on campus, with a specific focus on the effects of abortion on our society.

 

Vision Statement:

In order to build a culture of life on campus, our three guiding principles are:
Unity – Building solidarity among all people who support human life.
Education – Informing our community of the truth regarding abortion.
Outreach – Spreading the culture of life through activism, service, and awareness.
value.Summary: ICFL is an organization devoted to protecting the dignity of every human being, with a specific focus on women, children, and the effects of abortion on our campus society.

value.Name: Illini Contraband
value.Description:
Illini Contraband acts as a service to the University of Illinois regarding
its musical and entertainment needs.  Illini Contraband performs for private, as
well as University funded events including social gatherings and charity events.
value.Summary: Illini Contraband acts as a service to the University of Illinois regarding its musical and entertainment needs.  Illini Contraband performs for private, as well as University funded events including social gatherings and charity events.

value.Name: Illini Cycling
value.Description: Illini Cycling's mission is to support students who ride bikes. We do this by bringing together some of the most knowledgeable and experienced cyclists at the University of Illinois. Check out our website at illinicyclingclub.org and Facebook page at www.facebook.com/illinicycling for more details about when we host our group rides and when we hold our general meetings.
value.Summary:
Illini Cycling welcomes cyclists of all disciplines and experience. Here's some of what we offer:
 - Multiple weekly group rides
 - Annual Spring Break trip
 - Cycling skills clinics
 - Social events
 - Maintenance workshops
 - Collegiate racing

value.Name: Illini Dance Company
value.Description: We are a company that practices several times a week and competes once a semester at a National Dance Alliance competition.We have a strong focus on technical dance including contemporary and jazz.
value.Summary: Elite Competitive Dance Company

value.Name: Illini Dancesport
value.Description:
1. Providing a stage for UIUC students/faculty/staff who are interested in dance/performance to develop their talents beyond their academic field.

2. Representing UIUC at collegiate ballroom dance competitions.

3. Forming a collaborative environment for various types of dancing.
value.Summary: Illini Dancesport is a ballroom dancing organization dedicated to teaching the UIUC community how to ballroom dance as well as represent UIUC at various collegiate ballroom competitions throughout the Midwest.

value.Name: Illini Democrats
value.Description: To promote and extend the ideas of the Democratic Party at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign.
value.Summary: To promote and extend the ideas of the Democratic Party at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign.

value.Name: Illini Disc Golf Club
value.Description:
The Illini Disc Golf Club has three primary goals:

 

  1. The first goal of the Illini Disc Golf Club is to create a friendly and competitive playing environment for members. In both the fall and spring semester, the club will host a series of weekend tournaments.  These weekend tournaments will award points based on a participant’s placement.  The players with the highest point totals at the end of each season will receive prizes from the club.
  2. The second goal of the Illini Disc Golf Club is to promote the sport of disc golf in the local community.  Unfortunately, only one disc golf course currently exists in Champaign-Urbana. With Disc Golf emerging as a common sport, the Illini Disc Golf club will try to encourage the local park districts of Champaign and Urbana to install new courses in the area. 
  3. The third goal of the Illini Disc Golf Club is to work with similar clubs at other universities and create intercollegiate competition.
value.Summary: The Illini Disc Golf Club provides both a competitive and friendly playing environment for those interested in disc golf.  We host several leagues and other events through out the year.

value.Name: Illini Drone Club
value.Description:
Are you interested in drones? Do you fly a drone? Do you want to learn to fly a drone? Whether you have a drone, have flown RC before, want to learn to fly, or are just curious about drones and aircraft you are welcome to join our club! 

The Illini Drone Club is a group of drone racers, aerial photographers, and drone enthusiasts brought together by our love for things that fly. We follow FAA regulations. Safety is our top priority.

We are very excited to announce that we are now sponsored by Hobbico, Inc. the largest U.S. distributor of radio-control and general hobby products. In fact, the largest model hobby company in the world. Hobbico.com

Join our Facebook group here.
value.Summary:
The Illini Drone Club (sponsored by Hobbico) is a group of drone enthusiasts. Our love for aircraft bring us together. Join us if you fly, want to learn, or if you are just interested in drones. 
Safety and following FAA regulations is our top priority.

value.Name: Illini Drone Racing
value.Summary: We design, build, fly, and race drones.

value.Name: Illini EcoConcept
value.Description: Illini EcoConcept is an organization dedicated towards the goal of designing, fabricating, and testing a hydrogen fuel cell car in the Urban Concept category of the Shell Ecomarathon competition. The team seeks to produce an outstanding vehicle that is not only competitive in the competition but innovative in the automotive industry as a whole. Through the teams past experiences and the determination to succeed, the Illini EcoConcept will realize the goals it seeks to accomplish.
value.Summary: Illini EcoConcept is an organization dedicated towards the goal of designing, fabricating, and testing a hydrogen fuel cell car in the Urban Concept category of the Shell Ecomarathon competition. All majors are welcome to join, learn, and innovate.

value.Name: Illini Epilepsy Project
value.Summary: Epilepsy is a very common neurological disorder characterized by seizures. IEP's goal is to raise awareness and shed a light about this chronic medical issue as we fundraise in order to help find a cure.

value.Name: Illini Equestrians
value.Description: To further student knowledge of, appreciation for, and participation within the equine industry through social, educational, and competitive activities.
value.Summary: To further student knowledge of, appreciation for, and participation within the equine industry through social, educational, and competitive activities.

value.Name: Illini Equine Rescue Society
value.Description:
We are a service organization dedicated to raising money and supplying volunteers to local equine rescues and function as a student outreach group, educating the community on proper equine care. We also act in cooperation with local equine rescue agencies help rehabilitate and facilitate the adoption of rescued horses. Currently, we help Healing Horse Stables, and Crosswinds Equine Rescue, Inc.

Any level of experience in any discipline is welcome to join for just $15 a year, or $8 a semester.
value.Summary: We are a service organization dedicated to raising money and supplying volunteers to local equine rescues and function as a student outreach group, educating the community on proper equine care. We also act in cooperation with local equine rescue

value.Name: Illini Field Hockey
value.Description:
We are University of Illinois' co-ed field hockey team.  We practice and play year round: outdoor competitions in the fall and spring against other universities, and indoor training sessions in the winter.  All grade and skill levels are welcome! Practices are at the turf fields at First and Stadium: Mondays & Wednesdays 6pm, Saturdays 11am.

 

Our Sponsors:

Studypool is an online marketplace that connects students with questions with tutors who can answer them. Using Studypool gives you access to thousands of verified tutors to help you with any question at any time.

We are sponsored by Azazie.

The Most Booked Restaurant In The U.S. 5 Years Running: Founding Farmers
value.Summary: We are University of Illinois' co-ed field hockey team.  We practice and play year round: outdoor competitions in the fall and spring against other universities, and indoor training sessions in the winter.  All grade and skill levels are welcome!

value.Name: Illini Fighting ALS
value.Description: We're dedicated to fundraising and raising awareness of Lou Gehrig's disease on campus.
value.Summary: UIUC RSO for ALS outreach including fundraising, awareness, and service.

value.Name: Illini Fighting Alzheimer's
value.Description:
Our group hopes to pursue a variety of activities related to fundraising, outreach and service.

Fundraising- we hope to organize a local Walk to End Alzheimer's, and implement other events and activities, with all proceeds donated to support Alzheimer's research. 

Service- we will volunteer with Alzheimer's patients and their families, on a weekly basis, at area hospitals and nursing homes.

Outreach- we hope to promote increased awareness on our campus and surrounding community. Our organization will provide educational outreach, around the various factors surrounding Alzheimer's disease, to students and other residents of the Urbana-Champaign community. In addition, our student body is very interested in pursuing research opportunities- our student organization will reach out to the many labs on campus that research Alzheimer's disease, and direct interested students towards participating in these labs.
value.Summary: IlliniALZ hopes to generate awareness for Alzheimer's disease and support its victims, through fundraising, outreach, education, research, and community service.

value.Name: Illini Fighting Hunger
value.Description: Supporting hunger relief efforts in East Central Illinois through partnerships with community agencies and organization and implementation of hunger-fighting service projects including meal-packaging events.
value.Summary: Supporting hunger relief efforts in East Central Illinois through partnerships with community agencies and organization and implementation of hunger-fighting service projects including meal-packaging events.

value.Name: Illini Folk Dance Society
value.Description:
The Illini Folk Dance Society is a recreational dance group devoted to the preservation and enjoyment of traditional folk dances from around the world. We primarily dance for our own enjoyment, but also occasionally perform or teach for community groups.

We meet once or twice weekly (always on Tuesdays, and some Saturdays) throughout the year, and we welcome beginners -- no previous experience is required. We especially encourage beginning dancers to show up on Tuesdays, when we usually provide teaching for the first hour. value.Name: Illini Friendships
value.Description:
The purpose of Illini Friendships is to build relations within the community between University of Illinois students and local senior citizens. Illini Friendships provides volunteer opportunities for students of the university while positively impacting senior citizens in nursing homes, assisted living facilities and elsewhere within the Champaign-Urbana community. The goal of the Illini Friendships is to facilitate the creation of friendships between senior citizens and students while also improving and maintaining the cognitive health of senior citizens with mental illness and disease. A secondary function of Illini Friendships will be to raise awareness and to educate members and the community on mental illness and disease occurring in the older population. Another function of the club will be to fundraise for the local nursing homes. Money collected will be used to help improve the quality of care given at the nursing homes. In addition, the club will fundraise and raise awareness for neurological illnesses. 

Nursing homes and assisted living communities are often understaffed. Residents of these facilities are often left alone with nothing to do, some residents talk to others while others sit alone in silence. The nursing assistants of the nursing homes can become overworked and too busy to give the needed attention to the residents. This is where Illini Friendships can step in. Students can travel to nursing homes/assisted living communities and spend time quality time with the residents. Illini Friendships provides students the opportunity to get to know the residents and to hear their stories while also sharing their own. Students will be able to engage in activities with the residents such as playing games like checkers, chess, bingo, and etc.

Illini Friendships will meet once every two weeks on campus at a time and date to be determined. The club will offer weekly volunteer opportunities for its members. At the club meetings students will discuss and share their experiences with each other. Additionally, short lectures will be given during meetings discussing neurological illnesses. These lectures will focus on illnesses that often affect the elderly population such as: parkinson's, dementia, alzheimer's, depression, and etc. 

The club is intended for any and all students at U of I. The club offers an opportunity for pre-health students to gain volunteer opportunities as well as to gain experience interacting with an aging population, one in which they will most certainly be caring for.
value.Summary: The main goal of Illini Friendships is to build relations within the community between University of Illinois students and local senior citizens while also helping to maintain the cognitive health of senior citizens with mental illness and disease.

value.Name: Illini Hyperloop
value.Description:
SpaceX has announced an open competition, geared towards university students and independent engineering teams, to design and build the best Hyperloop pod. This will be the second Hyperloop Competition that SpaceX is holding. To support this competition, SpaceX has constructed a one-mile test track adjacent to their Hawthorne, California headquarters. Teams will test their half-scale pods during the second competition weekend at the track, currently targeted for August 2017. The knowledge gained here will continue to be open-source.

Illini Hyperloop has been formed to promote cross-disciplinary relationships to design and build a functional Hyperloop Pod that will be tested on the SpaceX track in California, come August 2017. All University of Illinois students are invited to participate!
value.Summary: Students  participating in Illini Hyperloop will design, build, and test a Hyperloop pod for the SpaceX Hyperloop Pod Competition released in August 2017.

value.Name: Illini Internet of Things Association
value.Description:
The Illini Internet of Things Association is the first Internet of Things organization on campus.

Internet of Things as a concept is soon to take over the world and going to change how we live. All the top companies of the world are investing heavily in the technology and the industry is projected to be worth more than 4 Trillion dollars by 2020.

In light of the same, the organization aims to take up IoT projects to integrate campus life with IoT and thus make UIUC an IoT enabled campus. The organization is attracting a lot of corporate partners who are extremely excited about UIUC utilizing its talented engineering student body for IoT related projects.

Although the organization is tech oriented, we are looking for students from all majors, be it business, finance, public policy or urban planning, anyone with a passion for innovation is welcome.

value.Name: Illini Juggling and Unicycling Club
value.Description:
The Illini Juggling and Unicycling Club (IJUC) provides a space for folks to meet up and practice the art of juggling and unicycling. We are a friendly group who love teaching people the art of Juggling!

  • Club meeting times are simply time slots where we have space to juggle. You are free to show up at any time between when the meet-up starts and when it ends.
  • All skill levels are welcome! If you ever wanted to learn how to juggle, IJUC is a great place to start! We gladly help newcomers learn how to juggle, and we love helping folks learn new tricks!
  • The club has no agenda for its members (though personal improvement is always encouraged!), so anyone is free to attend club meet-ups any time during the semester.
  • Props, such as balls and clubs, are provided by IJUC, but feel free to bring any of your own equipment!

IJUC is exited to bring many semesters of fun to the University of Illinois Campus!

We will be meeting Mondays and Wednesdays at 5:00 pm on the Northwest corner of the Main Quad. Email Andrew Bloomberg (bloombe2@illinois.edu) if you have any questions.
value.Summary: To provide a casual setting for people of any skill level to come learn and practice juggling.

value.Name: Illini Jujutsu
value.Description:
To provide affordable instruction in the art of jujutsu to members of the UIUC community.

We practice traditional Japanese jujutsu with a focus on various throwing techniques and joint locks. Unlike many other martial arts these days, we focus on real-world practical applications of techniques focusing on self-defense as opposed to training for competitions. Sensei Jeff Gaynor has practiced martial arts for almost 35 years and, while having experience in other forms, insists that jujutsu is the absolute best martial art and that everyone should learn a martial art.

Additional information can be found on the club's Netfiles site or by emailing us a question. We'd love to see you at practice some time!!
value.Summary: To provide affordable instruction in the art of traditional Japanese jujutsu to members of the UIUC community.

value.Description: IMSS provides the uninsured and low-income residents of Champaign County a free medical screening service that determines risk for Obesity, Diabetes, Hypertension, and Hyperlipidemia.  All screenings are scheduled and operated by undergraduate pre-health students, funded by Provena's Center for Healthy Aging and student fundraising, and supervised by licensed healthcare professionals. Our members volunteer at our screening events by conducting tests and also volunteer at affiliated community health organizations to improve the healthcare access crisis in this area.  Established in Fall 2008, we have held over 25 screening events and have tested over 300 clients.  This year, we plan to hold at least eight events per semester and test 300 individuals.  Ultimately, we hope that our organization will serve as a template for other universities to serve their geographic area.

We also interface with the University to express concerns from the Illini Veteran community regarding University programs and VA benefits issues. The Illini Veterans are also dedicated to fundraising and working with UIUC's upcoming Center for Wounded Veterans in Higher Education.

value.Name: Illini Young Life
value.Description: Young Life is a Christian outreach ministry for high school and middle school students.  College leaders walk through life with students from Centennial High School, Central High School, St. Thomas Moore, Mahomet-Seymore High School, St. Matthews, Edison Middle School, and more.  As leaders, we plan weekly events; club on Mondays, breakfast on Wednesdays, and bible study on Thursdays.  Along with this we do a huge amount of contact work which includes going to school lunches, football games, and coffee with students in order to grow in our relationships and earn the right to tell them the gospel.  Every summer, we take a large group of students to camps in Georgia, Michigan, and New York.
value.Summary: Young Life is an international Christian outreach ministry for high school and middle school students.  Illini Young Life is focused on building Christian communities in the Champaign County Area.

value.Name: Illini Yugioh
value.Description:

We hold our weekly meetings Friday at 7 pm in the Illini Union basement.
