value.Name: IlliniFurs
value.Description:
Furries are a subculture of people who are interested in discussing and appreciating media of anthropomorphic animals, from Rocket Raccoon in Guardians of the Galaxy, to characters in video games like Fox McCloud, to the recent movie Zootopia. Of course, nowhere will you find a hard and concrete definition of what a furry is, or what constitutes furry media versus just popular culture. The furry fandom as a whole is an ever-changing, ever-whirling maelstrom where the edges are never constant but the center always is. As resolutely as anything can be stated, those who identify as furries enjoy the idea of anthropomorphic animals.

This group is intended as a community of such individuals, designated to further their interests and give them an opportunity to explore this interest with other like-minded people.

Activities are primarily social, though this includes art sessions, discussion of matters of fandom intrigue (such as the 2016 documentary Fursonas, by Dominick Rodriguez), and other such activities. Meetings are currently every other week, typically on Friday or Saturday, though not with a set time or place, due to the varied natures of events. Ask the Primary Contact or email us at illinifurs@gmail.com for access to our newsletter and more details.
value.Summary: This organization is for the discussion and appreciation of anthropomorphic animals in media, across popular culture and fandom. Activities are primarily social, though include art nights and discussion of matters of fandom intrigue. All are welcome!

value.Name: IlliniThon
value.Description: IlliniThon raises money and awareness for children treated by St. John's Children's Hospital, our local Children's Miracle Network Hospital in Springfield, IL.  Fundraisers and events as well as events to get to know the families are held throughout the year leading up to a 12-hour night of fun on April 7th.  At the event, you will meet our Miracle Families and hear their stories, play games and sports, eat, win prizes, and, of course, dance!
value.Summary: IlliniThon is a nation-wide initiative which benefits Children's Miracle Network.  IlliniThon is a campus wide philanthropy for the kids of St. John's Children's Hospital.  Form a team with your friends and join the fun!

value.Name: Illinois Biodiesel Initiative
value.Description:
Formed in 2006 as a local Engineers Without Borders at UIUC initiative, IBI's mission is to supplement the Illinois Climate Action Plan by reducing emissions from the campus fleet and agricultural operations, reusing and recycing waste from dining halls and the surrounding area, and educating the community at large. Primarily we produce biodiesel from waste cooking oil; our secondary projects are producing soap from oil and biodiesel glycerin waste for university dining use, designing and building a methanol recovery unit for the biodiesel process, and expanding the scope of the project as we expand and grow into new areas.

We won a $28,000 campus sustainability grant in Spring 2016 to increase our biodiesel and soap production. We have recently moved our operation in 250 Noyes Lab: a large laboratory that only we operate in with lots of room to grow.

Join us! Everyone has a place; we are fast-paced, hands-on, and have measurable impact. We need your help to achieve our goals!
value.Summary: The Illinois Biodiesel Initiative is a student-run project improving the overall sustainability of our Illini community. We recycle and repurpose University Dining's waste cooking oil as biodiesel and soap as well as educate and do outreach on biodiesel.

value.Name: Illinois Business Market Anaylsis
value.Description:
Illinois Business Market Analysis (IBMA) is a student run organization registered at the University of Illinois tailored towards business students with an interest in market research, business strategies, consulting and investing. IBMA strives to utilize research and analytical principles for real world business operations, successfully preparing it's members for future careers in corporate settings. Our organization will implement seminars with business owners in the Champaign-Urbana area to establish networking skills and educate members on the value of market research. The goal of Illinois Business Market Analysis is to ensure business students that they will gain knowledge and hands-on experience with analyzing, allowing them to apply these skills in their respective professional field. 

 

To ensure this, IBMA implements team-orientated projects that will emphasize researching a specific market trend and constructing a business model for future operations or investments.
value.Summary: Illinois Business Market Analysis is a student run organization looking to provide experience to prospective students interested in market analysis and industry research. We aim to prepare members by studying business models, operations, and strategies.

value.Name: Illinois Connect
value.Description: Illinois Connect stands as a representation of all international based RSOs on campus by developing stronger relationships among the various student bodies. We envision an inclusive community where we grow and learn as a unit, where we share lifestyles, traditions, and heritage of others. Our goal is to develop a platform that creates an engaging cross cultural environment for other student bodies to support one another. RSOs on board would benefit immensely as they can fully concentrate on showcasing their unique national heritage, more so, the university will be rewarded the most as communities come together and define our historically rich institution. We believe, with this, the students of University of Illinois at Urbana Champaign would not only receive a top tier education, but to also be able to enrich themselves in diverse cultures, ethnicities, languages, and food on our very own campus.
value.Summary: Illinois Connect aims to unite student bodies at the UIUC, by developing a platform that promotes a more engaging cross cultural environment. We strive to enrich students at UIUC by showcasing diverse cultures, ethnicities, languages and food on campus.

value.Name: Illinois Female Engineers in Academia Training
value.Description:
The purpose of iFEAT is to help female graduate students and post doctoral students in various STEM fields prepare faculty application materials with the end goal of applying for an academic position. They also learn more about the application process itself and other best practices.

A combination of seminars and peer review sessions allow for the participants to write and rewrite their personal application materials, better preparing them for the faculty application process. It also gives a unique platform for engineering education research involving women in STEM fields preparing for academia.

iFEAT was started in 2014 by Elizabeth Horstman, Yanfen Li, Danielle Mai, and Professor Rohit Bhargava through the Graduate Society of Women Engineers (GradSWE) here at the University of Illinois Urbana Champaign. It has now evolved into its own RSO that works closely with GradSWE to provide opportunities for STEM graduate students and postdocs.
value.Summary: The purpose of iFEAT is to help female graduate students and post doctoral students in STEM fields prepare faculty application materials with the end goal of applying for an academic position. We offer a combination of seminars and peer review sessions.

value.Name: Illinois Men's Rugby
value.Description:
PRACTICES

Our practices take place at the PAR/FAR Complex fields on Florida Avenue.  They are Tuesdays and Thursdays from 5-7pm.  Anyone may join at any time during the season.  We have an A and a B side so we will place you based on your skill set, experience, and dedication.  

 

 

General Information:

The Illinois Men's RFC is a college club team that belongs to the Big Ten D1-A Conference and is associated with the University of Illinois-Urbana/Champaign. Since its establishment in 1963 the club has achieved numerous successes including being crowned Big Ten champions in the 1980's more times than not and four National final 4 finishes. Currently, the team fields a minimum of two fifteens teams each spring and fall and plays a full Big Ten sevens schedule in the Spring. In the 2012-'13 season, the Illini made their debut in D1-A and finished 3rd in the Big Ten and earned the rank of 17th in the nation on D1Arugby.com.

If you are interested in playing for the Illinois Men's Soccer Club, the first team and reserve squad hold tryouts on the first day of classes in the fall semester. More information can be found at www.IllinoisMensClubSoccer.com.

If you are interested in becoming a member of the organization that functions behind the team, there are three departments to apply to as well as a fan membership. The departments include Athletic Administration, Marketing / Accounting, and Design. Our fan membership is called the Moose Club. Information on both can be found at www.IllinoisMensClubSoccer.com.

value.Name: Illinois Robotics in Space
value.Description:
Illinois Robotics in Space (IRIS) was formed in 2009 to represent the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign in the annual NASA Robotic Mining Competition (RMC). The IRIS team consists of members from a wide variety of academic and professional backgrounds, which cover a large spectrum of expertise.

While designing and constructing a robot for the NASA RMC, members not only learn about robotics from the ground up, but also build teamwork skills, and foster a familiarity with systems integration and engineering.
value.Summary: Illinois Robotics in Space (IRIS) was founded to encourage and facilitate education and hands on experience in engineering and robotics, especially in the arena of space applications, for students of all ages.

value.Name: Illinois Sales and Marketing Association
value.Description:
Illinois Sales and Marketing Association is an undergraduate student organization providing members educational and networking opportunities within the world of sales and marketing. We began as the Selling Illini and evolved into ISMA to expose a larger breadth of students to professional development opportunities. The mission of Illinois Sales and Marketing Association is to offer students opportunities to expand their personal and professional competencies within the industry through insightful guest speakers, workshops, and professional conferences. Our organization is headed by dedicated students looking to better the University of Illinois as a whole. 

The goal for Illinois Sales and Marketing Association is two-fold. Firstly, to raise the visibility and reputation of the Media Sales certificate program at the University of Illinois to outside recruiters and place it as one of the top sources for talented and passionate students. Also, the organization as a whole would function to develop and facilitate opportunities for its members to learn about Sales and receive unique internship/job opportunities through networking with other students, guest speakers, panel discussions, and club trips.
value.Summary: Illinois Sales and Marketing Association is an undergraduate student organization providing members educational and networking opportunities within the world of sales and marketing.

value.Name: Illinois Solar Decathlon
value.Description:
Our Mission

Illinois Solar Decathlon seeks to lead innovation in design and technology to advance towards an environmentally sustainable future. We bridge the legacy of past Illinois competition projects to the development of future successful teams. For our existing homes, we ensure their continual usage as a research and outreach platform. On campus, we engage in projects and foster relationships to educate and develop our organization. Through our integrated approach, we aim to elevate the standard of Solar Decathlon and ensure a true contribution to green building.

To learn more about the Illinois Solar Decathlon, check out our webpage. 

About the Competition

The U.S. Department of Energy Solar Decathlon challenges collegiate teams to design, build, and operate solar-powered houses that are cost-effective, energy-efficient, and attractive. The winner of the competition is the team that best blends affordability, consumer appeal, and design excellence with optimal energy production and maximum efficiency.

For more, check out http://www.solardecathlon.gov/
value.Summary: Design and build net-zero solar homes! We recruit future Solar Decathlon competition teams, engage in green building projects & educate the campus & community about sustainable design and construction. Engineers, designers, business & all welcome!

value.Name: Illinois Space Society
value.Description:
The Illinois Space Society (ISS) was founded at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign in September 2003 by Kirk Kittell and Derek Meyers. ISS was created to develop a network of students who are interested in space exploration and development. The purposes of the Illinois Space Society are to:

  • Create a network of space supporters in the Champaign-Urbana area
  • Serve the community through educational outreach
  • Provide supporters with resources that will assist them in following their dreams in the field of space exploration

The Illinois Space Society provides its members with a variety of technical, professional, and educational outreach opportunities. In a typical year, ISS participates in the NASA Student Launch high-power rocketry competition, NIA/NASA RASC-AL aerospace design competition, NASA Micro-g NExT competition, and NASA Midwest Space Grant High-Powered Rocketry Competition.
value.Summary: To promote the development and understanding of space through student-focused technical projects, educational outreach, and attendance at professional aerospace symposiums

value.Name: Illinois Spikeball Club
value.Summary: Enjoy the good game of Spikeball on campus with other Spikeball enthusiasts. Open to everyone: veterans and newcomers, competitive and casual. #jointhemovement

value.Name: Illinois Sports Business Conference
value.Description:
Illinois Sports Business Conference was started by a group of students who saw an opportunity to fill the gap of knowledge and resources between the sports industry and the business world.  The ISBC team works together throughout the year to put on an annual conference hosting, elite leaders and professionals in the sports industry. Through various workshops, networking events and an annual conference, ISBC fosters relationships and creates a roadmap for students to find their path in the sports business industry.

Organizing and hosting the annual Illinois Sports Business Conference will be the main focus of Professionals in Sport. Creating this conference provides students the opportunity to learn from leading professionals, promote future networking relationships and explore possible careers in the field.  ISBC will be composed of executive board members individually managing teams with specific responsibilities including but not limited to, alumni relations, finances, public relations and media. It is imperative to the ISBC team that the conference has a variety of speakers with prestigious backgrounds to give students a competitive edge.  While the conference is the main focus, events and workshops will be held to further refine and develop skills crucial to starting a successful career.
value.Summary: ISBC is designed to connect leading professionals with students aspiring for a career in the sports business world. Through an annual conference, ISBC fosters relationships and provides a greater knowledge of the sports industry.

value.Name: Illinois Student Association of Music Scholars
value.Description:
The object of Illinois Student Association of Music Scholars (ISAMS) shall be to augment the academic experience, scholarship and community of students in musicology (historical and ethnographic) and related fields of music scholarship, including music theory, music education, and composition through:

- Fostering community interaction and dialogue through social engagement

- Scholarly support and critical dialogue

- Professional development

- Organizational support for student initiatives, including (but not limited to) new student welcoming events, conferences, invited guest speakers, and writing support groups

Regular meetings may include reading group and writing group sessions, professional development roundtables, social events, opportunities for students to present scholarship, new student welcomes, and other types of activities.

Members of the Illinois Student Association of Music Scholars may include students enrolled in academic music programs (Historical Musicology, Ethnomusicology, Music History, Music Theory, Composition, and Music Education), students with minors in these departments, and graduate and undergraduate students with an interest in these areas.

Leaders are selected by members in attendance at the meeting in question.
value.Summary: The Illinois Student Association of Music Scholars (ISAMS) seeks to augment the academic experience, scholarship, and community of students in musicology and related fields of music scholarship through community interaction and social engagement.

value.Name: Illinois Student Chapter of the American Veterinary Medical Association
value.Description: The purpose of the Illinois Student Chapter of the American Veterinary Medical Association is to promote a spirit of friendly professionalism and leadership among students attending the veterinary college.
value.Summary: The purpose of the Illinois Student Chapter of the American Veterinary Medical Association is to promote a spirit of friendly professionalism and leadership among students attending the veterinary college.

value.Name: Illinois Student Chapter of the Foundation for Veterinary Dentistry
value.Description:
"The Foundation for Veterinary Dentistry operates exclusively for charitable, scientific, or educational purposes and was founded to:

  1. To educate the public about the importance of oral health in animals.
  2. To advance the understanding of the science of veterinary dentistry among all veterinarians.
  3. To further the knowledge of the veterinary and related professions through education of veterinarians, veterinary technicians and other health-care professionals interested in veterinary dentistry about effective veterinary oral health care delivery.
  4. To provide funding to colleges of veterinary medicine, veterinary technician schools, or other institutions, entities or individuals approved for funding by the Foundation to enhance the education of their students, provide appropriate equipment to facilitate teaching and delivery of effective oral care, and to support research projects in the field of veterinary oral health."

The Illinois Student Chapter of the Foundation for Veterinary Dentistry (ISCF4VD) strives to develop veterinary dentistry knowledge among the students in the College of Veterinary Medicine. Furthering the ideals of our parent organization, ISCF4VD provides lectures, hands-on experiences, and valuable contacts to enhance education in this very important field.
value.Summary: The Illinois Student Chapter of the Foundation for Veterinary Dentistry (ISCF4VD) strives to develop veterinary dentistry knowledge among the students in the College of Veterinary Medicine.

value.Summary: Our organization focuses on the health and diseases of wild animals in relation to their biology, conservation, research, and interactions with humans, domestic animals, and zoological species

value.Name: Illinois Student Chapter of the Women's Veterinary Leadership Development Initiative
value.Description:
Taken from the national organization's website:

"The veterinary profession has undergone a great demographic shift over the past 25 years, but the change in leadership hasn’t kept pace. Women, now more than half of the profession and rising, need to be better represented in leadership roles if we’re to deliver on the promise of veterinary medicine to society."

The Women's Veterinary Leadership Development Initiative seeks to identify those women within various aspects of the veterinary field, and highlight their leadership abilities. It is our goal to help develop these leadership abilities in order to assist our members in reaching their maximum potential. At a collegiate-level, the aim of this organization is to instill the confidence and skill set in female veterinary students to be able to achieve any leadership role within our field. By providing a strong, supportive group of members, and an active communication network between members and other female veterinary professionals, we hope to change the discussion about the roles of women within the veterinary profession.
value.Summary: An organization dedicated to helping women in veterinary medicine reach their maximum potential as leaders in various aspects of the veterinary medicine field.

value.Name: Illinois Student Council on Family Relations
value.Description:
ISCFR is a professional student organization for graduate and undergraduate students interested in families and family relationships.

ISCFR organizes at least one volunteer/fundraising activity for a local community organization and one speaker/professional development activity each semester. We also typically have a couple of social events throughout the year. ISCFR is a good way to get involved in a professional organization and is a great resume booster.

What are the benefits of joining?
* professional development
* networking
* developing leadership skills
* social events and activities
* involvement in your local community
value.Summary: The purpose of ISCFR is to provide educational, service learning, and professional development activities for students, while promoting family education and awareness in our local community.

value.Name: Illinois Student Officials Association
value.Description:
illiniofficials@gmail.com 

In conjunction with Campus Recreation, the purpose of ISOA is to connect student sport officials with officiating opportunities primarily within the University of Illinois campus community. ISOA and its members will provide the opportunity to utilize student officiating for athletic competitions. ISOA will assist in the scheduling and payment of sport officials (Basketball, Soccer, Flag Football, Dodgeball, Softball, Baseball, Volleyball, etc… ). Designated members will also offer assistance for student groups to administer tournament rules, format, and provide equipment for athletic competition.

 Furthermore, this will provide a forum outside of intramural activity events for student sport officials to officiate organized sporting contests. The organization strives to give student sport officials the opportunity to gain experience beyond the Intramural Activities program. We will foster a community of students on campus that enjoy sport officiating, and have a desire to obtain new experiences within the profession.
value.Summary: In conjunction with Campus Recreation, ISOA connects student sport officials with officiating opportunities primarily within the University of Illinois community. ISOA will provide the opportunity to utilize officials for athletic competition.

value.Name: Illinois Synchronized Skating
value.Description:
Synchronized skating is a team sport in which 8-20 skaters perform a routine together. It uses the same judging system as singles, pairs, and dance, and is characterized by teamwork, intricate formations, challenging step sequences, and fast and confident skating. All teams perform a free skate routine with required, well-balanced program elements. Elements in synchronized skating include blocks, circles, wheels, lines, intersections, moves in the field, moves in isolation, no-hold blocks, spins, and pairs moves. The variety and difficulty of elements require that each team member is a highly skilled individual skater.
Our vision for the future of IllinoiSkating is to achieve continuous growth, individually and collectively, in an inclusive environment that fosters unconditional respect and support.
value.Summary: Illinois Synchronized Skating at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign is an organization for people with backgrounds in all disciplines of figure skating that desire to compete as a team at the Open Collegiate, Collegiate and/or Senior levels.

value.Name: Institute of Communications Research Graduate Student Organization
value.Description:
Today nearly everyone recognizes the importance of knowing everything possible about communication. Information technologies, media mergers and computer marvels are daily convention. However, intellectually significant research and its associated pedagogical issues on communication is not commonplace. Work of enduring quality develops from comprehending the gravity and stature of the subject—and communication is among the most challenging and fascinating areas that humankind has been inspired to address. Additionally, research in this area must extend outside of pure intellectual endeavors and into understandings of our everyday lives and practices. In this vein, the ICR Grad Student Organization is dedicated to the facilitation of research and pedagogy of contemporary communications, media, and critical/cultural studies both through intellectual inquiry and practical understandings of the ways in which these forces shape our everyday lives. The organization has been created with two main goals in mind:

1) To involve the broader UIUC community to the critical issues surrounding media economics, organization and structure; media policy; political economy of the media; new technologies and new media; telecommunications; advertising and consumer research; media ethics, media and communications history; social and cultural studies of science and medicine; popular culture and film; race ethnicity and gender; democracy and the media; and global/international communications. This involvement can include public lectures on cutting-edge issues, practical workshops on media technologies/production, seminars on pedagogical development and trends, and strategies for integrating theoretical and critical inquiry into the development of personal and professional skills.

2) To facilitate the networking and interpersonal relationships of ICR graduate students, as representative of the UIUC intellectual tradition, into to broader professional community of communications and media scholars.

With one of the most renowned communications Ph.D. programs in the world, ICR grad students are uniquely positioned to work to advance these goals. As such, the ICR Grad Student Organization is dedicated to crossing the boundaries of established academic disciplines, drawing on a holistic intellectual heritage grounded in liberal arts, the traditions of social scientific research and cultural interpretation, a thorough spirit of critical inquiry, and a commitment to extending the intellectual into the everyday.
value.Summary: The ICR Grad Student Organization is dedicated to the facilitation of research and pedagogy of contemporary communications, media, and critical/cultural studies.

I-HEAL is an opportunity for us as health care students to explore different CAM methods and learn how they can benefit our patients' health treatment plan. In addition to professional enrichment, I-HEAL provides students the opportunity to connect with like-minded peers and explore our own well-being.

value.Name: International Socialist Organization - Urbana-Champaign
value.Description:
The ISO is building a socialist alternative in a world of poverty, oppression and war. Our organization participates in many different struggles for justice and liberation today, while working toward a future socialist society, free of all exploitation and oppression, and built on the principles of solidarity and democracy.

We are a U.S. organization with branches and members in about 40 cities and connections to other socialists around the world. We organize in the here and now against injustice and for reforms that will benefit the working class and oppressed. These struggles are important in their own right, but they are also building blocks for a movement to achieve a socialist society. At our meetings and in our publications, we discuss the political issues and movements of today, along with the rich history of past struggles from below and the ideas of the Marxist tradition dedicated to achieving socialism.
value.Summary: We are the UIUC branch of the International Socialist Organization. We participate in many different struggles for justice and liberation today, while working toward a future socialist society.

We also offer ethnic-specific groups like Indian Faith Journey for those who are interested. Please check us out on Facebook for updates!
value.Summary: ISC connects intl. students to Americans as we get together for fun activities. Along the way, our volunteers want to help students adjust to American culture and hope to build life-long friendships. Our volunteers are a part of local Christian ministries

value.Description: iRobotics is a community of students interested in competing in JSDC, VRCC, and other robotics competitions, as well as spreading the word of science and technology to the community.  Student leadership, organization, and time management are demonstrated in this club as we divide work and create schedules to finish projects on time.  The team is composed of three sub-teams: Mechanical, Electrical, and Software; each area works on their own specified tasks.  In addition, all club members are expected to participate in community outreach events, including mentoring, volunteering, judging, and demonstrating.  This organization aims to be a well-represented group of professional students who not only wish to hone their own engineering skills, but also share their excitement and passion for robotics and engineering with their community in an effort to inspire more young men and women to come to appreciate science and technology in the same way.
value.Summary: iRobotics is a community of students interested in competing in JSDC, VRCC, and other robotics competitions, as well as spreading the word of science and technology to the community.

value.Name: Japanese Animation Club
value.Description:
This club tries to give an intro to anime appreciation while also catering to long-time fans. We try to teach a sense of tolerance towards those in any subculture, and merge with other clubs very often. During our screeinings, we try and show animes that reflect Japanese culture more accurately than the ones commonly on TV, and also take pride in conducting what is often stigmatized in a very professional matter. Anime is an art, and we as a club treat it as such.

Our reddit website is https://www.reddit.com/r/uiucjac/. Pleas use this for contact

日本語会話テーブル（JCT)は日本語学習者と日本語ネイティブが気軽で愉快な交流ができるスペースを提供しています。そして、日本語会話テーブルはプロフェショナルとキャリアネットワーキングをする場所でもあります。金曜日の午後５時半から午後７時まで開催しており、ユニオンの地下で集合しております。大歓迎です！

value.Name: Japanese Mahjong Club
value.Description: Japanese Mahjong Club is a club for all people who are interested in mahjong, especially Japanese mahjong. As one of the oldest board games, mahjong is not only a way to entertain, but also a challenging sport which needs a high level of analysis ability. In this club, we learn about mahjong from various resources (including past competitions), analyze the data and possibility behind mahjong and practice with other members or online. It doesn’t matter if you are totally new to Japanese mahjong, everyone in this organization is ready to help you! We also have a team preparing for online competitions (such as Tenhou). People who are interested in the algorithm is also welcomed – we have projects related to mahjong too! To learn more about mahjong, just join us! We are waiting for you!
value.Summary: A club for all people who are interested in Mahjong, especially Japanese Mahjong. Learn, analyze and practice Mahjong with our members at UIUC!

value.Name: Jasmine Field Orchestra

The ensemble consists of two sections: Chinese instruments and Western instruments, and works on arranging pieces that involve both traditional Chinese and western music elements.
value.Summary: An Orchestra that plays both Chinese & Western music

value.Name: Jewish Law Students Association
value.Description:
The Illinois Jewish Law Students’ Association (JLSA) is an organization which promotes a community within the law school, to educate students about Jewish-American legal concerns, to provide information to students about places of worship, and to create a community within which students can come together to celebrate holidays.

JLSA helps students explore career opportunities through meeting with practicing attorneys, judges, government employees, and other professionals in the setting of JLSA-sponsored social events.

Many of our programs are co-sponsored by other Illinois Law School groups and groups at other Illinois graduate schools. We have also had the continued support and partnerships with Chabad House, Hillel and JET at Illinois.

Please e-mail us or any of the board members for more information about JLSA or Jewish issues at Illinois. If you would like to be added to our weekly email list, please send an email to jlsa@lillinois.edu.
value.Summary: The Illinois Jewish Law Students' Association promotes a community within the law school, educates students about Jewish-American legal concerns, informs students about places of worship, and brings students together to celebrate holidays.

value.Name: Kappa Delta Chi Sorority, Inc.
value.Description:
Our vision is to empower women, regardless of ethnicity, sexuality or race, at the university level to become leaders of their community by serving and educating underserved communities within and around the Champaign-Urbana area by providing different opportunities for their growth. “Sisters are different flowers from the same garden…” Here at the Univeristy of Illinois we intend to continue the KDChi mission statement and continue to promote the values of Unity, Honesty, Integrity and Leadership among women ensuring that they continually strive to do their best.


Mission Statement: Kappa Delta Chi Sorority, Inc. is a Latina founded,501(c)(7), national sorority who aims to achieve professional development, academic excellence, and graduation of all its members; an organization dedicated to community service to their local university communities with an emphasis on the Hispanic/Latino population. Through numerous service events, sisterhood retreats and academic and cultural workshops, KDChi’s learn more about themselves and each other. They sprout into impacting leaders and help guide the next generation to success. KDChi is a non-traditional sorority full of diverse members and eager young ladies ready to make a difference in their communities. With your sisters, anything is possible.
value.Summary: "Leading with Integrity, United through Service"

value.Name: Kazakh Student Association
value.Description:
Kazakhstan is a home for more than 100 different nationalities and ethnic groups and a leading country in Central Asia in economic growth and spread of democracy and peace.

Each year Ministry of Education of Kazakhstan sends its best students to study overseas. About 30 kazakh students are currently pursuing their academic career at University of Illinois and approximately 30 kazakhs are studying at English Language Institute at UIUC.

Increasing number of kazakh students needs organization which can help Kazakhs to preserve national uniqueness among other many nationalities studying at university and contribute to harmony and peace among students. Besides we would like to share our cultural heritage, language and ideas with other students and university faculty members. Our organization intends to organize coffee hours, picnics, sports games, parties on Kazakhstan national holidays and to participate in intercultural events, world’s fair and spread cultural diversity among students in order to promote peace, tolerance, and friendship.

value.Name: Kellsie's Krusaders
value.Description:
Kellsie’s Hope was started by Kellsie Marchbanks during her second round of cancer treatment. After her passing in June 2011 of Osteosarcoma, the Marchbanks family formed Kellsie’s Hope Foundation Inc, to celebrate the life of this remarkable young woman and to continue the work she started from her hospital bed.

Kellsie’s Hope Foundation Inc, mission is to lighten the load of families that have children suffering from cancer by offering support for trips, and gifts that might otherwise be unattainable to a child with cancer. Kellsie’s foundation is also dedicated to raising funds to support research into childhood cancers.
value.Summary: Kellsie's Krusaders raises funds for Kellsie's Hope Foundation Inc, which provides support for trips and gifts to children with cancer. The organization is also dedicated to raising funds to support research.

value.Name: Kendo Naginata Club
value.Description: Kendo and Naginata are a part of Japanese Budo, which is a philosphical system that includes physical practice along with mental training. The ultimate purpose of such practice is the continual cultivation of a strong body and mind as well as the mutual development of human character.
value.Summary: The purpose of this organization is to provide an environment for those affiliated with the university to study the philosophical way of life embodied by the Japanese arts of  Kendo and Naginata, as well as physically to practice these arts together.

value.Name: Korea Campus Crusade for Christ
value.Description:
WIN BUILD, TRAIN, SEND!

"All authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me. Therefore, GO and MAKE disciples of all nations, baptizing them in the name of the Father and of the Son and of the Holy Spirit, and teaching them to obey everything I have commanded you. And surely, I am with you always, to the very end of the age," Mathew 28:18-20

Korea Campus Crusade for Christ (KCCC) is an international ministry committed to help fulfilling the Great Commission of Jesus Christ in this generation. KCCC is one of the ministry groups under Campus Crusade for Christ as known as CRU. Campus Crusade for Christ has over 25,000 full-time staff workers and 500,000 trained associated staff workers in 191 countries around the world and they are fully dedictated to the cause of fulfilling the Great Commision.

KCCC is a campus ministry that helps reaching college students with a vision to see all nations hearing the message of Jesus Christ. KCCC ministry extends across the US including California and New York metropolitan universities as well as in Atlanta, Chicago, Urbana-Champaign, and Hawaii in the US.
value.Summary: KCCC is dedicated to creating movements on campuses through believers who are committed to connecting people to Christ. We are here to win people for Christ, to build each other up and to send them out to the world as sincere Christ-centered followers.

value.Name: Korean Cultural Center
value.Description:
Goals

The goal of Korean Cultural Center (KCC) is to raise awareness and appreciation of Korean culture and functions as a place to foster multiculturalism and inter-cultural exchanges in the United States . The center actively seeks to strengthen Korean identity of Koreans and ethnic Koreans in globe. KCC collaborates with various organizations to provide array of services to the Korean community . 

Mission Statement
KCC at UIUC promotes and raises awareness of Korean culture within the Urbana Champaign community. By so doing, the Center simultaneously functions as a central place to increase diversity in the United States and strengthen Korean identity among Korean diasporic communities.
The Center works with various groups and institutions to identify culturally and linguistically competent services and resources for the Korean community. The Center focuses on the accessibility of resources and services identified for those in need.
value.Summary: The goal of Korean Cultural Center (KCC) is to raise awareness and appreciation of Korean culture and functions as a place to foster multiculturalism and inter-cultural exchanges in the United States.

value.Description: Korean Student Association is dedicated to make a difference in the Urbana-Champaign community. Our mission is to help Korean students achieve their goals during college years and beyond. We do so by hosting career fairs and providing them with opportunities such as volunteer work or language and cultural diffusion to become active members of the society. We also provide sports and social events for them to enhance interaction with other Korean and non-Korean students. By introducing Korean culture to domestic students, we hope to familiarize domestic students to the culture and to encourage them to become the leaders of the globalized and diversified society.
value.Summary: Korean Student Association strives to promote Korean culture on campus and provide career and networking services to Korean students and those interested in Korea and Korean culture

value.Name: Korean-American Scientists and Engineers Association YG
value.Description:
[KSEA YG] Korean-American Scientists and Engineers Association Young Generation,

formerly known as [KESS] Korean Engineering and Science Society,

is a Registered Student Organiation at the University of illinois at Urbana-Champaign since January 2013.

Our aim is 

1. To share the interests in the same academia especially in Engineering and Science,

2. To help other Colleagues who are having trouble on their paths to the Future,

3. To Give the Opportunity to those who want to participate the organization activities,

4. To Set up the Networks among the Alumni, the Undergraduate, and the Graduate students.

We not only have Korean members but also have Non-Korean staff in our group to let students have the opportunities to get along with those people who have different cultures.
value.Summary: We represent Korean-American Scientists and Engineers Association as a YG chapter in UofI. Our members and staff work to improve and provide more opportunities for the Korean science and engineering students through mentoring, seminars, and more.

value.Name: Krannert Center Student Association
value.Description:
The Krannert Center Student Association (KCSA) is one of the longer running registered student organizations (RSOs) on the University of Illinois campus. We're comprised of students from all disciplines (mostly non-arts majors) who:
- Have a passion for the arts
- Want to contribute to the life of this premier university-based performing arts center
- Enjoy FREE tickets to some of the most sought-after performances
- Heighten their volunteering experience by leading on adboard
- Serve as ushers welcoming patrons from all over the world to experience life-affirming performances (not a bad gig)

Our members range from freshmen to grad students and study everything from music to business to engineering. We believe the arts are for everyone and serves as a place for people of all backgrounds and interests to come together!
value.Summary: KCSA provides students the opportunity to volunteer as ushers for shows at the Krannert Center throughout the year. KCSA also hosts social events which have included touring the Krannert Center, and trips to theater performances.

value.Name: Kreating Leaders in Mind & Body
value.Summary: KLIMB is an organization that looks to build strong characters and leaders in our society. This is done through community service, workshops, and events at various places on campus. To be a leader is to be both mentally and spiritually strong.

value.Description:
La Colectiva is student organization at the University of Illinois, which exists to address the challenges faced by the immigrant community within Champaign-Urbana.

Our mission is to advocate for social justice and change on behalf of all immigrants; while simultaneously serving the community by fostering leadership and providing resources through grassroots initiatives.

We meet every other Wednesday at 7 pm in the University YMCA Board Room.

value.Name: Lambda Phi Epsilon
value.Description:
Lambda Phi Epsilon was founded at the University of California, Los Angeles on February 25, 1981, and is the largest Asian-American interest fraternity in the United States, with 58 chapters and more than 12,000 brothers. It is also the first and only internationally recognized Asian-American interest fraternity in the world.

Since our inception, Lambda Phi Epsilon's goals have been to exemplify the highest standards of Academic Performance, Social Experience, Service to the Community, and most importantly Brotherhood among its members.

After recently celebrating our 30th Anniversary in 20011, Lambda Phi Epsilon continues to establish and perpetuate Brotherhood and fellowship among its members. Part of that Brotherhood is expressed in our motto "To be Leaders Among Men." We not only seek to bring together a diverse group of men who share interests, concerns, backgrounds and cultures, but who believe that the strength of many are forged into the power of being one.

Grounded on the principles of wisdom, honor, and courage; our Active Division continues to teach young men principles of leadership and strong moral character. Our Alumni Division then provides a forum in which brothers may apply these beliefs and become true leaders of society. It is that unique life long commitment to lead in every arena of life that makes "the Lambdas" the most respected organization of it's kind.

value.Name: Lambda Theta Alpha Latin Sorority, Inc.
value.ShortName: Lambda Theta Alpha Latin Sorority, Inc.
value.Description:
The FIRST Latina Sorority in the NATION established since 1975 catering towards scholarly excellence, empowerment of Latinas. We partake in cultural & political awareness as well as community activism.


"Latin by Tradition NOT by Definition"

 

Basic Information

Founded on campus:
Spring 2001 at the University of Illinois Urbana -Champaign

General Overview
- Founded at Kean University, NJ in December of 1975
- The purpose of the organization was to create a support group for Latinas pursuing higher education, and unite the Latino community through programs and services
- Established as an academic sorority with goals of community and political activism.
- Oldest and largest Latina-based sorority in the U.S.
- Not an exclusionary organization
- Empowerment of the Universal Women
- Calls, salutes, strolls and hand-signs

- Lambda Theta Alpha has established Graduate & Alumni Chapters.

- Lambda Theta Alpha has established chapters throughout New Jersey, Connecticut, Puerto Rico, New York, Maryland, Florida, California, Pennsylvania, Texas, Arizona, Michigan, Illinois, Virginia, Tennessee, New Mexico, Wisconsin, Georgia, Idaho, North Carolina and Washington.
value.Summary:
The FIRST Latina Sorority in the NATION established since 1975 catering towards scholarly excellence, empowerment of Latinas. We partake in cultural & political awareness as well as community activism.
 "Latin by Tradition NOT by Definition".

value.Name: LAS Leaders
value.Description: LAS Leaders works primarily with the LAS Advancement Office as they plan events throughout the year. Past events include Homecoming festivities, a tour of The Hill in St. Louis, and cooking demonstrations at Spiaggia's in Chicago. Leaders also have a strong presence at ceremonies honoring distinguished professors, graduation events, and admitted student days for incoming freshmen. We are a close knit group comprised of about 30 members ranging from freshmen to seniors in varying disciplines of LAS. When we aren't working events for the College, we are volunteering in the Champaign-Urbana community and organizing social events with each other. We have general meetings once a month to keep everyone updated on all of the events and activities. We encourage our members to work as many events as they can, but also understand the importance of being flexible with people's schedules.
value.Summary: LAS Leaders is a select group of student ambassadors to the college of Liberal Arts and Sciences. Throughout the year we staff alumni events and honors ceremonies and get the opportunity to connect with alumni, faculty, and students.

value.Description: Latinos in Pre-Health is here to provide guidance and academic support to students pursuing a health-related field. We assist health major students by providing opportunities and activities that will enhance their qualifications and increase competitiveness in the application process for graduate/health schools. Whether you’re any one of the numerous pre-health fields such as pre-med, or pursuing a graduate education in the health field, we are here for you.. Through volunteering opportunities, socials, workshops, guest speakers, student panels, medical mission trips, and great leadership opportunities, we hope to create an environment where each of our members can feel welcome and achieve their academic and professional goals.

League members come from all walks of life – united by our shared understanding of the importance of political literacy, we celebrate being non-partisan and diverse in our identities, affiliations, and experiences. Come check us out and find out what you're missing!

All students are encouraged to join our monthly general circle meetings and additional developmental events hosted throughout the acedemic semester.

Look for us on Quad Day!

value.Name: Les Claviers
value.Description:
Les Claviers is for uiuc students who are passionate to music. Les Claviers is consist of four departments. Insturmental, Band, Acapella, and Event committee. Regardless of genre- anyone can join to practice and perform any music pieces. Sharing about music and recommending pieces are encouraged. Help people who want to start playing any instrument. We're neither professional nor music majoring, but try as much as possible to help people finding great pieces of music and developing skills. As club activities, we are planning to host performances in public, such as in Union or else.

In summary,

1) Encourage club members to practice piano and play piano pieces

2) Share and recommend good piano pieces

3) Provide club members opportunity to perform in public

4) Support beginners to enhance their playing skills

 

*Our primary language is Korean. However, it will also be wellcomed whom not speaking Korean.

value.Description: LGBT Greek helps break the misconception that LGBT-identifying men and women do not participate in Greek Life. Along with providing a comfortable space and social group for these individuals, LGBT Greek aims to further the acceptance and inclusion of LGBT-identifying people within the UIUC community and Greek Life.
value.Summary: The purpose of LGBT Greek is to allow members of the Greek community who identify as LGBTQ to find a welcoming, safe, and social environment that adds to the traditional Greek experience on the UIUC campus.

value.Name: Liberty in North Korea
value.Description:
LiNK (Liberty in North Korea) is a national non-profit organization that works to increase awareness about the exploitation of North Korea by its leader Kim Jong-Un. Concentration camps, sex trafficking, and famine are just some of the things that still plague North Korea to this day.

The UIUC chapter of LiNK works to increase awareness on the U of I campus through public demonstrations, documentary screenings, fundraisers, and other events on campus. Some of the events we held are our "We Talk Shift" screening, the 500 fundraiser, LiNK Out Loud, LiNK Apparel sales, and so on.

Be a part of our movement!
Visit and join our FaceBook group here for more information!
Or follow us on Twitter here for updates! 

Contact us with any questions at uiuc.link@gmail.com
value.Summary: LiNK (Liberty in North Korea)'s purpose is to spread awareness about the North Korean crisis, and raise funds to rescue refugees. Our goal is to raise $3,000 each year, which is the approximate amount needed to rescue a N.Korean refugee out of hiding.

value.Name: Life Drawing Club
value.Description:
The Life Drawing Club at the University of Illinois will allow its members to learn and understand the human figure. Through the use of a live model, the members will observe and render the form to their own degree of satisfaction. The club will provide the space, limited materials, and a model. The club will allow for extended time with the model for art students as well as give the opportunity to non-art students to gain this experience. Because Life Drawing classes are generally restricted to art majors, the club will reach out to those interested in life drawing that are unable to register for these courses. 

Furthermore, the Life Drawing Club aims to achieve a sense of community among its members. While the process of drawing may be very independent at times, having feedback, group conversations and ultimately, a sense of comfort is ideal to that process. Along with providing designated time for drawing and practicing the technical approaches of rendering the human form, the club will focus on informal discussions of the work. Having an outlet for conversation about specific work and the arts will unify the group as a community. 

As an extension of the painting program, the Life Drawing Club will consist of a foundation of art students reaching out to the non-art community. The human figure is an approachable subject that will serve as a bridge between those who pursue the fine arts as a hobby and those involved with the fine arts professionally.
value.Summary: The Life Drawing Club at the University of Illinois will allow its members to learn and understand the human figure. Through the use of a live model, the members will observe and render the form to their own degree of satisfaction.

value.Name: MEDLIFE UIUC
value.Description: MEDLIFE is a secular, volunteer-run global health organization whose mission is to help families achieve greater freedom from the constraints of poverty, empowering them to live healthier lives. We seek to achieve this goal through partnering with motivated individuals from poor communities working to improve their access to MEDs: Medicine, Education and community Development. MEDLIFE believes access to quality healthcare, education and personal development are basic human rights. To this end, we commit all our resources to bring Medicine, Education and Development to Low Income Families Everywhere. Along with affiliate chapters, MEDLIFE UIUC works to promote the highest standard of MEDLIFE's goals and reputation within the community. The University of Illinois MEDLIFE chapter brings Illinois students together to raise money and awareness for this global organization.
value.Summary: MEDLIFE UIUC is a new chapter of MEDLIFE. We aim at bringing change through Medicine, Education, and Development at both the national and local level through volunteering, fundraising, awareness, and leadership.

value.Name: Midwestern Robotics Design Competition
value.Description:
The Midwestern Robotics Design Competition (MRDC) Committee is made up of college students from various majors such as Chemical Engineering, Electrical Engineering and Mechanical Engineering. The MRDC has been a source of engineering ingenuity and inspiration ever since its inception in 1987. We provide an outlet for brilliant and inquisitive minds to showcase their skills in science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM).

The MRDC takes place during the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign’s annual Engineering Open House (EOH) in the spring semester. EOH is the main engineering event that takes place on the UIUC campus. Various engineering clubs and organizations all come together to create an exciting learning experience for attendees of all ages. The MRDC has been a mainstay of EOH, bringing in everyone from elementary and middle schoolers to parents and professionals of all fields of study.

If you are interested in being part of the creation and building of the competition, email us at mrdc@lists.illinois.edu!
value.Summary: An annual robotics competition held during Engineering Open House. We plan, design, and build the competition that other robotics teams on campus and from universities across the Midwest compete in.

The Multi-Racial and Multi-Ethnic Student Union will provide a safe space for students of multiracial and multiethnic backgrounds to gather, have shared experiences, and inform others about this unique, and often overlooked, identity.

Our personal mission is as follows:

  • To collaborate with student organizations and campus partners to promote an inclusive and positive campus climate for Mixed students

  • To advocate for the needs and issues facing Mixed students

We will host biweekly meetings which may include dialogues, workshops, guest speakers, movie screenings and potluck celebrations.

A low-maintenance and fun club that is medical orientated. Our purpose is to encourage and nurture passion for problem solving, promote the idea that learning can be both stimulating and entertaining, and to give a taste of science related fields!

We meet once every two weeks (except in December and May due to final exams!) and we will always have snacks!

The chapter will partake in cultural events, interact with Mongolian Cultural Organization chapters at other schools, outreach to potential Mongolian student to attend the University of Illinois, and volunteer to give back to the community. Our chapter is composed of Mongolian students of all majors, however membership is not limited to Mongolian students.

Movement Exchange envisions a world in which dance education is accessible to all, dance is synonymous to service, & dance enables all to achieve their optimal mental, social, and physical well-being.

We value cross-cultural understanding, civic engagement, social equality and inclusion, community empowerment, creative expression, global citizenship, and sustainable dance education.

Sustainable impact. Movement Exchange created year-round, locally staffed dance programs in the communities where we work internationally. We currently have dance programs at three orphanages in Panama and support two foundations in India. Move-Ex at University of Illinois is continuously involved in dance outreach in the community.

value.Name: Muay Thai Club at UIUC
value.Description:
The sport of Muay Thai (Thai Boxing) is one of the fastest growing sports in the world today, while also being part of an ancient tradition of martial arts from Thailand. We are the only club at UIUC that focuses only on the sport of Muay Thai. We provide a respectful and open place to participate in the sport of Muay Thai.

 

We will focus on learning:

 

The martial art

Self defense

Self Confidence

Discipline

Thai arts and culture

 

We encourage anyone who would like to join to participate. We are all inclusive and support any goals or degrees of involvement, from working out to competition. Skills learned in Muay Thai transfer far beyond this club, from physical dexterity to grit and determination. We are supported by an active Muay Thai community here in Champaign-Urbana, as the only place in the community to practice Muay Thai exclusively in the area.
value.Summary: The Muay Thai Club at UIUC provides an open and welcoming space to participate in the sport of Muay Thai. We are the only club at UIUC that focuses only on Muay Thai, with instruction, and seminars from actual Muay Thai fighters.
