value.Name: Multicultural Students Association at LER
value.ShortName: Labor and Employment Relations Multicultural Student Association
value.Description:
Who are We?

MSA is the multicultural organization for the School of Labor and Employment Relations. The group was founded in 1993 as a mechanism to recruit, retain, and support qualified students from underrepresented groups. MSA serves as a support network for students as they embark upon their 18-month stay in the School. Whether you need advice on classes or some classmates to hang out with on the weekend, MSA members do there best to make sure that students feel comfortable during the program.

 

What do we do?

MSA continues to make changes to ensure that the group promotes unity and support to all of its members. Some past activities include:

  • Annual Multicultural Fest
  • Soul Food Sundays
  • Seminars focused on HR related topics
  • Community Service
  • Fundraisers

In addition to the fun that we are currently having, some future plans include:

  • Mentoring incoming students
  • Correspondence with NAAAHR
  • Social events with other graduate minority organizations on campus
  • More fundraisers
value.Summary:
Who are We?
MSA is the multicultural organization for the School of Labor and  Employment Relations. The group was founded in 1993 as a mechanism to recruit, retain, and support qualified students from  underrepresented groups.

value.Name: Music for the Masses
value.Description: Like music? So do we. We bring musicians and music enthusiasts together to form a network of people dedicated to enhancing the music experience here on campus. Our goals are to play at University events, host concerts of our own, provide practice locations, host jam sessions, give free lessons, go to shows together, and everything inbetween. When you're a part of this organization, you'll be running the show. Make the band, make the music, and most importantly, have a blast! So if you're a musician, want to become one, or just love being around music this may be the perfect organization for you.
value.Summary: Music for the Masses is an organization dedicated to expanding live music all over campus. We bring musicians together to collaborate with each other in order to put on killer shows here on campus. So join some bands, have fun, and make music matter!

value.Name: Music Production And Recording Club
value.Description:
This club will teach interested students how to produce and mix music using software such as "Logic Pro", "Garageband", "Ableton Live", and "FL Studio". Artists will be taught how to record, and will be given opportunities to perform at music venues. Software and equipment will be provided by the club, and the UGL studio will be used for recordings.

The club is open to all skill levels. It will be a collaborative learning experience for all involved. The goal of this club is to allow passionate musicians to pursue music production and recording, and learn teamwork, patience and music skills.
value.Summary: This club will teach the art of music production, mixing, and recording to artists in the University of Illinois. Performances will also be part of the club at venues such as The Canopy Club, Krannert Art Center, etc for artists to showcase their music.

value.Name: Muslim Students Association
value.Description: A religious and social group consisting of people of a variety of backgrounds; a means by which students maintain their faith in a college environment; a tool by which non-Muslims learn about Islam. Students strive to build bridges with other religious groups through service activities and interfaith dialogue. Above all, MSA is the stepping stone by which students learn the techniques and acquire the passion to commit to their faith and their communities.
value.Summary: A religious and social group consisting of people of a variety of backgrounds; a means by which students maintain their faith in a college environment; a tool by which non-Muslims learn about Islam. Students strive to build bridges with other religious

value.Name: My Brother's Keeper
value.Description: Based upon maintaining retention, progression and increasing the graduation rate of black males in college. To establish a brotherhood and to create a foundation of academic, mental, and social success for its members at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign.
value.Summary: An initiative to address persistent opportunity gaps faced by young males and to ensure that all young people can reach their full potential and goals.

value.Name: My Sister's Keeper
value.Description:
Adolescent years for teenage girls is a very important time of transition. Many changes physically, emotionally, and within their social lives can be damaging to self-esteem. 7 out of 10 girls believe that they are not good enough or do not measure up in some way, including their looks, performance in school, and relationships with friends and family members. It is essential that these teens maintain a healthy developing lifestyle while gaining a sense of who she is and who she desires to be in the world, as well as to have a 'voice' that she feels confident in.

My Sister’s Keeper will provide these teens with an opportunity to be exposed within an atmosphere of trust and respect in order to form positive relationship with the group member.  MSK empowers teens to help assure them of their strengths and immense potential; Educating them on issues related to their background to encourage them to make a difference.  They will also engage in service events throughout the community to learn the ethics of service which is the reason MSK was founded. 

Female University students dedicated to positively impacting the lives of young girls will be used as a team of facilitators. The girls will meet bi-weekly with University students where a series of planned workshops and educational activities will be held. These meetings will expose them to successful women in the Champaign-Urbana area, build life skills, and a chance to form new friendships. Right away the girls should start to feel empowered and encouraged to make healthy choices in their lives. Overtime they will utilize the skills given into their lives.
value.Summary: My Sister's Keeper is a sisterhood geared towards High School girls who represent a minority. Our goal is to provide inspiring workshops that will empower and educate them in all aspects of life in hopes for the girls to reach their full potential.

value.Name: Myra Bradwell Association for Women Law Students
value.Description: Members focus on the concerns of women, both in the College of Law and in the profession.
value.Summary: Members focus on the concerns of women, both in the College of Law and in the profession.

value.Name: Name Tag Elimination Club
value.Description: Based on Asian Variety shows. This club will have events that recreate games from shows like Running Man and 2 Days 1 Night. The most popular event is name tag elimination which consists of ripping velcro name tags off of people's backs. This game is similar to tag except every participant starts with a velcro name tag. When this name tag is ripped off of the participant, the participant is 'ousted'. First team to elimate all the other members from the opposing team win the event. Different varieties of NTE include free for all eliminations, team based eliminations, survival eliminations, and etc...
value.Summary: Based on Asian Variety shows. This club will have events that recreate games from shows like Running Man and 2 Days 1 Night.

value.Name: National Association of Black Accountants
value.Description:
The University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign's NABA chapter has been on campus for over a decade. We offer our members the opportunity to develop their professional skills through resume writing, professional dress, interviewing workshops, and professional etiquette workshops. NABA encourages networking by inviting corporate representatives to speak to the general assembly, as well as visiting their offices. In addition, we encourage personal growth and academic excellence through study groups and various activities. 

Although, we are the National Association of Black Accountants, we do not restrict membership to only African Americans and Accountants. NABA is devoted to serving all students seeking business development regardless of classification, race or major.
value.Summary: To address the professional needs of our members and build leaders that will shape the future of the business world.

value.Name: National Association of Black Journalists
value.Description: NABJ is a national organization that assists in the understanding, development and continuation of journalism and journalism research, especially at the current time where many feel that media forms are changing with a seeming decline in newspapers. Our purpose is to provide networking, career and scholastic opportunities for journalism students in both broadcast and print media. Opportunities are open to any student interested, whether in the field as a major or not.
value.Summary: NABJ is a national organization that assists in the understanding, development and continuation of journalism and journalism research, especially at the current time where many feel that media forms are changing with a seeming decline in newspapers.

value.Name: National Engineering Mentors Organization
value.Description:
National Engineering Mentors Organization (NEMO) began as a student-run mentorship program at Tufts University in Spring 2013 and has since then more than tripled in size. NEMO improves the higher education experience by enabling students to leverage the experience of their peers through mentoring relationships.

Once a student is paired as a mentee, he/she has a peer mentor to help him/her succeed by sharing advice on academics, career development and overall college success.

Mentees have access to valuable advice and mentors gain leadership experience and have a chance to hone their communication skills and make connections.
value.Summary:
NEMO’s mission is to bring mentoring opportunities to students in Engineering and Computer Science.

Our program will pair first and second-year students with upperclassmen mentor within their major and interest.

value.Name: National Organization for Business and Engineering
value.Description: NOBE Illinois is the University of Illinois Chapter of the National Organization for Business and Engineering (NOBE), a national society uniting business, management, and engineering organizations from universities coast to coast. NOBE strives to produce and refine leadership internally and develop professional skills in our members that can be translated into success in the business world.
value.Summary: NOBE Illinois is the University of Illinois Chapter of the National Organization for Business and Engineering (NOBE), a national society uniting business, management, and engineering organizations from universities coast to coast.

value.Name: National Organization for Women Campus Affiliate Group
value.Description: To take action to bring women into the mainstream of American society, exercising all the privileges and responsibilities thereof, in truly equal partnership with men.
value.Summary: To take action to bring women into the mainstream of American society, exercising all the privileges and responsibilities thereof, in truly equal partnership with men.

value.Name: National Retail Federation
value.Description: 1. The purpose of the University of Illinois National Retail Federation is to bring together like-minded students interested in the retail industry, educate them on all aspects of the industry, and create networking opportunities among one another and with retail companies for future opportunities within the industry.  This organization will enable its members to not only explore areas of interest within the retail industry, but it will also equip its members with leadership and personal development opportunities.
value.Summary: The UIUC National Retail Federation is a student association branching off of the National Retail Federation aiming to provide students with retail opportunities and educate them on industry trends.

value.Name: National Society of Black Engineers
value.Description:
NSBE's mission is to increase the number of culturally responsible Black engineers who excel academically succeed professionally, and positively impact the community. NSBE develops its membership into responsible professional leaders through community service, pipeline development (pre-college outreach), and the promotion of STEM. NSBE is dedicated to creating the best engineers for a brighter future.

For more info, email nsbe.uiuc.pres@gmail.com
value.Summary: NSBE's mission is to increase the number of culturally responsible Black engineers who excel academically, succeed professionally, and positively impact the community.  We strive to stimulate and develop student interest in the S.T.E.M. fields.

value.Name: National Society of Collegiate Scholars
value.Description: To foster the principles of leadership, scholarship, and service.
value.Summary: The National Society of Collegiate Scholars (NSCS) at UIUC is a chapter of a nation-wide honors society dedicated to leadership, scholarship and service.  Our members participate in a variety of service projects, as well as social events.

value.Name: National Student Speech Language and Hearing Association
value.Description: NSSLHA is a national organization for graduate and undergraduate students interested in the study of normal and disordered human communications. Students involved in NSSLHA have opportunities at both the local and national level to increase their knowledge about careers in communication disorders such as Speech Pathology and Audiology while building leadership and professional skills.
value.Summary: NSSLHA is the national organization for graduate and undergraduate students interested in the study of normal and disordered human communication.

value.Name: Native American and Indigenous Student Organization
value.Description: The Native American and Indigenous Student Organization serves our campus as a community for Native or Indigenous students and as an educational source for the student body on Native American cultures past and present. We celebrate and respect the concept of Indigeneity and often bring speakers in to discuss contemporary issues, conduct crafting workshops, and teach traditional cultural elements like music, dance, and singing.
value.Summary: We are a cultural and educational student organization that celebrates indigeneity, serves to educate the student body on Native American issues, and provides a community for Native people on campus and in the community.

value.Name: Naval Reserve Officer Training Corps
value.Description: To develop midshipmen morally, mentally and physically and to imbue them with the highest ideals of duty, honor and loyalty in order to commission college graduates as naval officers who possess a basic professional background, are motivated towards a career in the Naval Service, and have a potential for future development in mind and character so as to assume the highest responsibilities of command, citizenship and government.
value.Summary: To develop midshipmen morally, mentally and physically and to imbue them with the highest ideals of duty, honor and loyalty in order to commission college graduates as naval officers who possess a basic professional background, are motivated towards a

value.Name: Navigators
value.Description: To engage with interested students to know Jesus Christ personally, understand their created identity, and reveal their Creator to others through real life situations that include mentoring, Bible Study, trips, and fun activities.
value.Summary: To engage with interested students to know Jesus Christ personally, understand their created identity, and reveal their Creator to others through real life situations that include mentoring, Bible Study, trips, and fun activities.

value.Name: Net Impact
value.Description:
Net Impact is an international nonprofit organization whose mission is to make a positive impact on society by growing and strengthening a community of new leaders who use business to improve the world.

The mission of our Illinois MBA chapter is to develop learning, project, and career opportunities, that encompass corporate responsibility, social entrepreneurship, and environmental sustainability.
value.Summary: Net Impact is an international nonprofit organization whose mission is to make a positive impact on society by growing and strengthening a community of new leaders who use business to improve the world.

value.Name: Netjer
value.Description: The purpose of Netjer is to create more positive enlightenment and views of African diaspora and to understand the roots and history of African American Culture.This is a great opportunity for anyone to learn about African American Cultural influence in America and how it shaped America today.
value.Summary: Netjer is a African American Cultural Association. This organization is for Cultural Clarity and American History of Black people and for others to understand the different realms of of African American Culture in America and why it's important.

value.Name: New Age of Champaign-Urbana Project Chapter
value.Description:
The New Age of Champaign-Urbana Project is a chapter of the New Age of Chicago Project, a project under the nonprofit organization, Natural Path Nutrition Inc. The project was created as an incubator for entrepreneurial, socially conscious young adults to create new approaches and methods for community development. As a result, members of the registered student organization will be able to contribute to what projects or programs the organization runs.

The mission of the New Age of Chicago Project is to mobilize the youth to find solutions to the issues that affect us. The New Age of Champaign-Urbana Project is dedicated to the Black and minority students on the campus of University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign and the communities within the Champaign and Urbana area to bring awareness to the social, political, and economic issues that affect us and to bring about solutions to those issues. Just a few of the issues that we will focus on, but not limited to are:

  • Racial health disparities
  • The lack of Black representation in education
  • Socioeconomic disparities
  • Homelessness

The New Age of Champaign-Urbana Project will do work on and off the campus. Members of the New Age of Champaign-Urbana Project will become engaged with the community by:

  • Running Natural Path Nutrition Inc. authorized educational programs at local elementary and high schools*
  • Conducting a yearly health and wellness fair off-campus for the Champaign-Urbana area
  • Training people to become volunteers/ambassadors for Gift of Hope
  • Conducting food and clothes drives to donate to homeless outreach program
  • Volunteering at homeless shelters and food pantries
  • Working on the annual New Age of Awareness Rally 2017 held in Chicago
  • Conducting info sessions on organ donation (by certified ambassadors/volunteers of Gift of Hope)
  • Conducting a monthly educational session on how to organize and mobilize for change

Special Internship Component to the RSO*

Members of the New Age of Champaign-Urbana Project will have the ability to conduct educational programs at local elementary and high schools during the semesters and/or during the summer. Those who will participate in this special component will be nonpaid interns with Natural Path Nutrition Inc. Because this is a special component to the RSO, not everyone is eligible to participate. Those who wish to intern with Natural Path Nutrition Inc. must fill out and apply. If accepted, applicants will go through a training program on what to teach and how to teach the curriculum.
value.Summary: The Champaign-Urbana chapter of the New Age of Chicago Project under Natural Path Nutrition Inc. The mission of the New Age of Chicago Project is to mobilize the youth to find solutions to the political, social, and economic issues that affect us.

value.Name: New Brown Empire
value.Summary: New Brown Empire is an organization aimed at empowering brown communities through apparel. Our organization hopes to encourage productive cross cultural dialogue, promote intercultural understanding through an intersectional lens, and be an ally to all.

value.Name: New Revels Players
value.Description: The New Revels Players is student theater troupe at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign. Founded in 2000, its members took inspiration from the Revels Players, a classic drama troupe run by university students and faculty in the 1970s. Today, the group performs a variety of contemporary and classic works, including Arthur Miller’s Death of a Salesman and Aristophanes’ Clouds.
value.Summary: The NRP student theater troupe performs everything from student-written work to contemporary classics. Be a part of the plays you love through acting, directing or tech work.

value.Name: No Comment Co-Ed A Cappella
value.Description: To spread co-ed a cappella entertainment throughout the U of I Campus.  We love to sing and have a good time performing!
value.Summary: To spread co-ed a cappella entertainment throughout the U of I Campus.  We love to sing and have a good time performing!

value.Name: No Strings Attached
value.Description:
No Strings Attached is a coed A Cappella Group at the University of Illinois at Champaign-Urbana. Auditions for the group occur in the first couple weeks of school. Be sure to check out the No Strings Attached table on Quad Day (the Sunday before classes begin) to ask questions and sign up for an audition slot.  If you have a passion for music and want to try singing A Cappella in college, don't hesitate to audition.

We're the only UIUC A Cappella group to feature a mix of pop, jazz, and r&b music, so come check out our unique blend of music!
value.Summary: Coed A Cappella Group - Pop/Jazz/R&B

value.Name: Novaree
value.Description:
We are a group of students at the University of Illinois that is hosting a STEM based youth seminar, Illinois NOVAREE, in the spring semester. We’ve had positive feedback from youths, and parents in our first two years and we’ve decided to create an RSO so that local youth can enjoy this clinic for years to come! Many of our participants never knew that hands-on Science, Technology, Engineering, and Math (STEM) could be so much fun! Our mission is to excite local youth about STEM and to encourage them to pursue careers in these fields.

 

A wide range of STEM classes—including aviation, robotics, chemistry, radio, railroading, architecture, and so much more—are taught by University of Illinois students who are thrilled to share their love of STEM subjects with young people. As University of Illinois students, we have access to wonderful resources that enrich our program. Members of the NOVAREE RSO can expect to not only partake in volunteering but also help expand the NOVAREE each year.

 

The curriculum is designed to engage and excite everyone—even those who don’t love STEM subjects at school. These classes are designed around the Boy Scout merit badge/Nova awards, and the Girl Scouts Imagine awards. Our classes thus offer the opportunity for participating boy scouts and girl scouts to earn their respective merit badges, as we are affiliated with the Prairie Lands Council (Boy Scouts Council 172) and the local Girl Scout chapter; however, we are looking to expand our demographic beyond just the boy scouts and girl scouts in the upcoming years.

 

We are a non-profit organization; however, we do charge a small registration fee for participants of the event to pay for direct expenses incurred such as materials used in the classes, event patches, and volunteer t-shirts. We have been careful to keep registration costs to a minimum, so no students are excluded. NOVAREE’s success in its first two years has inspired us to reach out to more students, to provide more young people with this amazing opportunity to engage in interactive STEM learning on a world-ranked university campus.
value.Summary: Novaree is an organization dedicated to STEM outreach to middle school and high school aged youth. In recent years NOVAREE has partnered with the numerous RSOs on campus to host a STEM based outreach clinic on campus.

value.Name: Numenor Foam Fighting
value.Description: Have fun while safely and creatively re-enacting medieval combat.
value.Summary: A branch of the international battle game known as Belegarth in Champaign-Urbana, Illinois.  Belegarth is a full contact sport based on medieval combat (much like paintball with swords).

value.Name: Nutritional Sciences Graduate Student Association
value.Description: To provide a means of communication among Nutritional Sciences graduate students and between students and faculty of Nutritional Sciences.
value.Summary: To provide a means of communication among Nutritional Sciences graduate students and between students and faculty of Nutritional Sciences.

value.Name: Odd Request Improv
value.Description: To learn and perform short form improv comedy.  We accept all levels of experience, practice on campus, and perform for all types of venues.
value.Summary: To learn and perform short form improv comedy.

value.Name: OFF ROUTINE
value.Description: Off Routine is a fashion and art media founded by Mengyu Chen and Yishi Lu. It devotes to bring forth a unique mode of fashion and art through online campaigns and interactive experiences. Meanwhile, Off Routine corporates with local business and designs interesting off-line activities, such as fashion shows, art shows and etc.. Our goal is to encourage people to incorporate the very element of art into everyday life in order to better their lifestyles.
value.Summary: Off Routine is a new media organization founded by Mengyu Chen and Yishi Lu. It devotes to bring forth a unique mode of fashion and art through online campaigns, interactive experiences, as well as off-line activities.

value.Name: Off-Road Illini
value.Description:
Off Road Illini is the Society of Automotive Engineers at the University of Illinois (SAE) Mini-Baja Team. The team designs, builds, and races a single-seat off-road car in the SAE collegiate competition series. Off Road Illini provides an excellent source of hands on knowledge of basic engineering principles, with the reward of the creation of a car by the end of the school year.

http://picasaweb.google.com/offroadillini
value.Summary: Off Road Illini is the Society of Automotive Engineers at the University of Illinois (SAE) Mini-Baja Team. The team designs, builds, and races a single-seat off-road car in the SAE collegiate competition series.

value.Name: Oh My Gosh, Genetically Modified Organisms!
value.Summary: Educate students about the health and environmental risks that genetically modified organisms pose. We aim to implement a positive change on consumerism, environmentalism, and education regarding GMOs.

value.Name: OKNow Ladies
value.Description: The OKnow Ladies are an all-female sketch comedy troupe focusing on writing and performing comedic sketches.
value.Summary: The OKnow Ladies are an all-female sketch comedy troupe.

value.Name: Omega Chi Epsilon - Chemical Engineering Society
value.Description: Omega Chi Epsilon is the National Honor Society for Chemical Engineering. The Society promotes high scholarship, encourages original investigation in chemical engineering and recognizes the valuable traits of character, integrity and leadership. It serves both undergraduate and graduate students and fosters meaningful student-faculty dialogue.
value.Summary: To honor students that have shown outstanding leadership and academic qualities within the discipline of Chemical Engineering.

value.Name: Omega Delta Fraternity
value.Description:
Founded in 1997, Omega Delta was a pioneer in establishing the first diversity-based and professionally-oriented fraternity. Since our inception, our professional network has been rapidly expanding through our general membership and our associated network.

At its core Omega Delta is dedicated to building Men of Principle and Leadership. Our brotherhood aids the individual, builds the Fraternity and strengthens the host academic institution through lifelong devotion to intellectual excellence, high standards of moral conduct, and responsible citizenship. As individuals, we strive for professionalism in character as we continue our pursuit of knowledge and meaning. The achievement of intellectual excellence is an enduring object of a member’s life.

Men of Principle and Leadership calls for the implementation of a comprehensive program of mentoring and incentives that will foster academic excellence. Men of Principle and Leadership set specific annual chapter goals, which relate to the campus-wide GPA and the all-fraternity GPA. Perhaps of greater importance, commitment to the cultivation of the intellect in broader terms requires that the life style or culture of the chapter encourage and support academic achievement. ​Being Men of Principle and Leadership requires members to live by the highest standards of social conduct.
value.Summary: Omega Delta is a social and professional fraternity developing men of principle who lead and never forget how to be civil servants. Become a part of a diverse, networking base for college life and beyond. "Building Brotherhood through Professionalism."

value.Name: Omega Delta Phi Fraternity, Inc.
value.Description: The purpose of this Brotherhood, a Service/Social fraternity dedicated to the needs and concerns of the community, shall be to promote and maintain the traditional values of Unity, Honesty, Integrity, and Leadership. This Brotherhood was founded in order to provide to ANY MAN a diverse fraternal experience that coincides with a higher education.
value.Summary: The purpose of this Brotherhood, a Service/Social fraternity dedicated to the needs and concerns of the community, is and shall be to promote and maintain the traditional values of Unity, Honesty, Integrity, and Leadership.

value.Name: Omega Psi Phi Fraternity, Inc.
value.Description: The mission of Omega Psi Phi Fraternity, Inc. is to foster the growth of men, both college and post college men, by providing an outlet and opportunity to serve the community. We do this by carefully selecting programs in order to achieve this purpose. service that uplifts both campus and surrounding community.
value.Summary: The mission of Omega Psi Phi Fraternity, Inc. is to foster the growth of men, both college and post college men, by providing an outlet and opportunity to serve the community. We do this by carefully selecting programs in

value.Name: Omega Tau Sigma
value.Description:
Omega Tau Sigma encourages and fosters the development of well-rounded, ethical veterinarians and through them creates a better profession on the basis of friendship, cooperation, and respect for their fellow professional.

OTS imparts to its members a desire to serve faithfully and zealously the varied needs of our animal kingdom and inspires these members with the fact that the knowledge of the job well done and the regard of clientele and colleagues far surpasses financial gain.

OTS gives aspiring young veterinary students a chance to analytically survey the veterinary profession to ensure their best talents will be utilized in this profession before they have invested their valuable assets, youth, time, and ambition in the pursuance of an occupation that might leave their best talents dormant.

OTS instills the principles of honesty, morality, resourcefulness, and fraternal love in all its members and, last but not least, gives these young embryonic veterinarians a chance to learn the much valued trait of living happily with a group for the mutual benefit of all.
value.Summary: Omega Tau Sigma is the co-ed professional veterinary service fraternity at U of I. OTS has three main tenants; philanthropy and service, education, and social events, and members work to improve their surrounding community and themselves as veterinarians

value.Name: Open Ears
value.Description:
MISSION STATEMENT

Our mission is to listen. We wish to be there for people seeking an outlet for their problems and become an informal additive, or for some alternative, to therapy. We hope that our efforts may in time lessen the stigma associated with mental illness and seeking help. 

 

OUR GOALS

Create a community of listening, understanding, and trust, where people can feel free to share their experiences and help one another through our tough times.

Raise awareness for mental health issues and help shape the way society views these issues. Host events that will further mental health research, funding, and support.

 

OUR PROGRAMS

Friends - Any individual who is experiencing rough times and wishes to talk to somebody, but does not know where to turn is welcome to come to us. We will pair them with one of our members who will be there for them and listen to them, like a friend. In no way do we think that we can solve everyone's mental hardships, we are not doctors or psychologists, but we hope that us being there for them will make things easier for them.
value.Summary: A group for students helping students. We are here for anyone that just needs someone to talk to, about life, their struggles, college, anything. We also hope to raise awareness for mental health issues and reduce the stigma with getting help.

value.Name: Operations & Technology Management Association
value.Description:
The Operations and Technology Management Association (OTMA) is an organization within the University of Illinois MBA program that explores trends and opportunities in technology and operations. 

OTMA accomplishes this goal by inviting guests from academia and industry to profile topics of interest to our members.  Often times, these guest speakers speak of potential career opportunities to our members.  In addition, OTMA serves as a network of technology professionals who can provide career advice to their peers.  We also maintain relationships with other organizations, faculty and studnets interested in technology and operations in the College of Business.

While OTMA is part of the ILLINOIS MBA program, non-MBA studnets are welcome to attend OTMA events.
value.Summary: The Operations and Technology Management Association (OTMA) is an organization within the University of Illinois MBA program that explores trends and opportunities in technology and operations.

value.Name: Order of Omega
value.Description: Order of Omega is a leadership honor society for members of Fraternity & Sorority organizations. Order of Omega recognizes juniors and seniors who have exemplified high standards in the areas of scholarship, leadership, involvement within their respective organization and within the Fraternity/Sorority, campus, and local community. To date, over 500 chapters have been chartered throughout North America, each sharing the common goal of recognizing the many outstanding student leaders at their institution.
value.Summary: Order of Omega honors Greek student leaders with exceptional academics, values and accomplishments.

value.Name: Origami & Japanese Club
value.Summary: A club devoted to studying the Japanese language and culture as well as enjoying origami, an art deeply engraved in Japan.

value.Name: Orpheum Science Museum Club
value.Description:
The mission of the Orpheum Children's Science Club is to connect undergrad and grad students to the Orpheum Children's Science Museum in downtown Champaign. Students will have the opportunity to build upon the mission of the Children's Science Museum by creating and constructing exhibits, developing programs and curricula for pre-K to 12th grade kids, and taking part decorating for and coordinating family-friendly events in our historic theatre.

Members will be able to gain new skills and experiences, build their portfolios and resumes, make long-lasting connections with members of the community, and will be able to create something uniquely their own and for the benefit of future generations.

Students from all backgrounds are welcome.
value.Summary: Throughout the year, we will work to support the Orpheum Children's Science Museum and its mission to educate, engage and inspire children through the exploration of science and the arts.

value.Name: Orthodox Christian Fellowship
value.Description: The purpose of the O.C.F. is to provide religious, social, and philanthropic activities to all University of Illinois students, faculty, and staff that are interested in the Orthodox Christian Faith.
value.Summary: The purpose of the O.C.F. is to provide religious, social, and philanthropic activities to all University of Illinois students, faculty, and staff that are interested in the Orthodox Christian Faith.

value.Name: Oskees Illini Dance Company
value.Description: Oskees Illini Dance Company is a fun and laid-back way to continue your dance career in college. Most of our dancers come from competitive dance backgrounds, focusing mainly on jazz and contemporary styles of dance. We will hold rehearsals this Fall every Friday from 3-6pm, and Sunday from 9-12pm.  An open practice/clinic will be held Friday, September 22, with auditions the following Sunday, September 24.
value.Summary: The "Oskees" is a dance club at UIUC that performs at different events and shows around campus.  We mainly focus on contemporary and jazz styles of dance with most of our members coming from competitive dance backgrounds.

value.Name: OTCR Consulting
value.Description:
OTCR is the premier student-run consulting group at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign. We are forty top-students, primarily from the Colleges of Engineering and Business, and every semester we work with clients ranging in size from startups to Fortune 500 corporations with service offerings that span Business Strategy, Technology Strategy, and Technology Implemenation. 

Our mission is two-fold:

For our clients - we strive to make their businesses more efficient and productive. OTCR is a unique opportunity to let an energetic workforce with the resources of the University of Illinois tackle your toughest business problems.

For our students - we give our consultants a chance to apply their knowledge to real business problems. It is our hope that the skills our consultants gain in OTCR will help them on their way to becoming tomorrow's leaders.
value.Summary: OTCR is the premier student-run consulting group at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign. We are a group of fifty students (primarily engineering and business) who work on semester long engagements for clients of all sizes and industries.

value.Name: Other Guys
value.Description: To entertian and to serve as ambassadors for the University and Alumni Association
value.Summary: To entertian and to serve as ambassadors for the University and Alumni Association.

value.Name: Out in Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics
value.Description:
oSTEM is a national LGBTQ-affirming organization whose mission is to:

  • Provide services and support for students of sciences, technology, engineering, and mathematics.
  • Create a dynamic network between students and professionals in industry and academia.
  • Actively recruit and address the needs of diverse groups within the LGBTA community, inclusive of those who are historically underrepresented with regards to gender and ethnic background.

Pets Adoption club mainly wants to focus on the adoption of shelter pets.

Most students here are not familiar with the location and adopting process of shelters, so they do not know where to adopt. However, in this club, we are going to inform students the information of various shelters in Champaign and teach them how to adopt pets. Also, we will hold some activities to let people be familiar with shelter animals. Let them see that shelter animals are also as healthy and cute as the pets sold in pet stores.

The reason we hold this club is also encouraging people to adopt rather than buy pets in store, because buying pets can promote puppy mills to grow. 

Besides, our club will provide service for those who do not want to trouble themselves to go to shelter to adopt pets. We are going to help them with the process and contact shelters for them.

value.Name: Pi Tau Sigma
value.Description:
Background and History


    • The first chapter of Pi Tau Sigma, the Illinois Alpha chapter, came into being at the University of Illinois on March 16, 1915 when a group of upperclassmen in mechanical engineering formed an honorary fraternity for the mechanical engineering students. They organized Pi Tau Sigma to foster the high ideals of the engineering profession, to stimulate interest in coordinating departmental activities, to promote the professional welfare of its members, to develop mechanical engineering students with the attributes necessary for effective leadership, and to cultivate a strong notion of the responsibilities of a citizen in society. In addition, they believed that such an organization could foster cooperation between the students and faculty to promote worthwhile student activities.

  • The Illinois Alpha chapter has continued to perform these functions continuously since its inception. Today, Pi Tau Sigma continues to perform these traditions in its daily activities. Through participation in scholarship programs, service programs, events within the Department of Mechanical Engineering and the College of Engineering, social activities, and other countless leadership, personal, and societal development opportunities, Pi Tau Sigma provides its members with the ability to become the most effective mechanical engineers in society.

Objectives

 
  • Foster high ideals in the engineering profession
  • Stimulate and support departmental activities
  • Promote professional welfare
  • Develop leadership and responsibility

Agenda and Past Events

  • Sponsoring and developing a mechanical egnineering tutoring program<
value.Summary: Mechanical Engineering Honor Society

A free-format, noncommercial Internet radio station. Student-run, 24-7, music of any genre, talk, news, anything.

As a student run, free-format, noncommercial radio station, Pizza.fm plans to serve as a creative outlet for those who wish to express themselves through radio. By providing the students the opportunity to DJ their own shows, work in promotions, production or anything of the sort, Pizza.fm's mission is to give students the opportunity to gain radio experience in their own way without worrying about catering to the whims of advertisers that dominate and warp the radio industry today. In turn, we wish to provide listeners exposure to music they wouldn't necessarily hear on a typical radio station, which includes ample promotion of the Champaign-Urbana music scene. 

Run out of Allen Hall, Pizza.fm also serves as an educational outlet for Unit One students as a part of a Living Learning Community. Through classes, collaboration with Allen Hall organizations, events and more, Pizza.fm is an incredibly useful resource in media for Allen Hall residents.

value.Name: Pre-Law Black Law Students Association
value.Description:
The Pre-Law Division was created to further advance the mission of NBLSA. It is our mission to increase the number of culturally responsible Black and minority law students who will eventually become culturally responsible Black and minority attorneys who excel academically, succeed professionally, and positively impact the community.

Students who become members of NBLSA’s Pre-Law Division will join the membership of a prestigious organization that continues to culturally transform the legal community. Since 1963, NBLSA has produced some of the most talented and well-respected members of the legal profession, and our Pre-Law Division is the first to encounter them.

As a member of the Pre-Law Division, you gain access to irreplaceable resources, invaluable networking opportunities, as well as exceptional mentorship. This year, we hope to provide our members with the tools necessary to make law school dreams a reality—from LSAT prep to First Year Success, and everything in between.
value.Summary: The Pre-Law Division was created to further advance the mission of NBLSA: to increase the number of culturally responsible Black and minority law students who will eventually become culturally responsible Black and minority attorneys.

value.Name: Prime Mergers & Acquisitions
value.Description:
Prime was conceived in the spring semester of 2013, when our founders realized that there was a significant educational gap between the academic curricula in the College of Business and the skills and experiences that employers in the investment banking and consulting industries looked for in candidates. While programs like the Golder Academies, the Market Information Lab, and student organizations addressed this issue, there was still a paucity of opportunities for younger students (freshmen and sophomores). Prime was created to bridge that gap and provide these younger students a springboard for their careers.

Prime provides a comprehensive introduction to mergers and acquisitions by simulating a deal throughout the course of a semester, augmented by strong curriculum and guest speakers from industry. In weekly meetings, we cover topics ranging from corporate finance, valuation, and deal structuring, to market evaluation, firm strategy, and post-merger integration. Guest speakers connect these lessons to real life scenarios and provide additional insight - we've had professionals from PwC, William Blair, and J.P. Morgan, and Citi speak so far.

The semester-long simulation serves as the core of the Prime experience. Students form teams for 4-5 students, and play the role of investment bankers advising clients in M&A situations. Throughout the course of the semester, the deal unfolds under the guidance of the student advisor teams, in tandem with topics and situations covered in the curriculum portion of the program. This allows students to build teamworking, negotiation, and communication skills in addition to learning content.
value.Summary: Prime is a student run organization that uses a team-based, semester-long mergers and acquisition simulation and weekly classes to introduce freshmen and sophomores to careers in investment banking and consulting.

value.Name: Promoting Undergraduate Research in Engineering
value.Description:
PURE is an interdisciplinary program in the College of Engineering pairing freshman and sophomore undergraduates with research mentors. The general goal of the program is to encourage underclassmen to explore research at an early stage in their academic career.

The program pairs up 1-2 undergraduate students with a graduate student or professor mentor. Each pair will decide on a project to work on throughout the semester. All undergraduate mentees will write a 1-2 page summary and give a presentation at the end of each semester on what they have done/learned. Mentors benefit since PURE is flexible with their schedules, providing them undergraduate researchers with the desired skill set and inspirations who make great early additions to a research team. The structure of PURE, including events such as the Research Presentation Workshop, also trains mentees about the discipline of engineering research.
value.Summary: PURE is an organization that aims to promote undergraduate research in engineering by assigning underclassmen (mentees) to work with graduate students (mentors) throughout the semester on their respective research topics.

value.Name: Queer Library Alliance
value.Description: The Queer Library Alliance (QLA) is a group for iSchool students to explore ways that librarians and archivists can provide better service for their LGBTQ patrons.  Social aspects of this group include a monthly book club, cake decorating for the edible books festival in the Spring, and general outings throughout the year.  Professional development is a critical part of QLA as well.  For the past six years, QLA has sent a group of students to present at the Midwestern Bisexual, Lesbian, Gay, Trans, Ally College Conference (MBLGTACC).  We hope to continue this tradition as well as find other conferences that will provide students presentation experience. Summer 2014 we made a weekend trip to volunteer at the Gerber/Hart Library and Archives (http://www.gerberhart.org/).  In the future, we plan to repeat this trip, and we may also plan trips to queer library spaces such as the Kinsey Institute for Research in Sex, Gender, and Reproduction in Bloomington, IN (http://www.kinseyinstitute.org/),  and the Leather Archives & Museum (http://www.leatherarchives.org/) located in Chicago, IL
value.Summary: The Queer Library Alliance (QLA) is a group for iSchool students to explore ways that librarians and archivists can provide better service for their LGBTQ patrons. Educational, career development, and social events are organized.

value.Name: Red Bison
value.Description: Red Bison is a registered student organization at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign, and is a program of the University YMCA. Our primary focus is on restoring natural areas on and near campus, though we also like to appreciate nature throughout Illinois. In the past, prairie fires have been called "The Red Bison", with their blazes looming on the horizon reminiscent of huge, flaming stampedes of bison. In the wake of these raging walls of flame, the scorched landscape sprang back to life as the roots and seeds underground bounced back with vigor. These periodic infernos which kept our native prairie a stable biological community for thousands of years. Like the Red Bison of folklore, we also hope to be a positive agent of change in what is left of Illinois’ natural landscape. We get out into nature on a weekly basis to restore Illinois' prairies and woodlands, planting native plants, removing invasive species, and creating landscapes to maintain biological diversity around campus and build our community's ties to nature.
value.Summary: Red Bison is dedicated to the restoration and promotion of natural areas on campus and in the Eastern Illinois region. We protect the environment directly through hands-on work, building healthy ecosystems while we appreciate the outdoors together.

value.Name: Russian Heritage Association
value.Description:
We promote Russian culture and language by providing children and families of the UIUC and Champaign-Urbana communities with classes and cultural events.

Currently our school’s primary focus is working with children who already speak Russian and helping them develop and strengthen it, but we would be happy to see other members of the community reach out to us.

Schedule, classes offered, program for FALL 2017

Dear Parents,

We would like to invite you and your children to join us this fall for a year of studying Russian on the University of Illinois campus.

The classes offered are based on the national standards and the most recent foreign language instruction methodologies and include:

  • Russian for Heritage speakers (ages 4-5; 6-7; 8-10*) for children who already speak Russian
  • Beginner Russian class for children (children will be divided into appropriate age groups)
  • Beginner Russian class for adults

*There is no age limit. New language classes will be formed if necessary

In addition, there is a children’s choir class, an art class, a math class, and an educational class about fun facts around the world, all taught in Russian.

All language courses are taught in an immersion environment based on Concordia Language Villages methodologies. They are project-based and fun.

The school will be operating once a week on Saturdays from 9am to 4 pm following the University calendar.

LOCATION:

Foreign Language Building, 1st floor

707 S Mathews Ave,

Urbana, IL 61801

Campus map

(type "Foreign Language Building" under "BUILDINGS")

Campus parking map

(Click on the pdf version in the top right corner.)

On this map parking lots D2 and E3 are close to the Foreign Language Building and free on Saturdays. Please do not park at rental spots that have blue signs in front of them, saying that the spot is reserved for 24 hours.

We encourage everyone, even beginners, to take all classes, as art, math, physics, and the computer world have languages of their own, and therefore are very accessible even if taught in a foreign language. All classes are hands on. However, if  you feel it is too stressful for your child to spend three hours in a foreign language environment, you can choose to attend as many classes to attend as you would like.

History of the School:

The school was registered as a Student-Community Organization in January of 2011, and during its first semester (January through June, 2011) had the total of 20 students, all of whom were heritage speakers.  We are hoping to expand our curriculum to non-Russian speakers who would like to study Russian, especially to the families who adopted their children from Russian-speaking countries of the former Soviet Union. If you know such a family in our region, please let them know about this opportunity.  

If  you have further questions, please contact me at (217)550-2355

or at admitrie@illinois.edu

Sincerely,

Anna Dmitrieva

Director of the Russian Heritage School for Children

value.Name: Sanctuary of the People
value.Description:
We are students at the University of Illinois, Urbana-Champaign, who are committed to the safety and protection of undocumented and South Asian, Arab, and Muslim persons, as well as all other students, staff, and their families who may be targeted under the new administration.

To move from commitment to action on our campuses as well as our communities, our mission as a group is fourfold. RESEARCH: First, we will employ our wealth of knowledge and resources, as scholars and community members with diverse forms of expertise, to aid ourselves and each other in understanding existing practices across multiple agencies –federal, state, and local authorities as well as campus policies– as well as to inform the shape of practices to come, under rapidly-changing conditions. RESOURCES: Second, as part of our mission as educators, we will collect and disseminate the necessary resources to do this work to our campuses and communities, including workshops and trainings in knowing our rights. ACTIONS: Third, we will take action to ensure to the best of our abilities that our students and staff who might be targeted are safe and protected from harm, including surveillance and deportation based on race, sexuality, religion, national origin, or documented status. BUILDING: Fourth, all the work we undertake is focused on building sustainable structures based on freedom and justice for our campuses and communities in order to provide a necessary education in intellectual curiosity about our world, as well as ethical responsibility to each of us in it.
value.Summary: We are students who are committed to the safety and protection of undocumented and South Asian, Arab, and Muslim persons, as well as all other students, staff, and their families who may be targeted under the new administration.

Diversity and versatility are two of Sigma Nu's strongest attributes. Our brothers come from all over Illinois and all over the world: from Vienna, Virginia to Dubai, United Arab Emirates .
