value.Description:
Sigma Psi Zeta Sorority, Inc. (SYZ) is a cultural, social, educational, and community service oriented sorority. SYZ is the first Greek-lettered sorority of its kind to be established on the East Coast and is one of the largest and most distinguished Asian-interest sororities in the nation.

The fundamental goal of Sigma Psi Zeta Sorority is to promote awareness of the myriad Asian/Asian-American cultures. Our sorority addresses this issue through leadership, outreach, individual, community interaction, and most importantly, the bonds of sisterhood. The sorority also promotes development among its members, the students and the faculty at each of the campuses we represent. In order to achieve this goal, we partake in political, social, educational, and cultural activities. Each effort improves our environment, and instills within our sisters experiences that will follow them long after they’ve graduated. Through a network of like-minded yet highly individualistic women, the sorority lends structure and support to sorors that share this Sigma vision. We believe the strength of our foundation derives from the unity of sisterhood, one that was proudly established years ago. In addition, we work in collaboration with other Greek and non-Greek organizations to provide services for the local communities and the community at large. It is through our various participations in these cultural events, educational workshops, and philanthropic support that we make a difference. Nationally, regionally, and individually, we strive to embody the ideals of Sigma Psi Zeta.

As a Student Organization on campus that raises Asian/Asian-American awareness, we are also an affiliate of the Asian Pacific American Coalition (APAC): http://www.uiucapac.org/

Follow us on Facebook: https://www.facebook.com/uiuc.sigmas?fref=ts

Check out our website: http://www.uiucsigmapsizeta.org/

National Sigma Psi Zeta Sorority Inc. website: http://sigmapsizeta.org/
value.Summary: The Alpha Epsilon Charter was officially established in the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign on April 7, 2012.

value.Name: Sikh Student Association
value.Description: To educate the UIUC campus about the Sikh religion and build solidarity amongst the campus Sikh community.
value.Summary: To educate the UIUC campus about the Sikh religion and build solidarity amongst the campus Sikh community.

value.Name: Singapore Students Association
value.Description: Establish and maintain a familiar and accessible community for Singaporeans to connect and live in. Celebrate our Singaporean culture through engagement with other communities around UIUC.
value.Summary: A home away from home.

value.Name: Slavic Graduate Students' Association
value.Description: SGSA acts is an academic, professional, and personal resource for graduate students of Slavic languages and literatures.
value.Summary: SGSA acts is an academic, professional, and personal resource for graduate students of Slavic languages and literatures.

value.Name: Smiles 4 Miles
value.Description: We provide children who are staying in hospitals a home away from home. Through this the children are given blankets, scarves, and pillow cases and more to give them a sense of comfort, security and happiness. The organization travels to both local and small hospitals and to larger children's hospitals to give out the donation to the kids. During this time, the group would also put on an activity for the kids such as life sized games of monopoly, bingo and more. Our goal is to help them when they are not able to help themselves; to give the children a light in a time of darkness.
value.Summary: Smiles 4 Miles provides the youth of the world the childhood that circumstances ultimately took away from them.

value.Name: Social Gaming Club
value.Description: This organization focuses on meeting and interacting with new people while playing various board games, card games and video games.  We strive to create a friendly, social environment, so players of all skill levels are welcome. If we don't have a particular game, players are encouraged to bring their own. Additionally, we have semesterly votes on buying new games. Meetings usually occur 1-7pm on Saturdays in 1090+1092 Lincoln Hall for Fall 2017. Check our Facebook page for updates!
value.Summary: An organization that focuses on meeting and interacting with new people while playing various board games and video games.  We strive to create a friendly, social environment, so players of all skill levels are welcome!

value.Name: Socialist Students
value.Description: Socialist Students is an organization launched by student members of Socialist Alternative. It is an organization of young people and students who are tired of the rule of the billionaire class and are fighting to build a new society, a socialist society. Young people today face crippling student debt, a wasteland of a job market, and an increasingly poor standard of living. We see these crises as being a direct effect of global capitalism; a system based on profit rather than need. We will fight for a society that meets the needs of all people rather than just a handful of billionaires, and we will start in our schools and communities!
value.Summary: Socialist Students is an organization of young people building a fightback against the billionaire class.

value.Name: Society for Business and Management in Architecture
value.Description: To inform and educate architecture students about "non-traditional" design opportunities available to them in related fields such as firm management, real estate, construction management, development and law.
value.Summary: To inform and educate architecture students about "non-traditional" design opportunities available to them in related fields such as firm management, real estate, construction management, development and law.

value.Name: Society for Engineering Mechanics
value.Description: The Society for Engineering Mechanics (SEM) is an organization that promotes Engineering Mechanics as a major. We bring students together to design and build mechanical projects and the members decide which projects we pursue based on their own interests. Social events allow members to take a break from their studies while getting to know one another. Students also have the opportunity to meet professors in an informal setting at our general meetings and professional events.
value.Summary: The Society for Engineering Mechanics provides a community that helps students succeed in Engineering Mechanics. Members collaborate on projects to gain design experience and attend events to form and develop social, departmental, and professional ties.

value.Name: Society for Industrial and Applied Mathematics
value.Description: SIAM aims to advance the application of mathematics and computational science to engineering, industry, science, and society. Locally, the chapter seeks to build a community of members interested in the intersection of mathematics, computing, engineering, and science.
value.Summary: SIAM aims to advance the application of mathematics and computational science to engineering, industry, science, and society.

value.Name: Society for the Advancement of Chicanos and Native Americans in Science - UIUC Chapter
value.Description:
Mission

SACNAS is a society of scientists dedicated to fostering the succes of Hispanic/Chicano and Native American scientists-from college students to professionals-to attain advanced degrees, careers, and positions of leadership in science

Goals

-To increase the number of Hispanics/Chicanos and Native Americans with advanced degrees in science and the motivation to be leaders

-To increase the number of Hispanics/Chicanos and Native Americans in science research, leadership, and teaching careers at all levels.

-To increase governmental commitment to advancing Hispanics/Chicanos and native Americans in science resulting in increased resources, elimination of barriers and, greater equity.
value.Summary: This group is committed to supporting Latinos and Native American scientists attain their highest goals, academically and professionally.  We welcome ALL members committed to this goal.

value.Name: Society for the Promotion of Indian Classical Music and Culture Amongst Youth
value.Description: Our organisation is dedicated to bringing world class Indian Classical Music/Performing arts to the campus community. Indian Classical Music, both North Indian and South Indian, Vocal and Instrumental and Classical Arts and artists are invited to perform for the benefit of the students and community members of UIUC and Urbana-Champaign.
value.Summary: Our organisation is dedicated to bringing world class Indian Classical Music/Performing arts to the campus community. Indian Classical Music, both North Indian and South Indian, Vocal and Instrumental and Classical Arts and artists are invited to

value.Name: Society for Theriogenology, Illinois Student Chapter
value.Description:
Mission Statement: The Society for Theriogenology is an organization of veterinarian students dedicated to animal reproduction, whose mission is to promote standards of excellence in reproductive medicine, to provide outreach and education to veterinarians, and to foster continual improvements in theriogenology. 

The organization is offered to veterinary medicine students and veterinarians that are interested in lectures, wet labs, and other experiences of reproduction in all species of animals including large, small, production, and exotic animals.
value.Summary: The organization is the Illinois Student chapter for veterinary medicine students interested in lectures, wet labs, and other experiences of reproduction in large, small, production, and exotic animals.

value.Name: Society for Women in Physics
value.Description: Our goal is to promote networking and support for women in physics. All majors and genders are welcome!
value.Summary: Our goal is to promote networking and support for women in physics. All majors and genders are welcome!

value.Name: Society of American Archivists
value.Description: Graduate student-level student chapter of the Society of American Archivists. Our goals are to serve as a means of introducing new archivists into the profession, enhance the educational function by providing an additional focus for the students to discuss archival issues, identify with the profession, and engage in professional activities, promote communication among student members, develop the leaders of tomorrow's archival profession, and attract new members into the Society.
value.Summary: Graduate student-level student chapter of the Society of American Archivists.

value.Name: Society of Asian Scientists and Engineers
value.Description: The Society of Asian Scientists and Engineers is an all-inclusive organization that strives to better prepare our members for their futures by developing their soft skill sets as well as establishing connections between the industry and the industry's future leaders. Not only do we seek to create these professional networks, but also to provide a friendly and helpful community for our members. We plan on expanding our goals in future semesters in order to cater to the needs of our diverse student body on campus.
value.Summary: We help Asian scientists and engineers enhance their career development skills and obtain a career in the industry.

value.Name: Society of Collegiate Leadership and Achievement
value.Description: Our goal is to maximize each student’s potential by providing meaningful connections to a vibrant peer and mentor community as well as a proprietary platform for developing necessary personal and academic skills. We aim to inspire members to take control of their own futures, move toward independence, and ultimately, establish a foundation and foothold for successful careers and lives. The Society for Collegiate Leadership & Achievement invites a selected group of students, so therefore bestow an honor to those that accept. We believe every motivated student has the potential to be a leader in his or her profession. Knowledge is everywhere. Our crucial difference in leadership development is to offer students the right information at the right time to develop strength in our four key quadrants to develop students for professional excellence: academic and career support, leadership development, health and wellness awareness, and financial literacy. To accelerate learning and achievement, SCLA provides students information, advice, and mentoring at the time when it benefits them most.
value.Summary: The purpose of the Society is to honor undergraduate students’ achievement and empower them by providing powerful tools for academic and professional success.

value.Name: Society of Fire Protection Engineers
value.Description:
Want to learn more about how to use your engineering skill to help save lives and property? Fire protection engineering (FPE) is a growing field that applies engineering principles to reduce the risks of unwanted fires in the communities where we live and work. FPEs are highly sought in the Chicagoland area, around the country, and around the world. The Society of Fire Protection Engineers is a worldwide professional society whose purpose is to advance the science and practice of fire protection engineering (FPE) and its allied fields; to maintain a high ethical standard among its members; and to foster fire protection engineering education.

     A group of engineering students at Illinois is planning to start the twelfth SFPE student chapter. The purpose of this student chapter will be to promote the science of fire protection engineering. This will be accomplished by holding regularly scheduled meetings that will include guest speakers, laboratory workshops, EOH exhibits, and social functions, all of which will pertain to the art of FPE. Any student who wants to learn more about FPE to finds it be an interesting application of engineering is strongly encouraged to join. For more information, please contact Kathryn Donlin at donlin2@illinois.edu
value.Summary: The purpose of this organization is to promote the science of fire protection engineering (FPE) through guest speakers, laboratory workshops, EOH exhibits, and social functions, all of which pertain to FPE.

value.Name: Society of Hispanic Professional Engineers
value.Description: To promote the development of students in engineering, science, and math to acheive educational excellence, economic opportunity, and social equity. SHPE changes lives by empowering the Hispanic community to realize their fullest potential and impacts the world through STEM awareness, access, support and development.
value.Summary: SHPE changes lives by empowering the Hispanic community to realize their fullest potential and impacts the world through STEM awareness, access, support and development.

value.Name: Society of Professional Journalists
value.Description: Provide student journalists with a strong professional organization that will bring networking, internship and future job opportunities. This is a place for students to socialize and connect with the campus' journalism community. SPJ supplements classroom work and gives students an extracurricular opportunity to practice journalism skills.
value.Summary: Provide student journalists with a strong professional organization that will bring networking, internship and future job opportunities. This is a place for students to socialize and connect with the campus' journalism community.

value.Name: Society of Women Engineers
value.Description: The Society of Women Engineers (SWE) is the world's largest advocate and catalyst for change for women in engineering and technology. To ensure SWE members reach their full potential as engineers and leaders, the Society offers unique opportunities to network, provides professional development and shapes public policy. SWE champions the value of diversity. We inspire young girls to become engineers and support them with scholarships in order to expand the engineering profession's ability to improve the quality of life for billions of people worldwide.
value.Summary: Empowering women to achieve their full potentials in careers as engineers and leaders, expanding the image of the engineering profession as a positive force in improving quality of life, and demonstrating the value of diversity.

value.Name: Society of Women in Business
value.Description:
Our mission is to provide a positive networking and social environment for aspiring business professionals. We hope to do this by offering four types of events.

  • Professional Events
  • Mentoring Events
  • Social Events
  • Service Events

Additionally, we hope that our members can become more involved and dedicated to SWB by offering a variety of chair and committee positions. We require that members achieve active member status each semester by attending nine events and we also offer Elite member status to those that go above and beyond by attending eleven events.
value.Summary: To unite women and give them the essential skills and experiences to succeed in business.

value.Name: South Asian Law Students Association
value.Description:
Mission Statement

 

The South Asian Law Students Association (SALSA) of the University of Illinois College of Law is an organization that aims to bring together law students interested in South Asia, provide a forum to discuss South Asian issues and affairs, and foster both academic and professional success among its members.

 

 

Proposed Activities / Benefits

 

-          Host question and answer forums for UIUC pre-law students (promoted by the undergraduate Indian Students Association)

-          Connect South Asian law students with diversity fellowships, diversity public interest grants, and other opportunities

-          Host visiting speakers of South Asian descent

-          Social events (Indian food/movie night, etc.)

-   Hold fundraising event (to raise money for grants and future events)
value.Summary:
Mission Statement
 
The South Asian Law Students Association (SALSA) of the University of Illinois College of Law is an organization that aims to bring together law students interested in South Asia, provide a forum to discuss South Asian

value.Name: Special Interest Group for Computer Graphics
value.Description: A community for the development of computer animation & visual effects, video games, graphics research, multimedia, and software relating to graphics. We are an official student chapter of the international ACM SIGGRAPH organization.
value.Summary: A community for the development of computer animation & visual effects, video games, graphics research, multimedia, and software relating to graphics. We are an official student chapter of the international ACM SIGGRAPH organization.

value.Name: Speech and Debate Team at the University of Illinois
value.Description: We are a self run organization. We are a competitive speaking team who's activities range from Debate, Public Address, Limited Preparation and Interpretive Acting. We travel to several local universities in the area on almost a weekly basis.
value.Summary: We are a self run organization. We are a competitive speaking team who's activities range from Debate to Public Address, Limited Preparation and Interpretive Acting. We travel to several local universities in the area on almost a weekly basis.

value.Name: Spicy Clamato Improv
value.Description: We are the longest-running improv comedy troupe at the University of Illinois (25 years this fall, 2017!). We do short-form improv games, and have a free show every other Friday, at 8pm, in the Courtyard Cafe in the Illini Union. Contact us at malignanthumor.uiuc@gmail.com.
value.Summary: We are the longest-running improv comedy troupe at the University of Illinois (25 years this fall!). We do short-form improv games, and have a free show every other Friday, at 8pm, in the Illini Union's Courtyard Cafe.

value.Name: Spoon University
value.Description: Spoon University is the only online food publication for college students, by college students, dedicated to making food more than just sustenance. We cover everything from hot local restaurants and dining hall hacks to two-ingredient treats and tips on avoiding hangovers. The Spoon site is powered by student contributors across the country, who now make up a network of over 600 students at 35 campuses nationwide. Our goal is to help encourage exploration and conversation about food to help students navigate what the hell is going on in their dorms, dining halls and tiny apartment kitchens.We carefully recruit the brightest, most enthusiastic students to become national contributors or establish campus chapters and build their own editorial and marketing teams. The editorial staff at each college publishes local restaurant reviews, food news articles, recipes and kitchen tips on their pages so students can have personalized experiences on the Spoon site. Offline, marketing teams rally students on campus through events, fundraisers and collaboration with other student groups.
value.Summary: Spoon University is a national, online food publication that aims to promote local restaurants and a universal love for food through recipes, reviews, kitchen tips and much more!

value.Name: Sport, Tourism, and Recreation Association
value.Description: STAR, Sport, Tourism and Recreation, is a Registered Student Organization (RSO) within the College of Applied Health Sciences in the Department of Recreation, Sport and Tourism. STAR is a professional development club that serves as a liaison between the RST department and students and faculty. We aim to provide professional development and networking opportunities, volunteering, and community building for both RST majors and non-majors and faculty through events we host. STAR is not exclusively for RST students but also is a resource for other students that have an interest in the RST field. STAR is a great opportunity to network with peers, faculty and professionals in the field. STAR focuses on the personal and professional growth of the students in our organization. We provide countless opportunities to help students develop skills and gain knowledge about the field.
value.Summary: The purpose of STAR is to provide the opportunity to expand professional and social networks, to act as a liaison between the student body and the RST Department, and to offer professional development opportunities for U of I students.

value.Name: Sports & Entertainment Law Society
value.Description: To educate students about the many legal issues that affect the world of sports and entertainment, as well as to provide opportunities within the sports and entertainment industries.
value.Summary: To educate students about the many legal issues that affect the world of sports and entertainment, as well as to provide opportunities within the sports and entertainment industries.

value.Name: Sports Analytics Society
value.Description: SAS gives students the opportunity to participate in and lead analytics projects in the sporting environment. With an emphasis on baseball, basketball, and football, groups will analyze and present data pertaining to Strategy, Management, Stat-Line, or Marketing within each sport. Developmental meetings that focus on data analysis tools ranging from Excel to R give members the skills they need to perform analysis at a high level. Introducting students to an up-and-coming field, the Sports Analytics Society is perfect for sports fanatics and number-crunchers alike.
value.Summary: SAS gives students the opportunity to work on real, relevant projects in the rapidly growing field of sports analytics.

value.Name: Sports Business Association
value.Description:
The Sport Business Association strives to offer students at the University of Illinois quality opportunities to experience, investigate and explore the multi-billion dollar industry of sports.  The U of I SBA aims to foster professional development of its members through three basic types of programming:

1.) Guest Speakers.  
2.) Professional Conferences.
3.) Workshops and Volunteer Opportunites.
value.Summary: The Sports Business Association at the University of Illinois is an undergraduate student organization providing members educational and networking opportunities within the wide world of sports.

value.Name: Squash Club of Illinois
value.Description: This club is a must join for all squash players and students willing to learn/play squash. Members of the club will get a chance to play competitive squash and tournaments will be held every 2 months. Once each semester we may also participate at the external level, like moving out of campus and playing with the other players of different cities.
value.Summary: A club for everyone interested in squash. Players will get a chance to play competitive squash and new aspirants will have a chance to learn the sport.

value.Name: Squirrel Scurry
value.Summary: Our goal is to facilitate the responsible cohabitation and intermingling between students and squirrels, including handling, feeding, and respectful observation. We do this through presentations, field work, and group outings.

value.Name: Starts with Soap
value.Description: We are the University of Illinois chapter of Starts with Soap (SWS). SWS started when its founder went on a trip to help schools in Detroit. He noticed that many of the schools didn't have even the barest necessities, such as soap. Thus, Starts with Soap was created. This chapter partners with local schools in Urbana and Champaign to provide them with whatever they may need, whether it may be soap, laptops, or services.
value.Summary: We partner with local schools to provide whatever they may need. We work directly with the local Champaign-Urbana community to effect change in these schools. We provide them with anything, ranging from soap to laptops to services.

value.Name: Statistics in the Community at UIUC
value.Description: We are a pro-bono statistical consulting organization associated with the Statistics department at the University of Illinois, Urbana-Champaign. We reach out to educational institutions, non-profits, and local small businesses in order to encourage collaboration between the University and the community. Our main objective is to provide free-of-charge solutions with assistance on a wide variety of statistical issues. We hope our service creates cross-disciplinary relationships and an enriching learning environment by providing Stat-Com members hands-on experience with data analysis and providing analytical benefits to our clients.
value.Summary: We are a pro-bono statistical consulting organization associated with the Statistics department connecting the University with the community.

value.Name: STEM-Fem Alliance
value.Description: The STEM-Fem Alliance seeks to empower underrepresented women majoring in the following disciplines for graduate studies: science, technology, engineering, and mathematics. It seeks to raise awareness of gender issues occurring within the STEM community and those that the STEM community affects, to foster collaboration among disciplines by encouraging interdisciplinary work, and to improve the visibility of women in the sciences. It also hopes to facilitate the transition from graduate school to academia, industry, government agencies, and other professions. The STEM-Fem Alliance will accomplish this mission through various initiatives, including: talks, professional development, mentorship from early-career professionals, networking sessions, and social events. While the STEM-Fem Alliance focuses on empowering underrepresented women in STEM fields, it also intends to act as a sister support group to other specialized RSOs, including Graduate Engineers Diversifying Illinois (GEDI), Women in Science (WIS), and The Society for Advancement of Hispanics/Chicanos and Native Americans in Science (SACNAS).
value.Summary: The STEM-Fem Alliance seeks to empower underrepresented women majoring in the following disciplines for graduate studies: science, technology, engineering, and mathematics. It seeks to raise awareness of gender issues occurring within the STEM community.

value.Name: Stochastic Club
value.Summary: To provide students with the opportunity to meet new people and appreciate the stochasticity (randomness) of life! Open to all who appreciate good fun and a good laugh!

value.Name: Stone Creek Church Midtown
value.Summary: We are a church that is located on the campus of the University of Illinois.  Our desire is to positively affect Champaign-Urbana, the University of Illinois, and the nations of the world.

value.Name: Stratford Christian Cooperative House
value.Description:
Stratford house is made up of 38 Christian women living cooperatively to encourage one another in our daily faith. Since we are a “cooperative” house, this means the house is fully run by us – cooking, cleaning, social events, and weekly meetings. This is all made possible by a nominated group of girls who serve as the “executive board” for each semester. These girls help to organize, encourage, and just make sure everything is running efficiently and effectively.

 

To make sure our house is running efficiently and effectively, our House Manager (a student) organizes a semester lunch/dinner cooking and clean up schedule. In addition to cooking and cleaning, we are responsible for Monday and Thursday duties. Between cooking, cleanups, and duties, each girl is required to complete 3 hours a week of service toward the house. Although this may seem like a lot, if you are ever busy, there are always extensions and grace given.

 

Every Monday evening we have a house meeting, to go over “business” issues, hear from our executive board, have a chaplain’s challenge, give announcements, and share prayer requests.

 

Each year we have different social activities with our brother house Koinonia Christian Cooperative House. Such activities include: a summer picnic, fall and spring overnight retreat, brother/sister games, weekly praise and worship, initiate event, a Halloween dance, Semi-Formal, a Valentines dance, and Spring Formal. You will come to find Stratford House and Koinonia are close friends and brothers and sisters in Christ.

 

We are all thankful to live at Stratford House. We love coming back from classes to a “home environment” where we know we are cared and loved for. Also, it is such a blessing to live in such close Christian fellowship with both men and women on a large secular university campus.
value.Summary: Stratford house is made up of 38 Christian women living cooperatively to encourage one another in our daily faith. Since we are a “cooperative” house, this means the house is fully run by us; cooking, cleaning, and social events.

value.Name: Stress Management Peers
value.Description: Stress Management Peers is a Registered Student Organization at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign. We are a peer group through McKinley Health Center, Health Education Unit. Peers are trained to facilitate workshops throughout campus that help students manage their stress. We also educate the campus about stress-related concerns through various programs and campus-wide events.
value.Summary: The purpose of this organization is to provide stress management resources to the campus and community.

value.Name: Structural Engineering Graduate Student Organization
value.Description: The Structural Engineering Graduate Student Organization was formed in order to enhance the experience of graduate school for students. We focus on holding professional, academic, and social events. The professional events we plan to hold, such as informal networking events, company tours, and industry panels, are intended to provide professional complement to the academic curriculum. The academic events we plan to hold include academic skills development seminars. These will allow graduate students to broaden their existing academic knowledge and help them develop as researchers and scholars in their field. The social events we hold include student mixers, cookouts, and potlucks, all of which are geared towards building a sense of community amongst students while creating a network of peers that can provide assistance throughout the academic year.
value.Summary: SEGSO is an organization created by graduate students to improve the graduate school experience. Our purpose is to organize and plan professional, academic and social events for the betterment of Structural Engineering graduate students at UIUC.

value.Name: Structural Engineers Association
value.Description: To advance and advocate excellence in structural engineering and to aid in safeguarding the public.
value.Summary: To advance and advocate excellence in structural engineering and to aid in safeguarding the public.

value.Name: Student Academy of Audiology
value.Description: The Student Academy of Audiology (SAA) is the national student organization of the American Academy of Audiology that serves as a collective voice for students and advances the rights, interests, and welfare of students pursuing careers in audiology. The SAA introduces students to lifelong involvement in activities that promote and advance the profession of audiology, and provides services, information, education, representation and advocacy for the profession and the public we serve.
value.Summary: SAA serves as an assembled voice for students and professionals in order to inform and educate those pursuing careers in audiology and communication related fields.  The goal is to prepare students for a lifelong committment to audiology.

value.Name: Student Advocacy Coalition
value.Summary: A student organization dedicated to advocating for higher education

value.Name: Student Aircraft Builders
value.Summary: A team dedicated to  building kit planes from the ground up into research aircraft. In the process, participating students will transform into valuable industry employees through hands on work experience and large-scale project interactions.

value.Name: Student Alumni Ambassadors
value.Description: To promote Illini pride and spirit through inclusive programming for students and community members alike while representing the University alumni, staff, faculty, guests, students, and potential students.
value.Summary: To promote Illini pride and spirit through inclusive programming for students and community members alike while representing the University alumni, staff, faculty, guests, students, and potential students.

value.Name: Student Athlete Advisory Committee
value.Description: Each University of Illinois athletic team is represented on the committee by two team members. Through SAAC, student-athletes have a voice to communicate needs and concerns to the athletic administration. SAAC members also take the lead in organizing various community service projects, such as their annual clothing drive and the Angel Tree Project.
value.Summary: Each athletic team is represented on the committee by team members. Through SAAC, student-athletes have a voice to communicate needs and concerns to the athletic administration. SAAC members also take the lead in organizing various community service

value.Name: Student Bar Association
value.Description: Represent the interests and concerns of all law students at the College of Law.
value.Summary: Represent the interests and concerns of all law students at the College of Law.

value.Name: Student Body for Meaningful Education
value.Description:
We're an RSO dedicated to holding discussions and planning projects to explore a few core questions:

  1. Why are we taught the way we are? What works, what doesn't, and what does that mean for the students?
  2. What are people doing to make what they learn more meaningful? How are our peers pursuing their passions, and how do those passions tie into our courses?
  3. How can we help our peers make their educational experience feel more relevant in their lives?
value.Summary: SBME provides a place to discuss what goes into our educations on this campus, explore how people have been making meaning of the things they've learned and done, and plan how we can help engage our peers and faculty in this exploration.

value.Name: Student Chapter of the American Meteorological Society at UIUC
value.Description: This organization acts to serve as a forum for students interested in the atmospheric sciences to voice their opinions/concerns, to serve as a conduit between students and the Department of Atmospheric Sciences faculty and staff, to serve as a conduit between the students  and the surrounding community, to promote and support social, professional, and academic activities related to the atmospheric sciences, and to promote the welfare of all members within the organization.
value.Summary: This organization acts to serve as a forum for students interested in the atmospheric sciences to voice their opinions/concerns, to serve as a conduit between students and the Department of Atmospheric Sciences faculty and staff.

value.Name: Student Chapter of the Humane Society Veterinary Medical Association at UIUC
value.ShortName: Student Chapter of the HSVMA ar UIUC
value.Description: Humane Society Veterinary Medical Association student chapters provide a forum for veterinary students to get involved in animal protection issues, promote humane veterinary education, and participate in service opportunities.
value.Summary: Humane Society Veterinary Medical Association student chapter provides a forum for veterinary students to get involved in animal protection issues, promote humane veterinary education, and participate in service opportunities.

value.Name: Student Dietetic Association
value.Description: The Student Dietetic Association is the advocate of the dietetic option in Food Science and Human Nutrition at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign, serving the students and local community through promotion of optimal nutrition, health and well being.
value.Summary: The Student Dietetic Association is the advocate of the dietetic option in Food Science and Human Nutrition at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign, serving the students and community through promotion of optimal nutrition, health and well being.

value.Name: Student Education Association
value.Description:
With over 3.3 million students, teachers, administrators and other school staff,
Student Education Association is the largest and most widely known, pre-professional education association in the nation. As an IEA-student program, we provide students with professional opportunities to learn about issues teachers face while providing them with the skills and experiences necessary to become the best teachers. We also focus on community outreach and political action; serving as an organization for well-rounded, top-notch, future leading educators.

For more information and questions, please contact uillinoisucsea@gmail.com, visit uiucsea.weebly.com, or check us out on Facebook at Student Education Association
value.Summary: We focus on teacher quality, political action, and community outreach.  We are the student program of the Illinois Education Association and the National Education Association, the largest teacher's union in the nation!

value.Name: Student Legal Relief
value.Description: The mission of this group is to send students on volunteer legal aid trips and raise awareness of the social and legal issues impacting impoverished or marginalized persons and communities.
value.Summary: The mission of this group is to send students on volunteer legal aid trips and raise awareness of the social and legal issues impacting impoverished or marginalized persons and communities.

value.Summary: To assume responsibility for contributing to nursing education in order to provide for the highest quality of health care; To provide programs representative of fundamental interests and concerns to nursing students; To aid in the development

value.Name: Student Organization Resource Fee Board
value.Description: The SORF Board is comprised of 11 voting members: 3 appointed staff and 8 elected student members, two of which must be graduate/professional status. The Board is responsible for allocating money generated from the Student Organization Resource Fee to Registered Student Organizations for a variety of purposes. Any registered RSO is eligible to apply for SORF funding. Application deadlines, funding guidelines, and reimbursement forms can be found at the SORF website.
value.Summary: The SORF Board is comprised of 11 members, including 8 elected students. The SORF Board is responsible for allocating money generated from the Student Organization Resource Fee.

value.Name: Student Planning Organization
value.Description: We are the student organization for urban planners at Illinois and our mission is to provide a vehicle for communication between staff, faculty and students in Urban Planning, provide forums for discussions and workshops, and organize social events.
value.Summary: We are an organization of Urban Planning students at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign. We promote sustainable urban design, innovative social and economic programs, and hope to improve the lifestyles of everyday Americans.

value.Name: Student Soccer Foundation
value.Description:
The Student Soccer Foundation was founded in 2017 out of the University of Illinois.  The organization was established as a means for students who love the beautiful game to come together.  Our mission is to stimulate the cultural initiative that is soccer at the University through the following four initiatives:

BROTHERHOOD

Our organization holds fellowship amongst its members and the University to the utmost importance.  We host several social events - such as Chicago soccer games, tournaments, and happy hours - with the aim to increase the brotherhood within our foundation.

SCHOLARSHIP

Throughout the year, we provide scholarships to local high school athletes who plan on attending the University of Illinois.  Our decisions are based on the students' academic, athletic, and philanthropic aptitude.

UNIFICATION

Our mission is to unite all those who love the beautiful game at the University and the neighboring areas.  SSF reaches out to and accepts all men and women interested in our endeavors.

EMERGENCE

Our Foundation aims to emerge as the leading student-run athletic association at the University of Illinois.  Through our work, SSF stimulates the rising popularity of soccer in the US and the cultural incentives soccer can provide.

CHECK OUT OUR WEBSITE HERE
value.Summary: The Student Soccer Foundation aims to vitalize and unite the soccer community at the University of Illinois. Our mission is to stimulate the cultural initiative that is soccer at the University through scholarship, fellowship, and brotherhood.

value.Name: Student Society for Human Resource Management
value.ShortName: Student Society for Human Resource Management
value.Description: To broaden the understanding of the human resources field.
value.Summary: To broaden the understanding of the human resources field.

value.Name: Student Space Systems
value.Description:
SSS is a technical organization with the final goal of sending a student scratch built rocket to space. Along the way we aim to send rockets to higher and higher altitudes while making strides developmentally in areas such as propulsion, structures, and avionics. In addition, SSS will aspire to emulate the policies and organization of corporate space companies in order to provide members with exposure to this type of unique work enviroment. 

In addition to our primary goal of eventually achieving spaceflight, we are dedicated to educating students about high power rocketry. We will have a Level One High Power Rocketry Certification program where we will assist students who are interest in building their own kits to achieve a basic understanding of high power rocketry and earn a Level One Certification.
value.Summary: A technical organization with the goal of designing, manufacturing, and launching rockets to suborbital space.

value.Name: Students Against Sexual Assault
value.Description:
SASA is responsible for facilitating meetings and programs in order to spread awareness about sexual assault, support survivors of sexual assault, and work towards making policy changes on the UIUC campus. 

Our vision is to eliminate sexual assault on the UIUC campus as well as allow survivors to feel safe sharing their stories. We also want to be the driving force behind having sexual assault cases handled better by the administration here at UIUC.

We hope to achieve our mission by becoming a well-known outlet and source of assistance for survivors of sexual assault. Furthermore, the organization hopes to impact the university community through advocating for various policy changes to benefit those affected by sexual assault.
value.Summary: SASA is an organization that is responsible for facilitating meetings and programs in order to spread awareness about sexual assault, support survivors of sexual assault, and work towards making policy changes on the UIUC campus.

value.Name: Students and Youth for a New America
value.Description:
Students and Youth for a New America is an organization that is political and social in nature. We seek to organize students who are worried about the trajectory our nation is headed towards, and want to use SYNA as a body to discuss the various economic and social issues our nation faces to a greater extent every day (unemployment, poverty, institutionalized racism, militarized police, adventurous militarism abroad, etc). 

SYNA also seeks to engage with the Champaign-Urbana community on a close local level. We believe there is a considerable social gap existing between our campus and the cities, and feel it is our duty to create an open dialogue between these bodies. SYNA has an interest in working with local organizations to engage in grassroots activism within the community to help the least fortunate and forgotten of our society. This activism may take the form of food-drives, soup kitchens, really really free markets, books to prisoners, etc.

SYNA chapters are simultaneously being founded on the East Coast, Great Lakes Region, and California. The organization's primary leadership is mostly based in the New York and DC areas.
value.Summary: SYNA is an affiliated student organization dedicated to making meaningful positive connections with the local community, as well as addressing and discussing our nation's grave economic and social problems.

value.Name: Students Consulting for Nonprofit Organizations
value.Description:
SCNO is a mission driven, student-led consulting organization at UIUC.  Each semester, we deploy up to 10 project teams of 5 to 7 students in pro-bono consulting engagements with nonprofit organizations in our community. Since being established in 2005, SCNO has served over 60 nonprofits in projects focused on process optimization, technology management, program evaluation and more.

Visit our website at illiniscno.org to find out more about our growing organization!
value.Summary: Students Consulting for Nonprofit Organization (SCNO) is a student-led consulting organization that provides strategic consulting services to nonprofit organization in Champaign Country and the Chicago metropolitan area.

value.Name: Students Empowering Education
value.Description: Students Empowering Education aims to empower high school students to take charge of their eduction and engage undergraduates in teaching. Initially, this will occur through a biannual conference held on the UIUC campus, dubbed "Splash! at UIUC" which will invite high school students from around the state to come to UIUC for one day each fall and spring. At Splash! they will take interesting yet approachable collegiate classes, ranging in subject from The Physicis of Ballet to Geometries of Space and Time, and they will meet other motivated students like themselves form around the state. Furthermore, undergraduates from a variety of disciplines will be teaching these classes, and will hopefully find the joy of teaching. Funding will occur via various sources, including funding from various colleges and fundraising campaigns.
value.Summary: Student Empowering Education is an organization with a vision to empower high school student to take charge of their education and engage undergraduates from all disciplines in teaching. We hold a biannual conference for HS students. Contact us for info.

value.Name: Students for a Free Tibet
value.Description: Students for a Free Tibet (SFT) works in solidarity with the Tibetan people in their struggle for freedom and independence. We are a chapter-based network of young people and activists around the world. Through education, grassroots organizing, and non-violent direct action, we campaign for Tibetans’ fundamental right to political freedom. Our role is to empower and train youth as leaders in the worldwide movement for social justice.
value.Summary: In our work for Tibetan independence we also aim to inspire and enable people, especially youth, to create a just and equitable world, free of oppression, in which there is respect for the earth and all living things.

value.Name: Students for Accessible Health Care
value.Summary: Through a partnership with Champaign County Christian Health Center, we strive to provide holistic, free, and quality primary and dental care to the uninsured residents of Champaign County through fundraising and volunteer activities.

value.Name: Students for Alternative Sexualities: Safety, Support, and Consent
value.Description: S.A.S.S.C. stands for "Students for Alternative Sexualities: Safety, Support, and Consent. We advocate for safe practices in kink, including the potential for vanilla instructional and informational seminars, demonstrations, and community events. We will hold support sessions and other meetings at the LGBT Resource Center. We also support Polyamorous persons and their partners, and anyone else whose sexuality does not necessarily fit the typical LGBQA spectrum. We have professional resources as well as bring personal experience and knowledge to share. Some sessions will focus solely on poly issues, while others will focus on kink issues.
value.Summary: This is a support and safety group for students involved in the kink, poly, or other similar scenes, be they veterans or novices. A chapter of the LGBTRC, we promote Safe, Sane, and Consensual involvement and support those in need of information.

value.Name: Students for an Arab Cultural Center at Illinois
value.Summary: We are students that support and advocate for the establishment of a cultural center that represents students with backgrounds in the Middle East/N. Africa

value.Name: Students for Bennett
value.Summary: A group of students interested in protecting our University, becoming more involved in State politics, and electing Scott Bennett to represent us in Springfield.

value.Name: Students for Environmental Concerns
value.Description: To educate and inform students and community members about environmental issues and to work towards positive environmental change on a national, statewide, and local level through service and activism.
value.Summary: To educate and inform students and community members about environmental issues and to work towards positive environmental change on a national, statewide, and local level through service and activism.

value.Name: Students for JB Pritzker
value.Description: The RSO, Students for JB Pritzker will serve several functions. First, Students for JB Pritzker will work to raise awareness for gubernatorial candidate JB Pritzker and his progressive campaign. Second, the RSO Students for JB Pritzker will serve as an engine to campaign on behalf of the Pritzker campaign in order to propel JB Pritzker to victory not only in and around UIUC but in all of Illinois.
value.Summary: The RSO, Students for JB Pritzker serves the function of working in conjunction with the gubernatorial campaign of progressive candidate JB Pritzker in and around the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign.

value.Name: Students for the Baroque Artists of Champaign Urbana
value.Description:
From http://www.baroqueartists.org/

"The Baroque Artists of Champaign Urbana specialize in vibrant, historically informed performance of music from the 17th and 18th centuries. BACH is the only professional organization in Illinois, outside Chicago, whose programming is dedicated to baroque music.

Founded in 1996, with the purpose of teaching, learning, and performing music of the baroque era, BACH has grown to become a community organization that thrives on local musicians, our resident chorus, and the love of music."

Students for BACH is an organization for U of I students working with the Baroque Artists of Champagin Urbana.
value.Summary: The Baroque Artists of Champaign Urbana specialize in vibrant, historically informed performance of music from the 17th and 18th centuries. Students for BACH is an organization for U of I students working with the Baroque Artists of Champagin Urbana.

value.Name: Students in Indoor Mapping Robotics Research
value.Description:
Students in Indoor Mapping Robotics Research is focused primarily on developing methods for producing high fidelity magnetic field maps of indoor environments that can be used for localization and mapping on robotic and pedestrian platforms. Magnetic field maps of this nature and purpose are currently being developed by a number of large technology companies and are currently an exciting topic of research at many universities all over the world. Using these maps, we hope to develop a method by which a platform can be located to sub-meter level resolution in an indoor environment. The benefit of such a method would be enormous, with applications in industries such as defense, energy, construction, emergency services, disaster relief, consumer products, manufacturing, and education, to name a few.

We are also focused on training new members and developing their research skills to prepare them for opportunities in graduate school or for undergraduate research opportunities. This includes topics such as setting up an experiment, properly taking data, writing a technical paper, and technical presentation skills.
value.Summary: The mission of SIMRR is to provide opportunities for students from a diverse set of backgrounds and disciplines to contribute to the development and publication of magnetic field datasets to push the envelope in indoor mapping and localization.

value.Name: Students Solving Foster Care
value.Description: This organization will focus on improving the foster care system by trying to solve the issue of aging out of the foster care system and the issue of the low percentage of students in foster care that further their education. We will focus on fundraising events to get money in order to provide foster care students with scholarships to fund their college career. Another goal of this organization is to create a community of people that are passionate about the foster care system, whether they were in the system, know someone that was in the foster care system, or just want to improve a system that needs to be fixed. Overall this organization will be a community of students with a passion for the foster care system that take their passion and put it into action by raising money to give foster care youth scholarships so they have the opportunity to earn a college degree.
value.Summary: This organization will work to raise money for scholarships to benefit students in foster care that want to further their education. We will create a community of students with a common goal of improving the foster care system by encouraging education.

value.Name: Students Today Leaders Forever
value.Description: STLF is an organization that involves students making a difference in their communities  by being leaders. Being a part of STLF means being a part of a National organization that engages thousands of middle school, high school, and college students. STLF is known for it's Pay it Forward Tours and for the leadership camps that are held in the summer. College Pay It Forward Tours are 9 days-long, with service projects in 6 cities.  Buses leave from one campus and travel to 5 different cities—a different city and service project each day.  The last city is the celebration city, or the Tour’s end destination.  For weeks with multiple Tours, the celebration city is the first time the buses unite.  It is amazing to see hundreds of young people in the same color shirt doing one massive, joint service project. College Students also have an opportunity to help lead high school leadership camps.STLF's Summer Leadership Camps are a great way to meet incredible people from across the Midwest, make lifelong friends and memories, gain experience and confidence in various areas of leadership, and to commit to making a difference in your own school and community.
value.Summary: We are an optimistic group of students who engage in servant leadership to create positive life experiences. With a mission to reveal leadership through service relationships, and action, STLF is engaging students in service and leadership

value.Name: Studio
value.Description: Learn more here!
value.Summary: Studio is a community of student creators.

value.Name: Studio Art Club
value.Summary: A club to create, share, and critique art for students of any major! No previous art experience required, just a casual art club.

value.Name: Style Council
value.Description: Style Council aims to create a community of students with a passion for fashion and provides a space for them to express their creativity. Through open discussions and workshops the organization will introduce members to the world of fashion and its different facets. With the help of the organization’s committees, we will plan events documented on social media (photoshoots, fashion shows), fundraisers and social gatherings. We intend to have weekly meetings to hold our workshops or discuss future plans for the organization. The club will convene as one at the beginning of our meetings and then branch off into our sub-committees towards the end. The sub-committees will include event-planning, fundraising, and social-media. The organization will provide the resources to broaden networks and open up new creative realms for its members.
value.Summary: Style council is an organization for students with an avid interest in fashion who will work together to create fashion related events and express their passion through different creative platforms.

value.Name: Subatomic Pigeon Improv
value.Description: Love watching improv and want to learn how to do it yourself? Or maybe you want to refine your skills and have fun performing with others? Then join us in this newly formed improv club, where we'll be practicing short form and experimental games! No experience or auditions required! Hope to see you there! :)
value.Summary: Love watching improv and want to learn how to do it yourself? Or maybe you want to refine your skills and have fun performing with others? Join us in this newly formed improv club for short form and experimental games! No experience or auditions required

value.Name: Swan Ballet
value.Description: This Club aims to offer free ballet and Chinese classic dance class to on-campus students. The instructor is well-known in China. Students are also offered opportunities of performance and dancing competitions. We welcome every dance lover.
value.Summary: Ballet & Chinese Classic Dance Group

value.Name: Sweet & Spicy
value.Description: The purpose of our organization is to increase cultural diversity and raise awareness through the exchange of international cuisines. Through the process of sharing we will be able to integrate and merge international differences and therefore induce cultural exchange .
value.Summary: The purpose of the organization is to increase cultural diversity and raise awareness through the exchange of international cuisines.

value.Summary: Promotion of an active interest in amateur radio communications, equipment, and operation of club station W9YH, and furtherance of public service.
