value.Description: To train in the physical and mental aspects of Tae Kwon Do.
value.Summary: To train in the physical and mental aspects of Tae Kwon Do.

value.Name: Taiwan Intercultural Association
value.Description: We provide a place to let Taiwanese students get involved with people of other cultures on campus. Not only do we help Taiwanese students adjust to this new environment, but also help them make new friends, and make more people aware of Taiwan. We host events, such as Paint balling, canoeing and skiing, monthly and invite different people to join us. Our objective is to let people make friends, while giving them a chance to know Taiwan.
value.Summary: We provide a place to let Taiwanese students get involved with people of other cultures on campus. Not only do we help Taiwanese students adjust to this new environment, but also help them make new friends, and make more people aware of Taiwan.

value.Name: Taiwanese American Students Club
value.Description:
The purpose of TASC shall be to build a family-like community at the University of Illinois that understands Taiwanese culture and appreciates Taiwanese American and Asian American identity through social and educational activities. TASC shall strive to achieve its purpose through the following:

  • Organizing campus events that promote knowledge of Taiwanese culture or Taiwanese American and Asian American awareness.
  • Strengthening and supporting the greater Taiwanese American student community, especially through active involvement in the Intercollegiate Taiwanese American Students Association (ITASA) and other Taiwanese organizations on campus.
  • Strengthening the campus Asian Pacific American (APA) community through active involvement in the Asian Pacific American Coalition (APAC) and supporting other campus organizations.
  • Building an involved, family-like community that empowers its members through growth and leadership on this campus on the above principles by promoting, preserving, educating, and celebrating Taiwanese American culture.
value.Summary: The purpose of TASC shall be to build a family-like community at the University of Illinois that understands Taiwanese culture and appreciates Taiwanese American and Asian American identity through social and educational activities.

value.Name: Taiwanese Students Association
value.Description: To provide a point of connection for Taiwanese students at the University of Illinois Urbana Champaign through support and accommodation in cultural events, information sessions, and other activities.
value.Summary: To provide a point of connection for Taiwanese students at the University of Illinois Urbana Champaign through support and accommodation in cultural events, information sessions, and other activities.

value.Name: Tandem Learning Club
value.Description:
Our goal is to promote learning languages in tandem: learning with each other, and learning from each other. International students and American students are matched up based on their language backgrounds. They then arrange to meet as often as they like, the American student helping the International student improve his/her conversational English, while the international student does the same for the American student in his/her native language, or the language spoken in the country which he/she is from. 
Tandem Learning Club will host monthly meetings for members to meet, mingle, and discuss what they've learned over the past few weeks.
value.Summary: T.L.C provides a forum where International and American students can meet and learn each others languages together. Students can learn from each other and make connections with others from around the world and become friends in the process.

value.Name: Tango And Flamenco
value.Description: Learn, Dance, and Enjoy the art of Argentine Tango as well as the art of flamenco! In the CU community, there are a lot of dance lessons, and two to three dance events every week. But, more importantly, we have one of the most diverse and vibrant group of people who passionately dance to the tango music, and share their passion with everyone.
value.Summary: Learn, Dance, and Enjoy the art of Argentine Tango and Flamenco!

value.Name: Task Force Team
value.Description: We are the people who peer-review the start-up buisness plan and share the ideas. The only purpose of being in the group is settling down the abstract idea to practical idea that can be utilized in the reality. The new start-up will not be help under the orgainzation, but we can foster and concrete the idea to start in outside of the organization.
value.Summary: The organization are helping people who like to start their own entrepreneur by peer-reviewing and brainstorming as a group. And we are trying to link other organization to foster the start-up.

value.Name: Tau Beta Pi Engineering Honor Society
value.ShortName: Tau Beta Pi Engineering Honor Society
value.Description: To recognize excellence in engineering
value.Summary: To recognize excellence in engineering

value.Name: Tau Sigma National Honor Society
value.Description: An academic honor society designed specifically to recognize and promote the academic excellence and involvement of transfer students.
value.Summary: An academic honor society designed specifically to recognize and promote the academic excellence and involvement of transfer students.

value.Name: Tax Advisors for the Champaign Society
value.Description:
Tax Advisors for the Champaign Society (TACS) was established by four accounting and finance major students (Jaeyeon Pyo, Jeewhan Shin, So Yoon Lee, and Yongsun Shim) in January 11, 2012. Our mission is to provide tax return volunteer services for the Champaign society. We now serve approximately 150 individuals per year. We are continuing to grow as a group every year as the demands are increasing.
TACS deals with both resident and nonresident individuals filing tax returns. One example of our clientele are international students (F or J Visa status) who receive stipends at the university. Every year, all our members get certified in basic and intermediate section certification for VITA (Volunteer Income Tax Assistance) by the IRS. Also, all our founding members successfully completed tax preparer training sessions at Center for Economic Progress Organization. Based on that, our executive board members hold seminars in the fall semesters to discuss issues related to taxes, accounting, and finance, and the volunteer services that we provide in the spring semesters. In the spring semesters, we provide one-on-one client service in assisting them with their individual tax returns (1040, 1040 NR, etc.).
TACS is a professional and friendly organization that is open to all the students on campus and all members in the Champaign area.
value.Summary: Tax Advisors for the Champaign Society (TACS) provides individual income tax return services as volunteers. We help both residents and nonresidents through consulting them with their returns. Our members are VITA (Volunteer Income Tax Assistance)-certifi

value.Name: Tea & Company
value.ShortName: The Society for Appreciation of Fantastic Tea and Great Conversation
value.Description: Ever since I started, I had had tea parties every sunday for the fun of it. Then more people came to join to appreciate the wonderful tea and make lively conversation. At th tea parties, many strangers who only knew me  as a connection began to make friends and contact each other. Thus emerges the two goals of the club; to talk of topics ranging from existentialism to black holes to Norwegian death metal while at the same time, enjoying the delicious, luxurious types of tea that other members and myself provide. The tea appreciation is quite real as meetings will dive into lectures of the differentiation of English Black Tea and Chinese Black Tea, the faults of a tea bag, and etc. So anyone can come if one wish to make a new friend and drink something delicious or one of the above.
value.Summary: The primary focuses  of the club are of course tea and socialization. It is a club for people to appreciate the finer teas in life while at the same time, meeting new people through the variety of conversations between total strangers.

value.Name: Teach For China UIUC Chapter
value.Description: Teach For China is concerned about education issues in both America and China. TFC committed to inspire, improve and innovate educational inequity at the Urbana-Champaign community. Our mission is to recruit top leaders to teach at low-income areas to ensure all children receive a qualified and valuable education. Through the experience of our various teaching programs and volunteering events, students will not only learn to give back to the society by contributing their time and sharing their intelligence, they will also develop leadership skills and valuable personalities along the way. TFC is a window, it inspires people to discover and think about education issues; TFC is a mirror, it helps improving both the issues and individuals; TFC is a bridge, it connects like-minded leaders to change and innovate the world.
value.Summary: Raising the awareness of educational inequity in both America and China, and let the people know about Teach For China and its various programs and events.

value.Name: Teach for India UIUC Foundation
value.Description: Teach for India is an organization dedicated and striving to help every child in India receive an education. Here in the United States, we are beyond fortunate to receive the educational opportunities that we do. This foundation here at UIUC for Teach for India serves multiple purposes. In order to go about solving a problem, awareness of the problem is crucial. Through hosting seminars with guest speakers, videos, presentations, and more, we plan to raise awareness of the issue at hand. Funding is crucial and fundraising money to donate to the organization serves as a priority. We hope to do multiple fundraisers throughout the year in order to raise funds to make this happen. Any contribution, no matter the size, makes a difference at the end of the day! Lastly, we hope to introduce and train people to the opportunity of becoming a fellow with Teach for India and joining the mission directly to help make a difference.
value.Summary: Teach for India is an incredible organization designed to help every child in India receive an education. The purpose of our location at UIUC is not only to raise awareness, but fundraising, seminars, and training for those who wish to become fellows.

value.Name: Technological Frontiers Society
value.Description:
Casually known as Techfront to our members, we encourage debate and discussion about technology past, present, and future through our various social activities, especially board games and sci-fi/fantasy films and shows. Change the face of the country in Ticket to Ride, manage energy resources in Power Grid, defend your ship from intergalactic menaces in Space Alert, or perhaps all three in Chrononauts. Sing along to the Buffy the Vampire Slayer musical epsiode, enter another dimension which we call The Twilight Zone, or uncover Chess's plans to defeat The Cape. Suffer with us through the Star Wars Holiday Special, share some laughs with Tom Servo in Mystery Science Theater 3000, or try to figure out how to escape the Dark City.

Techfront strives to be an accepting, welcoming, and safe space for queer and trans people and anyone else who might be made to feel unwelcome in broader "geek culture."
value.Summary: Casually known as Techfront to our members, we encourage debate and discussion about technology past, present, and future through our various social activities, especially board games and sci-fi/fantasy films and shows.

value.Name: Thai Student Association
value.Description: The mission of the Thai Student Association is to help promote unique Thai tradition and culture. We aim to be a central resource for members of the student body and people of the Urbana-Champaign community.
value.Summary: The mission of the Thai Student Association is to help promote unique Thai tradition and culture. We aim to be a central resource for members of the student body and people of the Urbana-Champaign community.

value.Name: The Academy of African American Arts
value.ShortName: The Academy of African American Arts
value.Description: To present theatrical productions that address social issues, particularly those unique to the African-American Community.
value.Summary: To present theatrical productions that address social issues, particularly those unique to the African-American Community.

value.Name: The Art of Negotiation
value.Description:
Negotiation skill is widely used in our daily life, from group discussion to job hunting. For students from different language background, it is very important to understand how to negotiate with others in a global world. Negotiation is not only used when you try to influence others, but also a basic skill for you to get accepted. 

Our organization is aimed at encouraging students to express their ideas, to get themselves more involved in groups, and to make their own voice heard by others. 

Tentative events include negotiation games, mock debates, and workshops on negotiating and networking skills.
value.Summary: The important skill of negotiation is practiced via negotiation games and mock debates. We aim to better understand different language and cultural through their different ways of negotiation.

value.Name: The Arts Initiative
value.Summary: To offer a helping hand to arts programs in our local communities in hopes of ultimately promoting, supporting, and spreading awareness about the importance of a healthy arts education in America's public school systems.

value.Name: The Association of Biological Anthropologists at UIUC
value.Description: To provide a forum to discuss new and classic biological anthropology publications, to invite speakers from within the diverse field of Biological Anthropology, to attend Anthropological conferences, and to perform public outreach.
value.Summary: To provide a forum to discuss new and classic biological anthropology publications, to invite speakers from within the diverse field of Biological Anthropology, to attend Anthropological conferences, and to perform public outreach.

value.Name: The Baha'i Association at the University of Illinois
value.Description:
Baha'is believe that humanity is one single race and the formation of a spiritually conscious global society is now present. The Baha'is at the University of Illinois are dedicated to breaking down barriers of race, class, creed, and nation, through a promotion of healthy dialogue that supports:

 

  • the abandonment of all forms of prejudice and discrimination
  • equality between men and women
  • unity among religions
  • the elimination of extremes of poverty and wealth
  • the establishment of a global commonwealth of nations
  • harmony between religious and scientific knowledge
value.Summary: The Baha'i Association is designed to bring together people of all faiths at the UIUC and to try and practice the beliefs that Baha'is follow.

value.Name: The Chief's Airsoft Platoon
value.Description:
Airsoft Club/Team at the U of I. We use small-unit tactics while gaining leadership and organizational skills in a less-than lethal combat setting.

We frequent both local skirmishes at Saltfork Paintball, and large events such as MAG and CAA sanctioned scenarios.

CollegiateLink is somewhat unwieldy, so keep up with our Facebook page instead. If you need to contact us, either post or message on Facebook.
value.Summary: Airsoft Club/Team at the U of I.  We use small-unit tactics while gaining leadership and organizational skills in a less-than lethal combat setting.

value.Name: The Collective Magazine
value.Summary: We are an arts and humanities publication for students to collaborate and showcase their best creative work/skills. The Collective Magazine serves as a platform for creative UIUC students to meet, work, and network with other passionate students.

value.Name: The Dollar Club
value.Description:
Dollar Club

As college students, we are by no means wealthy. Even so, $1 is easy to come by. That $1 that might not mean much to you or I could be used to help buy a meal for a hungry person in our community. This RSO is focused on helping needy people in our community by meeting a financial need that they may have (i.e. buying food, clothes, etc). By doing this, we aim to build relationships with those less fortunate and be a friend to them as well. Many of the homeless people in Champaign-Urbana are ignored by most of the population. People pretend they are invisible and just walk right past. This is dehumanizing and cruel. My goal is to let these people know that they are cared about and valued as people, and we want to show them this through the investment of small, individual monetary contributions pooled together to buy something they have a need for as well as the investment of time and being a friend in any way we can.

We want to build relationships with those less fortunate in our community, which requires more than just a one time “good deed.” To facilitate this, members of this RSO will try and buy a meal for and spend time with the same person on a weekly basis in teams of around 5. While some would argue that more people would be helped if we focused on more people for a smaller amount of time, we value really getting to know one person over just buying a meal for someone one time and never seeing them again.   As our group grows, this will allow us to reach more and more people.

This RSO will also participate in various fundraisers going toward various causes. One of these fundraisers will be take place next fall to buy warm winter coats for those who cannot afford them. As needs become evident, fundraisers will be held to meet those needs. These can have broad targets (like buying as many coats as possible and distributing them/donating them) or more narrow targets (like meeting a specific need i.e. taking 1 family grocery shopping).

This RSO would like to volunteer periodically in homeless shelters in Champaign-Urbana as well as with the Salvation Army.

This RSO’s primary focus is on needy people in Champaign-Urbana, but is not limited to this. We also have an interest in working with Misericordia, a home for children and adults with disabilities located in Chicago. Some of our group members have loved ones that are very involved with Misericordia, and we would like to be involved in assisting that organization as a secondary goal.
value.Summary: The Dollar Club is a group of students who are willing to give a little time and $1 a week to help the homeless population here in Champaign.  The dollar goes toward taking a homeless person out to lunch, which we will do as a group.

value.Name: The DREAM Studio
value.Description: The D.R.E.A.M. Studio (Developing Real Expression Around Music) is a mentorship program that pairs University students with local high school students. The program centers around developing positive self-expression and a sense of community among the high school students. Throughout the semester the students will learn about themselves and the music and media around them. They will create a song, record it and perform it during a showcase at the end of the semester.
value.Summary: A mentorship program that pairs University students with local high school students to develop positive self-expression, self-discovery and community through original music creation and performance.

value.Name: The Exclusive Ladies Illuminating Talent Elegantly Majorettes Team
value.Description: E.L.I.T.E. would like to create an environment at home games where everyone can be engaged with the overall atmosphere (i.e., game, music, and dance). E.L.I.T.E. wants to help the women on campus carry out their passion for dancing as well as change the way students feel about attending games. We will also dance at campus events and competitions. We will also participate in the campus shows.

value.Summary: The Family Law Society facilities a connection between professionals and law students interested in family law. The society aims to bring family law professionals, including judges and attorneys, to the Champaign-Urbana campus to speak with students.

value.Name: The Fashion Network
value.Description:
The Fashion Network is an organization where one can foster creativity and connect with individuals who share the same interests. Every meeting, this club will explore all aspects of the fashion industry as well as create projects to implement on campus (i.e. a fashion show).

 With opportunities to network as well as pursue resume-boosting projects, this club is for all students who want to pursue a career in the fashion or luxury lifestyle industry.

We will be having designers give us insight, professionals teach us and let our imagination roam free. 

Join today to become an Illinois Fashionista!

value.Name: The Flow Arts
value.Description:
The Flow Arts aims to create a space where students can come together and practice/perfect different types of flow arts, such as Gloving, Hooping, Poi, etc. This is will be a judge free zone, accepting any newcomer to the art forms and assisting them in learning new forms of expression as well as practicing and training together in a group rather than on their own.

We also aim to break the stigma of drug use with these art forms, and to spread awareness of the #glovingisnotacrime trend as well as other movements within the community.
value.Summary: The Flow Arts is a space where students can come together and practice/perfect different types of flow arts/dances, such as Gloving, Hooping, Poi, etc.  This is a judge free zone that accepts any newcomer and helps them learn the arts

value.Name: The Golden Z Club at the University of Illinois
value.Description: The Golden Z Club at the University of Illinois is our chapter of a global organization known as Zonta International. Zonta International is comprised of individuals, who through service and advocacy, work together to advance the status of women worldwide. Zonta Clubs are present in 63 countries and have a membership base of over 30,000 volunteers. Individual collegiate branches of Zonta International are known as Golden Z-Clubs. The Golden Z Club at the University of Illinois is sponsored and supported by a professional branch of Zonta International located in Lincoln, IL. The Golden Z Club’s purpose on campus, in the surrounding community, and globally is to help, support, and encourage women.
value.Summary: An organization dedicated to advancing the status of women both locally and internationally through service and advocacy.

value.Name: The Helping Illini
value.Description: The Helping Illini seek to create positive impacts in the community surrounding and supporting the university. Through community outreach, cooperation with other student organizations, fundraising, and volunteering, we believe that we can help make a difference in the community.
value.Summary: The Helping Illini seek to make a positive impact in the Champaign-Urbana community through planning, fundraising, and completing various service projects throughout the year. We invite you to join our philanthropy / service / volunteering opportunities.

value.Name: The Ill Harmonic
value.Description: The Ill Harmonic is a 13-member, all-male a capella group. Our thirteen members are Shaun Chung, David Dahowski, Dean Gozum, Dillon Gozum, Mike Ovassapian,  Josh Graham, Nathan Dimaano, Jangho Seo, Christian Siki, Lee Biedermann, Brett Cohen, Issac Ruthe, and Micah Bernas. We're the fastest expanding group on campus, gaining nationwide recognition in our participation in the ICCAs and the various other competitions.
value.Summary: The Ill Harmonic is a 13 member all-male A Capella Group from the University of Illinois! We're expanding fast, gaining nationwide recognition in our participation in the ICCAs and various other competitions.

value.Name: The Illini Paintball Club
value.Description:
The Illini Paintball Club is a group that was formed with the intention of growing the sport of paintball on the Illinois campus by providing a fun, laid back atmosphere for playing. Players from all skill levels and styles of play are welcome (experience of the five founding members ranges from 5+ years of play and refereeing to no experience at all). No equipment is required but players are welcome to bring their own gear if they have it. The main trips will be to Saltfork Paintball which is a 15 minute drive from the main quad, although farther trips to larger fields can be arranged. We will also be setting up carpools to ensure that everyone can get to and from the fields for every game so if you don't have a car it's no problem. 

P.S.

If the group shows enough interest I am all for starting an NCPA team and hosting tryouts so we can compete against other colleges.
value.Summary: We are a club dedicated to growing the sport of paintball on the Illinois campus by providing a casual atmosphere for playing. Anyone interested is welcome to join-- no experience is required!

value.Name: The Illini Swing Society

We love swing dancing! And we want you to come find out how much fun it is.

We promote the education and enjoyment of the various swing era dance styles in Champaign-Urbana. We hold dances, organize workshops and offer lessons teaching East Coast Swing, Lindy Hop, Charleston, Balboa, and more. Where dancers from all over join us in a weekend of fun and dancing.

We love new people, and will be MORE than happy to dance with you! Come check us out, and find out why so many people love to swing dance.
value.Summary: We're the Swing Society at The University of Illinois, a group of students and community members of Champaign and Urbana, Illinois interested in Swing-era dances such as Lindy Hop, Charleston, and more!

By hosting career panels, inviting speakers, and reaching out to local organizations that help immigrants in the Champaign-Urbana area, we hope to give students a resource to turn to and experience in this changing area of law.
value.Summary: The Immigration Law Society (ILS) strives to promote discussion of immigration law and policy issues that are currently impacting the United States.

Welcome to Theta Tau, the world's oldest engineering fraternity.

Re-activated by a group of Unversity of Illinois students in 2005 following a 50 year hiatus, Theta Tau's Kappa Chapter once saw membership from notable U of I alums such as William Grainger and Arnold Beckman.

Our mission is to continue Theta Tau's long tradition of professional development coupled with meaningful community service and excellence in academics; the new Kappa Theta Tau seeks out the best and brightest men and women in the field of engineering.

value.Name: Those Impacted by the Mass incarceration Era Scholars
value.Description: TIME Scholars is a registered student organization at UIUC, which aims to support formerly-incarcerated individuals, persons holding felony convictions, as well as the friends and family of those effected by the mass-incarceration era.  We work towards reducing the stigma associated with having a criminal conviction, and assisting those who have made mistakes to feel welcome in the University community.  Discussion and forums pertaining to the mass-incarceration epidemic, prison re-entry, the school-to-prison pipeline, and prison privatization will grant us the proper knowledge to intellectually insert ourselves into this conversations on a higher level, while putting us in the position to affect social change in Champaign-Urbana, and beyond.
value.Summary: TIME scholars is a collective of social justice minded individuals who have been impacted by the mass-incarceration epidemic.  Whether you are formerly-incarcerated, carrying a felony conviction, or have friends or family who are or have been,  join us.

value.Name: Transcendental Meditation® Club at UIUC
value.Description:
The Transcendental Meditation® technique is practiced by students and educators from all around the world. Our club would like to connect with our fellow practitioners and enjoy lively discussions and social activities.

 

We want to work together to invite other students to learn about the benefits that we have gained from our daily TM practice.

 

We want to explore the wide range of research on the technique and invite guest speakers so that we can advance our intellectual understanding. TM and the brain and physiology, heart health, psychology, and general well-being are just a few of the topics we hope to learn about together.
value.Summary: The purpose of the Transcendental Meditation® Club is for members to gather socially and discuss the benefits of the TM technique. The club will host guest speakers and invite visiting scientists and other experts to give talks about the latest research

value.Name: Transportation and Development Institute Graduate Student Organization
value.Description:
The ASCE-T&DI GSO of the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign is a Graduate Student Organization affiliated with the Transportation and Development Institute of the American Society of Civil Engineers. The GSO is established with the main purpose of strengthening the professional and extracurricular development of graduate students in transportation engineering specific to the following:

  1. Professional Development – through the organization of seminars, technical trips, and related activities with the purpose of providing opportunities for information exchange regarding current transportation research and practice issues;
  2. Intra-university Outreach – by increasing awareness of variety of subjects within transportation engineering for current and prospective graduate students and by fostering the engagement and collaboration of transportation engineering graduate students in University activities; and
  3. Community Outreach – by promoting awareness of transportation engineering in the Urbana-Champaign community through informative events and by contributing to the betterment of the Urbana-Champaign community, reaching beyond the university with volunteer work that meet societal needs from an engineering perspective.
value.Summary: The ASCE-T&DI GSO is a Graduate Student Organization affiliated with the Transportation and Development Institute of the American Society of Civil Engineers. We welcome all with interests in the transportation field.

value.Name: Triangle Fraternity
value.Description: The purpose of Triangle shall be to maintain a fraternity of engineers, architects, and scientists. It shall carry out its purpose by establishing chapters that develop balanced men who cultivated high moral character, foster lifelong friendships, and live their lives with integrity.
value.Summary: Triangle is a social fraternity whose purpose is to develop balanced men in the fields of Engineering, Architecture, and Science by providing an environment which fosters personal growth and professional success.

value.Name: Try Everything Club
value.Description:
The objective of this club is to encourage people to share their interests/passions, to broaden their horizons and to learn from others. We aim to keep an open, friendly and casual atmosphere. This way people will experience the fun in trying/learning new things, yet escape the academic pressures of a more formal education. 

Members of the club will be given the opportunity to hold their own personal 'workshops', teaching a skill or subject of their choice to a small audience. These are left very open ended, so individuals can come up with creative ways to convey their enthusiasm. Sessions can thus be held at various locations, using various (accessible) tools. Club members shouldn't feel that they need significant expertise to hold a workshop - these are meant to be fun and informal. 

We will also provide ample opportunity for regular members to make friends and feel part of a close-knit community.
value.Summary: Members will hold personal 'workshops' teaching skills/subjects that they are interested in or passionate about. This will encourage people to learn from each other, broaden their interests and pick up new skills in a casual, informal setting.

value.Name: Turkish Student Association
value.Description: Our goal is to unite the considerable number of Turkish students at UIUC and those enthusiastic in learning about Turkey under the same roof.  Scheduled events include an annual dinner on the Republic Day of Turkey, screenings of acclaimed Turkish movies, picnics/outings, and exhibitions, among others.
value.Summary: Our mission is to create an interactive environment for Turkish students at Urbana-Champaign, as well as those interested in learning about Turkey and Turkish culture.

value.Name: Turning Point USA
value.Description: Turning Point USA educates students about the importance of fiscal responsibility, free markets, and limited government. Through non-partisan debate, dialogue, and discussion, Turning Point USA believes that every young person can be enlightened to true free market values. TPUSA activists strive to: Educate students about the importance of fiscal responsibility, limited government, and free markets. With innovative messaging techniques and strategic outreach methods TPUSA is able to educate thousands of college students each day. Identify student activists in every corner of the country who believe in limited government and individual liberty. TPUSA activists are the community organizers of the right. Register students to vote. TPUSA has helped thousands of college students apply for voter registration and access vote-by-mail ballots. Empower young activists to get involved in the fight for free markets and limited government. Through building strong campus networks, organizing conferences and training workshops, and equipping activists with the knowledge and strategies needed to combat the left, TPUSA empowers young people to make a difference within their own campus and community. Organize young activists in chapters and networks on colleges across the country. TPUSA believes there is strength in organization, and our activists work tirelessly to build grassroots networks on every college campus in America. Mobilize students who believe in free markets. Email lists don’t mean anything if they aren’t used properly. TPUSA mobilizes its activist networks to get involved in activism, issue-advocacy, public policy education, and grassroots organization.
value.Summary: Turning Point USA educates students about the importance of fiscal responsibility, free markets, and limited government.

value.Name: Twin City Bible Church
value.Description:
Our mission:

Campus and community transformed by Christ to renew the world.

 

As we pursue this mission, we are driven by these Core Values:

We value biblical teaching and preaching.

We take the "Bible" in our name seriously because we believe God's key means of revelation is through his Word. We grow as disciples and we help others grow as disciples of Christ as we seek God together through his Word and help one another live out his Word.

We value campus and community together in life and ministry.

Because of our university setting, God gives TCBC a unique opportunity to have a wonderful mix of college students and community people. Rather than simply having a ministry to students, we desire to bring the generations together. As community people and students have opportunities to do life and ministry with one another, we believe God will use TCBC for widespread impact.

We value equipping and sending.

Because we minister in a transient community, God gives us the opportunity to serve the worldwide Church as an equipping and sending station. We want to invest in the development of people who are part of TCBC even for just a few years and then send them on to what God has next for them. We also desire to equip every person to live daily as "sent ones"—effective ambassadors for Christ in our sphere of influence.

We value meaningful relationships.

We want every person to have an opportunity to develop genuine relational connections with others at TCBC. Our desire is to be a church in which we truly love one another and practice the "one another"s of Scripture.

We value clarity on the essentials in a culture of grace.

God brings people to TCBC from a wide variety of backgrounds.We want to pursue Christ-centered unity through an approach that "majors on the majors" while cultivating a culture of grace in areas where godly people have differing perspectives. We desire to listen to and learn from one another.
value.Summary: A local church seeking to bring the campus and community together to make a difference in the world for God and His purposes.

value.Name: Tzu Chi Collegiate Association
value.Description:
"Tzu Chi" are Chinese characters which mean compassionate relief. Our organization aspires and works to relieve all of those in need.

"Tzu Ching" means youths with compassion and joyous giving, who abide to Tzu Chi principles and spirits to extend and carry out Tzu Chi missions on campus. 

Tzu Chi's four major missions:
1. Charity 
2. Medicine 
3. Education 
4. Humanity 

The main mission of Tzu Chi Collegiate Association (TCCA) is to introduce Tzu Chi to more young adults and encourage students of all ethnic groups to learn and to care for others while developing a noble character and a sound mind.

At UIUC, TCCA holds regular volunteering activities at a nursing home (Meadowbrook Health Center) and a children shelter (Crisis Nursery). Once every semester, we organize a large fundraising activity to benefit programs by Tzu Chi. One example of this program is the Power of Five program, which benefits children in South Africa, Haiti and the US, and the homeless in the US (www.thepower5.org). TCCA provides a unique volunteering environment because we consider every member as part of a big family. Approximately once a month we will have a family gathering where we share and discuss life lessons and enjoy good food together.

Please visit our website at https://sites.google.com/site/uiuctcca/ for more details
value.Summary:
We are a volunteer-based organization to introduce Tzu Chi to young adults and encourage students of all ethnicity to learn and care for others.

Please visit our website at https://sites.google.com/site/uiuctcca/ for more details

value.Name: UIUC Students for Betsy Dirksen Londrigan
value.Description: Betsy Dirksen Londrigan declared her candidacy for Illinois' 13th Congressional District in July. She is running as a Democrat in effort to unseat incumbent Congressman Rodney Davis. Students for Betsy will help mobilize and organize student support for Londrigan at the University of Illinois. The organization will meet on a bi-weekly basis (once every 2 weeks). There will be multiple opportunities for student involvement in the campaign, from getting petition signatures, to registering students, to attending/holding support events, to effectively learning how to represent the campaign, to getting students to the polls on election day. The organization will exist for at least this semester and the next, ideally through the fall semester of 2018, as we intend to do everything we can in order to ensure that Betsy Dirksen Londrigan is the Democratic nominee. Students will be able to stay in contact with the organization's president/members on a more regular basis than the biweekly meetings via Facebook group. The organization will serve to support Londrigan's campaign at the University of Illinois; however, the process will yield invaluable connections and experiences for its participating students along the way.
value.Summary: Students for Betsy seeks to more effectively organize and mobilize student support for Betsy Dirksen Londrigan, Democratic candidate for Congress in Illinois' 13th District. We will work together in 2018 to deliver IL-13 the representation it deserves.

value.Name: UniPlace Community Service
value.Description: The goal of this organization is to reach out help those in need. The UniPlace Christian Church Community Dinner has been ongoing for four years, providing a free meal to anyone, no exceptions, every Wednesday during the school semesters. The RSO wishes to expand upon this dinner to further ensure basic necessities for community members and students. Providing food is the first step to better helping those who are in need of basic human resources. The members and leadership will volunteer their time to help serve and enable the mission of this RSO.
value.Summary: Providing basic resources and services to those in need within the Champaign-Urbana area through UniPlace Christian Church.

value.Name: Unite Our Campus
value.Description: At Unite Our Campus, we believe in the power of intercultural dialogue. Join us as we plan and implement an annual convention where participants engage with keynote speakers, enjoy cultural foods and participate in small group discussions. Help us create a stronger campus community.
value.Summary: Promote dialogue, foster community, learn about the cultures around you.

value.Name: United Against Inequities in Disease
value.Description: We aim to provide volunteer opportunities that increase awareness and mobilize students regarding infectious diseases and health disparities through hosted events and collaboration with community partners.
value.Summary: United Against Inequities in Disease is a nonprofit, student-run organization that strives to promote advocacy for health inequities by providing testing, counseling, and awareness initiatives to at-risk populations.

value.Name: United Church of Christ Campus Ministry
value.ShortName: United Church of Christ Campus Ministry
value.Description: Our purpose is to explore and grow in our faith, reach out to others, and experience fellowship in the spirit of God's love.
value.Summary: Our purpose is to explore and grow in our faith, reach out to others, and experience fellowship in the spirit of God's love.

value.Name: United Greek Council
value.Description: Governing body for culturally-based fraternities and sororities
value.Summary: The Governing body for culturally-based fraternities and sororities.

value.Name: United Illini for a United Campus
value.Description:
Mission: Working together for a better U of I. Breaking down the barriers that divide us. We call for fostering a safe, inclusive, united campus for all students.
- Create relationships with campus wide organizations,
- Cosponsor events with other groups promoting unity
- Making tangible changes in student life
- Reaching every student at the University of Illinois

Vision: United Illini for a United Campus calls for fostering a safe, inclusive, united environment at the University of Illinois that stands with all students regardless of their race, religion, ethnicity, sexual orientation, gender identity, and political ideology. We seek to break down barriers that divide us and bring students together around common goals. We are united for inclusion, united for diversity, united for our university.
value.Summary: Working together for a better U of I. Breaking down the barriers that divide us. We call for fostering a safe, inclusive, united campus for all students.

value.Name: United Minority Relief, UIUC
value.Summary: United Muslim Relief is a not-for-profit organization that brings those living under extreme harsh conditions to ease through fundraising. Everyone, regardless of race and religion has a right to a sustainable livelihood.

value.Name: United Muslim and Minority Advocates
value.Description: The University of Illinois, Urbana-Champaign chapter of the United Muslims and Minority Advocates (UMMA) is primarily an outreach and interfaith student organization. Our mission is to build a community that addresses political, global, and sociocultural issues and promotes a comprehensive understanding of the world around us. Through constructive dialogue and activism, we strive to establish an attitude of inclusivity on campus, while also building strong partnerships with other student organizations advocating mutual interests.
value.Summary: The United Muslim and Minority Advocates (UMMA) is primarily an outreach and interfaith student organization. Our mission is to build a community that addresses political, global, and sociocultural issues.

value.Name: Unseen: Christian A Cappella
value.Summary: Unseen: Christian A Cappella serves to create a place to have praise, growth, fellowship and fun through singing, Come join us sing Christan music, mash-ups, and a variety of genres as well

value.Name: Up With Life Walk for Suicide Prevention and Awareness
value.Description: Up With Life is a suicide prevention and awareness walk that originated in the town of Cambridge, Illinois in 2012. The walk is currently expanding to different locations, including the University of Illinois campus. Up With Life is most active on Campus during September, which is suicide prevention month, but efforts are made all year round to spread awareness about the cause.
value.Summary: Up With Life is a 5k walk dedicated to spreading awareness about suicide. Every life is worth living, and our mission is not only to save lives, but to educate others about mental illness & suicide prevention.

value.Name: uPoint
value.Summary: Transforming personal development into community growth.

value.Name: Urban Health Program at Urbana-Champaign
value.Description: The mission of the University of Illinois at Chicago’s Urban Health Program is to recruit, retain, and graduate underrepresented racial/ethnic minority students, specifically African Americans, Latinos, and Native Americans, in the health professions, and to expand educational opportunities for these populations at the pre-college (K-12), undergraduate, graduate, and professional levels.
value.Summary: To recruit, retain, and graduate underrepresented racial/ethnic minority students. Part of UIC College of Nursing located on the Urbana-Champaign campus.

value.Name: Urbana Champaign Books to Prisoners
value.Description:
UC Books to Prisoners is an Urbana Illinois based project providing books to Illinois inmates at no cost by mail as well as through two county jail libraries which we operate.

We are a community-powered volunteer organization with a number of easy ways for you to get involved. No experience is required and whether you have an hour a month or would like to volunteer more often, you are invited to to work with us.

Our volunteers interact with inmates by reading their letters, selecting books from our collection of donated materials and sending books to inmates in response to their requests. We also staff the two lending libraries located in the Champaign, IL County jails.  If you would prefer to work behind the scenes, we can also utilize your unique skills managing volunteers, coordinating book donations and fund raising, as well as many other education & outreach as well as technical tasks.
value.Summary: UC Books to Prisoners is an Urbana Illinois based project providing books to Illinois inmates at no cost by mail as well as through two county jail libraries which we operate. We have volunteering sessions during which you can come work with us.

value.Name: Urbana Country Dancers
value.Description:
Join us for FUN energetic dances with great live string-band music on a beautiful sprung-wood floor. All dances are taught by our callers. Experienced dancers will welcome you and other new dancers. No partner or experience is necessary. Contra Dancing is the American descendant of English Country Dancing and has figures similar to those from square dancing (swing, do-si-do, etc).

Bring an additional pair of clean, soft-soled shoes to protect the floor. Please refrain from wearing perfume or cologne. Admission fee pays for our callers, bands, and dance hall. Be sure to arrive in time for our 7:30pm New Dancer Orientation.

For more information and updates about dances, workshops, musician jams, pre-dance potluck dinners, and special events, sashay to our website: http://urbana-contra.org/
value.Summary: Join us for FUN energetic dances with great live string-band music on a beautiful sprung-wood floor!

value.Name: Urbana-Champaign West African Dance and Drum Collective
value.Summary: This organization promotes and celebrates West African performing arts, cultures, and history -- providing instruction and performances in drumming and dance.

value.Name: Vanilla Illini
value.Description:
Our primary goal is to help international students especially the Chinese students, get more involved in the campus community.

We will bring PhD students or even faculty memebers from various fields of study together and share ideas via talks and discussions. We will also address some practical and important issues related to campus life of international students, especially the Chinese undergraduate and graduate students.

Our team is and will be compact in size and will be organized in a modern and American style. We will not be affiliated to any political regimes.
value.Summary: Our goal is to help international students especially the Chinese students, get more involved in the campus life. Our team is and will be compact and organized in a modern and American style. We will not be affiliated to any political regimes.

value.Name: Varsity Men's Glee Club at the University of Illinois
value.Description: Founded in 1886, the Varsity Men's Glee Club at the University of Illinois is the only all-male ensemble at the university. VMGC is unique at UIUC in that it is not only the oldest Registered Student Organization on campus, but also an integral part of School of Music's Choral Division.  Recently, VMGC celebrated 125 years of musical excellence.  VMGC consists of both undergraduate and graduate students of all majors who are united as brothers in song, and the group offers a unique musical experience with its combined spiritual and secular repertoire and a commitment to service and comradery.
value.Summary: Founded in 1886, the Varsity Men's Glee Club at the University of Illinois is the only all-male ensemble at the university, and the oldest RSO on campus.

value.Name: Vedanta Study Circle
value.Description:
Vedanta is one of the world’s most ancient religious philosophies and one of the broadest. Vedanta affirms the oneness of existence, the divinity of the soul, and the harmony of religions. The idea of harmony of religions is expressed in one of the earliest Vedantic texts — ekam sat viprā bahudhā vadanti (“Truth is one, sages call it by var­i­ous names”) (Rig Veda). Vedanta is the philosophical foundation of Hinduism; but while Hinduism includes aspects of Indian culture, Vedanta is universal in its application and is equally relevant to all countries, all cultures, and all religious backgrounds.

At Vedanta Study Circle, we are dedicated to learn, understand and practice Vedanta as taught by Swami Vivekananda, one of the foremost Vedantins of modern times. A Vedantin can profess any religion. He/she can be a Hindu or a christian or a Muslim or a Jew or a Buddhist or a Sikh or a Jain or can even be an atheist. So, VSC is open to everyone irrespective of their race, nationality, gender, religion etc.

Activities
Our primary activity is a weekly study meeting, where we read, discuss, debate and understand Vedanta. This is the first step in practicing Vedanta.

Find up-to-date details about our activities on our facebook page https://www.facebook.com/illini.vedanta/

We will also have a few 'outreach events' topics will be of interest to broader student community. These talks will be given by invited speakers including Swami Ishatmananda.


Vivekananda
Swami Vivekananda is the first Hindu Monk and preacher in the west. He represented Hinduism at the Parliament of Religions, held as part of the World's Columbian Exposition in Chicago in 1893, where he was an instant success. Subsequently he was invited to speak all over America and Europe. He was a man with a great spiritual presence and tremendous intellect.

He strove to promote peace and human brotherhood on the spiritual foundation of the Vedantic Oneness of existence. A mystic of the highest order, Vivekananda had a direct and intuitive experience of Reality. He derived his ideas from that unfailing source of wisdom and often presented them in the soul-stirring language of poetry. The natural tendency of Vivekananda's mind, was to soar above the world and forget itself in contemplation of the Absolute. But another part of his personality bled at the sight of human suffering. He chose, in obedience to a higher call, service to man as his mission.
value.Summary: Vedanta Study Circle (VSC) is a forum to study, discuss, understand and practice Vedanta. Vedanta is an ancient religious philosophy from India that deals with questions such as nature of soul, of universe and God, and the relation between these.

value.Name: Velocity Dance
value.Description: Velocity is dance team that aims to expose the University community to a variety of dance styles, and expand the understanding and appreciation of all dance forms, including modern, jazz, hip hop, lyrical, tap, ballet, and more. In addition, Velocity Dance capitalizes on the vastly different dance backgrounds and training of its members to blend dance styles and create innovative and unique pieces for the enjoyment of the community. Velocity Dance members strive to explore the multiplicity of different dance styles intertwined into a single composition.
value.Summary: Velocity dance aims to expose the University community to a variety of  dance styles, and expand the understanding and appreciation of all dance  forms, including modern, jazz, hip hop, lyrical, tap, ballet, and more. (Auditions in Fall semester)

value.Name: Venture Capital Association
value.Summary: VCA has a mission of preparing students for a career in venture capital through an educational lecture series, research projects, collaboration with student-led startups, and networking opportunities with our partner venture capital firms.

value.Name: Venturing
value.Description:
How will you "Lead the Adventure"?

Venturing is an inclusive program through the Boy Scouts of America for males and females aged 14-21. You'll acquire life skills and gain experiences that will prove to be valuable regardless of where your future takes you, all while having a blast: leadership, event-planning, organization, communication, responsibility -- the list goes on!

The Venturing program emphasizes four main areas:

  • Adventure - Mentoring, leading, and participating in crew-led adventures.
  • Leadership - Ongoing leadership development through training, mentoring, and hands-on leadership.
  • Personal Growth - Goal-setting in support of personal growth.
  • Service - Leading and participating in community service.


The Venturing program aims to enable young adults to:

  • Experience a program that is fun and full of challenge and adventure.
  • Acquire skills in the area of their crew's specialty.
  • Become a skilled training and program resource for other youth groups.
  • Experience positive leadership from adult and youth leaders and be given opportunities to take on leadership roles.
  • Learn to make ethical choices throughout their lives by instilling the values of the Scout Oath and Law.
  • Have a chance to learn and grow in a supportive, caring, and fun environment.
value.Summary: Venturing is an inclusive program through the Boy Scouts of America for males and females who are interested in adventure, leadership, personal growth, and service. Our crew focuses on high-adventure outings, both close to campus and far away.

value.Name: Veritas Forum at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign
value.Description:
How can we mend a broken world? How should we seek justice? What is the good life?

The Veritas Forum helps students and faculty ask life's hardest questions. Many of the world's leading universities were founded to answer the big "why" questions. Our mission is to help them confront these questions anew. The first Veritas Forum was planned by students, faculty and chaplains at Harvard University in 1992. Since then, over 200 universities in North America and Europe have hosted over 2,000 Forums.

The Veritas Forum is committed to courageous conversations. We place the historic Christian faith in dialogue with other beliefs and invite participants from all backgrounds to pursue Truth together.

The Veritas Forum at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign Registered Student Organization hosts speakers from the Veritas Forum and facilitates their open dialogue with campus.
value.Summary: Supporting the mission of Veritas Forum to confront life's hardest questions anew and place the historic Christian faith in dialogue with other beliefs in order to pursue Truth together.

value.Name: Veterinary Medicine Aquatics Club
value.Description: Aquatics club is a branch of IAAAM (Internanational association for aquatic animal medicine). We take care of the fresh and saltwater tanks at the Union and the Veterinary school. Primarily, we work to further educate students and the public on aquatic species husbandry, conservation, and ecosystems. We hold lunch lectures and wet labs at the veterinary school, and do an annual behind the scenes tour of the Shedd Aquarium and their medical clinic.
value.Summary: Aquatics club is University of Illinois College of Veterinary Medicine's branch of IAAAM (Internanational association for aquatic animal medicine).

value.Name: VEX U: Cyber Chiefs
value.Description: This team represents the University of Illinois as we design and build two robots from scratch to compete in VEX U, the collegiate division of the VEX Robotics Competition.  The team redesigns the robots each year to tackle the new game, and the robots must be constructed using VEX-brand or VEX-approved parts.  In February, the team competes in a VEX U Regional Tournament at Purdue, and in April, the team travels to Lousiville, KY, to compete in the VEX U World Championship, competing against teams from other universities around the world.
value.Summary: This team represents the University of Illinois as we design and build two robots from scratch to compete in VEX U, the collegiate division of the VEX Robotics Competition.

value.Name: Vietnamese Investigative Bible Exploration
value.Summary: To be a community the Vietnamese people can come and learn and share about the person of Jesus Christ.

value.Name: Vietnamese Student Association
value.Description: Our purpose is to offer many opportunities for students to learn about the Vietnamese culture, traditions, and customs on campus. Additionally, we strive to create opportunities for members to get involved in the community.
value.Summary: Our purpose is to offer many opportunities for students to learn about the Vietnamese culture, traditions, and customs on campus. Additionally, we strive to create opportunities for members to get involved in the community.

value.Name: Vintage Analog Manual Photographers
value.Description:
VAMP (Vintage Analog Manual Photographers) is open to all photography lovers and to those who love learning on a film camera, whether it be a SLR, TLR, toy camera, view camera, etc.

Our focus is on film, and the art and balance in capturing the beauty in every crumb of time. We love sharing ideas and resources, the aesthetics and the philosophy - about film, about photography.

Along with photo adventures, workshops, darkroom experiments, guest speakers, and other opportunities, we work together to produce quality exhibits in Champaign-Urbana. Grow with us.
value.Summary: VAMP is open to all photography lovers and to those who love learning on a film camera, whether it be a SLR, TLR, toy camera, view camera, etc. We focus on sharing film photography resources and producing exhibitions to showcase our members' artworks.

value.Name: Vis-A-Vis Tutoring
value.Description: To provide an opportunity for students to tutor children one-on-one or serve as a classroom aide in the local Champaign-Urbana elementary, middle, and high schools.
value.Summary: A volunteer tutoring organization at the University of Illinois, a student program of the University YMCA.

value.Name: Visual Impact
value.Description: This is a service club with an artistic focus. Visual Impact is strongly devoted to helping the community through an artistic outlet, as well as developing young artists in the process. This club is open to all majors. Whether it is creating murals throughout the downtown area, doing art workshops with youth in elementary schools, doing projects with people in nursing homes or with special needs, engaging in graphic design requests of restaurants or other businesses in the Champaign-Urbana community, giving private art lessons to youth, or mentoring young adults with an artistic career inquiry, Visual Impact is sure to make a impact on the Champaign-Urbana community in a visual way. Art is something that really brings people joy when done together. This club is going to keep this communities art scene thriving, as well as give university students an outlet to engage with others in the community to spread their passions.
value.Summary: A service club with an artistic focus. Visual Impact is strongly devoted to helping the community through an artistic outlet, as well as developing young artists in the process. This club is open to all majors.

value.Name: Vitality Dance Team
value.Description: Vitality Dance Team is a team for students interested in continuing to dance throughout their college career.  We are a non-competitive organization who is committed to providing a fun, relaxed, and non-stressful way to dance on campus.  We have various opportunities to perform throughout the school year on campus at primarily Greek-sponsered events but also other events that come our way.  We dance all kinds of different styles, have members of all ages, and many Greek and non-Greek members.
value.Summary: To provide a fun, non-competitive opportunity for students to continue dancing and performing at campus events, primarily greek-sponsored programs.

value.Name: Volunteer Illini Projects, Inc
value.Description: To promote peace, unity, and change through service on campus and in the Champaign-Urbana community
value.Summary: To promote peace, unity, and change through service on campus and in the Champaign-Urbana community

value.Name: Water Environment Federation-American Water Works Association
value.Description:
Water Environment Federation-American Water Works Association (WEF-AWWA) at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign offers students interested in water resources engineering and water/waste water quality an opportunity to learn about and get involved with current issues facing the water world today. Our mission is to get involved within these fields through going on company tours to firms within the water industry as well as taking waste water treatment plant visits. Our greatest focus is on the regional and national student design competitions. We feel it is important to apply the concepts we learn in our courses to real world issues in order to practice the critical thinking skills demanded by industry. The organization is open to all levels of students and it is a great way to prepare to be the professional engineers we aspire to become

In the fall semester we look to enhance our professional development skills and knowledge about the water industry through attending conferences, going on office and plant tours, and bringing in professionals from the water industry as guest speakers at our meetings. The spring semester (and the end of the fall semester) we mainly work on our student design competition. Additionally in the spring, we participate in E-Week, Engineering Open House, and the Boneyard Creek Clean Up.

The best way to find more information about WEF-AWWA is through our website but we update our events primarily through our Facebook page! Check us out at the links below!

https://publish.illinois.edu/wef-awwa-uiuc/

https://www.facebook.com/wefawwauiuc/
value.Summary: WEF-AWWA at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign offers students interested in water resources engineering and water/waste water quality an opportunity to learn about and get involved with current issues facing the water world today.

value.Name: Wesley Food Pantry
value.Description:
The purpose of this organization is to help the Wesley Evening Food pantry
meet its goal of providing assistance to those in need of food in the community.  Members of this RSO will help by coordinating student volunteer groups, volunteering as individuals and raising funds.
value.Summary: The purpose of this organization is to help the Wesley Evening Food pantry meet its goal of providing assistance to those in need of food in the community.  Members will help by coordinating student volunteer groups, volunteering, and raising funds.

value.Name: Whine and Cheese Club
value.Description: The Whine and Cheese Club is an organization in which students from all backgrounds can connect in their shared desire to vent out, whine, or complain about any issues. These issues can be big or small, affecting their lives or others, and so forth. All members are encouraged to participate and talk about any issue. However, all information shared during the meeting is confidential. Furthermore, the club promotes social justice as well as spreads awareness of current issues to members through its meetings. Flavored vitamin water, cheese, and crackers would be served at every meeting.
value.Summary: The Whine and Cheese Club is where students can freely discuss  problems affecting their lives or others. No matter how big or how small the issue, you are free to whine, complain, or grumble. Simple snacks and drinks would be served at every meeting.

value.Name: Wildlife Society, Illinois Student Chapter
value.Description:
Please see our Facebook group page for the most up to date information about our activities: https://www.facebook.com/groups/TheWildlifeSocietyUIUC/

We represent the TWS Student Chapter at UIUC, a subchapter of the international organization dedicated to inspiring, empowering, and enabling wildlife professionals to sustain wildlife populations and habitats through science-based management and conservation.
value.Summary: We are the TWS Student Chapter at UIUC, a subchapter of the international organization dedicated to inspiring, empowering, and enabling wildlife professionals to sustain wildlife populations and habitats through science-based management and conservation.

value.Name: Wishmakers at UIUC
value.Description:
We grant the wishes of children with life-threatening medical conditions to enrich the human experience with hope, strength, and joy.

 

Contact Natalia at wojnwsk2@illinois.edu.
value.Summary:
"The Make-A-Wish Foundation of Illinois grants wishes to children with life-threatening medical conditions to enrich their lives with hope, strength and joy."

Wishmakers raise money for the Make a Wish Foundation through various fundraisers on campus!

value.Name: Wolves of Green Street
value.Description: We will begin the year by fundraising. Once we reach our fundraising goal we will invest the money in the stock market. Throughout the year we will research various stocks to find those most likely to increase in value, and then vote on which ones to invest in. Near the end of the year we will liquidate our positions and donate all the money to a charity, also chosen by our members.
value.Summary: Fund-raise, invest, donate: these are the three simple steps in our mission to give back, while teaching students valuable skills of managing and investing money.

value.Name: Women in Business Society
value.Description:
The purpose of the Women in Business Society (WIB) is to provide a platform for aspiring business leaders to inspire, educate, and support one another. Our mission is to offer the opportunity to network, learn, and equip each other with the necessary connections, knowledge, and tools to be successful.

Our club hosts events like the MBA Women’s Conference, networking receptions, charity auctions, picnics, and wine & cheese nights to foster a strong sense of community. Our vision for WIB is to provide a rich resource pool for support and guidance through mentorship, workshops, and informal sessions with recruiters, alumnae, and successful business leaders.

By partnering with the faculty, administration, the MBAA, and other student led organizations, we aim to raise awareness among current and prospective students about women’s experience in the business world. We are committed to developing club initiatives that are relevant, exciting, and informative, and we encourage membership from all students.
value.Summary: To support women's leadership and their future careers in the MBA program.

value.Name: Women in Computer Science
value.Description: Women in Computer Science is a non-profit, educational, service organization dedicated to supporting the efforts of young women who are considering pursuit of a career in computer science or show an overall interest in computers. Because of the number of women pursuing Computer Science has been steadily decreasing, this organization aims to retain and provide a network of support for members to rely on for advice and camaraderie.
value.Summary: Women in Computer Science is a non-profit, educational, service organization dedicated to supporting the efforts of young women who are considering pursuit of a career in computer science or show an overall interest in computers.

value.Name: Women in Electrical and Computer Engineering
value.Description: To support and encourage women in Electrical and Computer Engineering.
value.Summary: To support and encourage women in Electrical and Computer Engineering.

value.Name: Women in Science
value.Description:
This organization is open to anyone and hopes to promote equal opportunity for women and men that enter scientific professions. Our goal is to create a supportive community in professional, academic, and social settings, in addition to raising awareness of the barriers many women face in these settings and how to overcome those barriers. We will coordinate activities with other organizations that share our goals.

Please feel free to contact any of the officers, we are very friendly and would love to answer any questions!
value.Summary: Our organization strives to form a community for anyone, particularly women, to foster their growth in the sciences. This includes professional and academic events to increase skills, as well as social events!

value.Name: Women of Color
value.Description:
The purpose of Women of Color is to educate, uplift, and unite minority women on the University of Illinois campus and in the greater Champaign-Urbana community.

 

Contact us:

email: wocuiuc@gmail.com

Twitter: @woc_uiuc

Instagram: @woc_uiuc
value.Summary: The purpose of Women of Color is to educate, uplift, and unite minority women on the University of Illinois campus and in the greater Champaign-Urbana community.

value.Name: Women of Pride
value.Description: Women of Pride is a student group made for queer women and their allies as a safe place to gather. We informally educate the campus community of cultural, political, and other social issues related to lesbians, bisexual women, and transgender people. One of our goals is to foster a sense of community among queer women and out allies. We do this by gathering weekly for discussions, workshops, and events on or off campus.
value.Summary: Women of Pride is student group made for queer women and their allies as a safe place to gather. We informally educate the campus community of issues related to lesbians, bisexual women, and transgender people.

value.Name: Women Who Read
value.Description: Women Who Read was founded on August 4th, 2015 by Jordan Conklin and Brianne Lang. The organization was founded on the core belief that women, particularly those with a clear passion for working in the business world, should take the time to educate themselves on what knowledge, skills, and attributes are needed to succeed and promote positive change for all women within the industry. Our goal is to not only provide business-minded women with the opportunity to learn about the professional world through our carefully chosen readings, corresponding book talks, and networking events, but to also instill in these ambitious women the desire to share what they have acquired with other women throughout their entire lives. We will give girls/women who may not have the resources and support that they need to flourish in society the opportunity to do so through our humble charity work. As an organization, we will empower women who work and show others how to do the same.
value.Summary: Women Who Read is an organization that strives to educate women who work in the business world on what is required to succeed within the particular industry through carefully chosen readings, corresponding books talks, and networking events.

value.Name: Women4Outreach
value.Description:
Purpose of W4O:

To develop, strengthen, and unify university women through service, leadership, and mentorship by making a positive and personal impact on the women in the surrounding community.

Mission of W4O:

W4O seeks to empower and enlighten women of all ages through all stages of womanhood by community service, mentorship, and workshops. W4O is an initiative that strives to produce change that will better the lives of women in our community. We are committed to excellence in leadership, education, and awareness. We are ambassadors with a heart to serve.
value.Summary: Women4Outreach is a group of female students dedicated to develop, strengthen, and unify university women through service, leadership, and mentorship by making a positive and personal impact on the women in the Champaign-Urbana community.

value.Name: Womens Ultimate Frisbee
value.Description: Womens Ultimate Frisbee is an organization that promotes athleticism and teamwork in women from this University. We encourage our teammates to dedicate time to improving themselves as athletes and in the process, improving the team. We also help women to learn how to balance their studies and extracurriculars, as dedication to any endeavour is key to success. We foster friendships and support, on and off the field. We're teammates, but most of all, we're family.
value.Summary: Womens Ultimate Frisbee is a club that promotes athleticism and teamwork in women from this University. We foster friendships and support, on and off the field. We're teammates, but most of all, we're family.

value.Name: Wrapsody Dance Co.
value.Description: The mission of Wrapsody Dance Company is to provide unlimited learning opportunities to women, men, and children who have the desire to express themselves through movement and to present a source of entertainment that embodies and celebrates the beauty of the human body and its many ways of moving.
value.Summary: “To watch us dance is to hear our hearts speak.”

value.Name: Writers Organizing Realistic Dialect
value.Description: Writers Organizing Realistic Dialect (W.O.R.D.) mission is to promote, engage, and publicize the artistic side of the performer. With this organization, we want artists to know the reason and depth behind their craft. We also want to expose such artist and the community on how essential the writing aspect of performing is. We wish to provide the artists with the privilege to perform their craft to the Champaign-Urbana Community.
value.Summary: Writers Organizing Realistic Dialect (W.O.R.D.) mission is to promote, engage, and publicize the artistic side of the performer. With this organization, we want artists to know the reason and depth behind their craft. We also want to expose such artist

value.Name: Wushu Club
value.Description:
Wushu Club is a University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign RSO that focuses on teaching students Wushu or Chinese Martial Arts. Wushu can be considered one of the most demanding forms of martial arts due to its tremendous focus on aesthetics and grace. As a member of the Wushu Club, students will have the opportunity to learn basic techniques, stances, acrobatic jumping techniques, and bare-hand and weapon forms. Wushu Club has performed for CSSA's Moon Gala, PSA's FACT, AAA's Fashion Show, Northwestern's Celebrasia, Illini Men's and Women's Basketball half-time and much much more; our students are given the opportunity to perform at such venues. Wushu is an excellent way to stay in shape, build character, and meet new people. Wushu Club is fortunate to have several instructors who have competed at many national and international competitions and have performed at venues across the Chicago-land area. 
 
All are welcome to join us and learn, no experience necessary. We meet every Monday, Wenesday and Thursay from 8-10p at the Amory track grounds. 
 
http://youtu.be/1lOEUCv_nDU
value.Summary: Wushu is a Chinese martial arts and means "military arts" when translated literally. At Wushu Club students learn basic techniques, stances, acrobatic jumps, and bare-hand and weapon forms. All are welcome to join Wushu Club, no experience necessary!

value.Name: XdEA
value.Description: XdEA, pronounced “idea”, is a dance team that focuses on learning East Asian pop dances (e.g. C-pop, J-pop, and K-pop dances). XdEA strives to educate its members and others about contemporary East Asian pop dance cultures through dance performances. XdEA uses their practices, performances, and other activities to create fun places for UIUC community members to connect with others interested in East Asia and grow their knowledge of East Asian pop cultures while they nurture and develop their dance skills.

value.Name: YesPlus- UIUC Chapter
value.Description: Operating in 152 countries, The Art of Living Foundation (AOLF) is a non-profit, educational and humanitarian organization founded in 1981 by the world-renown philanthropist and spiritual leader Sri Sri Ravi Shankar. All of AOLF’s programs are guided by Sri Sri’s philosophy: “Unless we have a stress-free mind and a violence-free society, we cannot achieve world peace.” The AOLF community is diverse and attracts people from all walks of life backgrounds and religious orientations.
value.Summary: AOL UIUC offers programs, which include breathing techniques, meditation, yoga, and practical wisdom for daily living to facilitate elimination of stress and foster deep and profound inner peace, happiness and well-being for all individuals.

value.Name: Young Americans for Liberty
value.Description:
In general, we work to promote the ideas of economic and social liberty, in that we oppose any sort of authoritative body, whether it be the school administration or the government, stepping-in to tell you how to live your life.

Along these lines, some of our past events include:

  • A drinking laws protest, complete with root beer kegger, on the quad
  • A protest/awareness event concerning the Patriot Act
  • An anti-drug war event with free brownies given out of cooking pots (pot brownies)
  • A protest of the TSA
  • A showing of Busted: A Citizen's Guide to Surviving Police Encounters to educate students on their rights when dealing with police
  • Several anti-war events
  • A national debt & overspending awareness event
  • An extensively publicized protest on the smoking ban
  • And many, many more

We hold weekly meetings where we plan events and have discussions on diverse topics and how the principles of liberty are involved. We have held forums on foreign policy, gun control, healthcare, higher education, and many other topics.

If you're interested in getting involved, check out our social media pages and contact information.
value.Summary: YAL at UIUC seeks to recruit, educate, and mobilize students in the ideals of liberty. Our work is a part of a global student movement. Our objective is to facilitate its success.

value.Name: Zeta Phi Beta Sorority, Inc. Nu Delta Chapter
value.ShortName: Zeta Phi Beta Sorority, Inc. Nu Delta Chapter
value.Description: Zeta Phi Beta Sorority, Inc. was founded January 16, 1920 on the Campus of Howard University in Washington D.C. The social organization was founded by 5 "Pearls" on the principles of Scholarship, Service, Sisterly Love, and Finer Womanhood. The Nu Delta Chapter was nationally chartered on the campus of University of Illinois Urbana Champaign April 15, 1972 by 10 daring young ladies. Embodying the legacy established by its founders the chapter remains "A community conscious, action oriented organization"

value.Name: Zindaa UIUC
value.Description: Zindaa is a Bollywood & hip-hop fusion dance team at UIUC. Our name means "alive" in Hindi, and feeling alive and having fun is what we believe dance is all about. We are a diverse, non-competitive team that performs at both cultural and charity events. It's all the fun without the big time commitment. The best part about Zindaa is the people--you'll truly become a part of the family! Get in touch with us at zindaauiuc@gmail.com!
